<P1>(b) the resulting Judgment in favour of the Plaintiffs, inclusive of pre-judgment interest and after the apportionment of liability, was $2,625,640.00;</P1>
<P1>(c) Justice McLean erred in law in granting an assignment of future accident benefits payable to the Plaintiff, Barbara Carroll, where there was no allocation by the jury of the future care costs and instead only a global assessment;</P1>
<P1>(d) Justice McLean erred in fact and law in failing to appreciate and/or apply the proper test for the assignment of collateral benefits;</P1>
<P1>(e) Justice McLean erred in fact and law in failing to provide any comparison or matching of the jury verdict to the accident benefits for which the assignment was sought;</P1>
<P1>(f) Justice McLean erred in fact and law in finding that the Defendants' actuary had done a &ldquo;matching&rdquo; analysis when her role was restricted to a mathematical exercise of calculating the value of the offers to settle and future accident benefits;</P1>
<P1>(g) Justice McLean erred in law in granting an assignment of accident benefits without requiring the Defendants to fully compensate the Plaintiffs;</P1>
<P1>(h) Justice McLean erred in law in prohibiting the Plaintiffs from claiming under the bankruptcy of the Defendants, Robert and Caroline McEwen, for any shortfall in satisfaction of the resulting Judgment;</P1>
<P1>(i) Justice McLean exceeded his jurisdiction by extinguishing the Plaintiffs' rights under the bankruptcy of the Defendants, Robert and Caroline McEwen;</P1>
<P1>(j) Justice McLean erred in fact and law in failing to consider, or even mention, an offer to settle of the Plaintiffs as against the Defendants, Robert and Caroline McEwen, which the Defendants ought to have accepted as it was significantly lower (approximately $1,625,000 lower) than the ultimate jury award and it would have permitted those Defendants to have settled the action within their insurance limits;</P1>
<P1>(k) Justice McLean erred in law in failing to consider the costs implications of the Defendants, Robert and Caroline McEwen, remaining in the action when the Plaintiffs offered to settle within insurance limits in circumstances where there was no question that the $1,000,000 insurance limits of the Defendants, Robert and Caroline McEwen, would be exhausted;</P1>
<P1>(l) Justice McLean erred in fact and in law in failing to appropriately consider that the Plaintiffs were successful in obtaining a jury verdict which exceeded both the Plaintiffs' offer to settle against the Defendants, Robert and Caroline McEwen and also the Plaintiffs' joint offer to settle against both Defendants;</P1>
<P1>(m) Justice McLean failed to consider and/or apply Rule 49.13 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> with respect to offers to settle made by the Plaintiffs;</P1>
<P1>(n) Justice McLean erred in law in determining that the insurance limits of the Defendants were relevant to the issue of costs particularly when the Defendants refused to pay their insurance limits to settle the action despite receiving offers to settle within insurance limits;</P1>
<P1>(o) Justice McLean erred in law in failing to put any weight on the numerous offers to settle of the Plaintiffs which provided clear and convincing evidence that the sole reason this action proceeded to trial was due to the Defendants' conduct in refusing to accept reasonable settlement offers which were exceeded by the Jury Verdict;</P1>
<P1>(p) Justice McLean erred in fact and law in suggesting that the Jury Verdict exceeding the Plaintiffs' offers (as well as the offers of the Defendants) was insufficient as the margin of success was not &ldquo;substantially&rdquo; over the offers to settle;</P1>
<P1>(q) Justice McLean erred in fact and law in considering incorrect values for accident benefits prior to trial which even the Defendant's own expert admitted were in error;</P1>
<P1>(r) Justice McLean erred in fact and law in failing to consider or even summarize the arguments raised by the Plaintiffs with respect to costs and erred in stating that the Plaintiffs argued that &ldquo;these offers were exceeded by the jury verdict by approximately $2,600,000.00&rdquo; which was never the position of the Plaintiff nor is it logistically possible unless the Plaintiffs had offered to settle for &lt;nil&gt;;</P1>
<P1>(s) Justice McLean erred in fact and law in failing to appropriately consider and value the offers to settle exchanged between the parties;</P1>
<P1>(t) Justice McLean erred in fact and law in failing to consider that the Defendant's offer to settle (which resulted in the failed settlement) expressly stated that the offer was for &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo; and did not state that it included either the bad faith claims which the Defendants knew was going to be the subject of a subsequent legal action nor did it state that it included past accident benefits;</P1>
<P1>(u) Justice McLean erred in fact and in law in inconsistently interpreting the Defendants' offers to settle as including the bad faith action and past accident benefits for the purposes of criticizing the conduct of Plaintiffs' counsel with respect to the failed settlement but <UNDER>not</UNDER> including any valuation of those claims for the purposes of assessing costs;</P1>
<P1>(v) Justice McLean erred in fact and law in failing to consider that the Defendants' offers included the additional claims (bad faith and past accident benefits) despite finding it was apparently &ldquo;without doubt&rdquo; that these offers included the other claims and the Defendants took the position that they would <UNDER>not</UNDER> settle without release of those other claims;</P1>
<P1>(w) Justice McLean erred in law in failing to consider that the Defendants ought to have proceeded with the failed settlement as the Plaintiffs obtained a more favourable jury verdict even without consideration of the value of past accident benefits or the bad faith claims which remain outstanding;</P1>
<P1>(x) Justice McLean erred in fact and law by characterizing the offer to settle of the Defendants of $1.75M offer as a &ldquo;Rule 49 offer&rdquo; when it was admitted by the Defendants that acceptance of this offer included a release of claims outside the scope of the within action (i.e. bad faith claims and past accident benefits);</P1>
<P1>(y) Justice McLean erred in fact and law in reducing the Plaintiffs' entitlement to costs due to the late service of expert reports while completely ignoring the fact that both parties served expert reports outside of the case management timetable, including one expert report of the Defendants which was served in the middle of trial and after the Plaintiffs' expert had already testified; and</P1>
<P1>(z) such further and other ground as Counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:</BOLD>
<P1>(a) sections 6(1)(b) and s.133 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>;</P1>
<P1>(b) Rule 61.03.01(17) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>;</P1>
<P1>(c) the Order of Justice McLean is a final Order; and</P1>
<P1>(d) such farther and other basis as Counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P1></P>
