<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">NOTICE OF CROSS-APPEAL OF THE DEFENDANTS ROBERT MCEWEN AND CAROLINE MCEWEN</TI>
<P><BOLD>THE RESPONDENTS, ROBERT MCEWEN AND CAROLINE MCEWEN CROSS-APPEAL</BOLD> in this appeal and asks that the judgment/Order of the Honourable Mr. Justice McLean dated May 19, 2016 be varied as follows:
<P1>1. An Order setting aside the costs Order of the Trial Judge dated May 19, 2016;</P1>
<P1>2. An Order that the Defendants be awarded their costs of the action;</P1>
<P1>3. In the alternative, an Order that there be no order as to costs with respect to the trial of this matter; and</P1>
<P1>4. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court deems just.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS FOR THIS CROSS-APPEAL</BOLD> are as follows:
<P1>1. The Trial Judge properly found that the Defendants were entitled to an assignment of future accident benefits. However, the Trial Judge erred in law and failed to properly consider the value of the assignment in an assessment of the value of the offers to settle made by the Defendants;</P1>
<P1>2. The Trial Judge appreciated that the value of the Defendants' offers to settle, including an all-inclusive settlement offer of $2,150,000.00, with no assignment of future accident benefits, dated September 11, 2015 rendered the trial of slight benefit to the Plaintiffs. The Trial Judge erred in law in the exercise of his discre tion when he awarded $375,000.00 in costs to the Plaintiffs;</P1>
<P1>3. The Trial Judge failed to apply the appropriate sanction for what had been discussed as &ldquo;sharp practice&rdquo; with respect to the Appellants' acceptance of the $2,150,000.00 offer dated September 11, 2015 and the immediate issuance of a new action against the Respondent Aviva Canada Inc. claiming $2,000,000.00 in damages, a tactic that the Trial Judge accurately described as &ldquo;a trick&rdquo;; and</P1>
<P1>4. The Trial Judge correctly held that the Appellants gave &ldquo;lip service&rdquo; to the Order of the Case Management Master dated May 26, 2014. The Case Management Order required service of all expert reports 90 days in advance of the pre-trial on June 17, 2015. Instead, the Plaintiffs served a report, dated August 18, 2015, containing a new plan for the Plaintiff Barbara Carroll's future care, even though they had advised the Defendants prior to the pre-trial that Barbara Carroll's future care needs had not changed. The Trial Judge erred in law in the exercise of his discretion when he failed to apply the appropriate sanction for this and other aspects of the conduct of counsel for the Plaintiffs in his award of $375,000.00 in costs to the Plaintiffs.</P1></P>
<P>DATE: June 29, 2016</P>
