<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;NATURE OF THE APPEAL</TI>
<P>1. The Plaintiff Barbara Carroll appeals the Judgment of the Honourable Justice McLean, dated October 30, 2015, following an eight (8) week trial with a jury at Ottawa, Ontario.</P>
<P>2. The Plaintiffs received Judgment in the amount of $2,610,774.32, together with $375,000 in costs. It further provided for an assignment of future statutory accident benefits <UNDER>upon payment of the Judgment</UNDER>. To-date, the Defendants have not paid the Judgment and have only paid their insurance limits of $2,000,000 (plus accrued interest on that amount). No amount has been paid on costs.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;OVERVIEW STATEMENT</TI>
<P>3. On March 28, 2009, Barbara Carroll, then a pedestrian, sustained a catastrophic brain injury when she was struck by a motor vehicle owned by the Defendant Caroline McEwen and operated by the Defendant Robert McEwen (&ldquo;the McEwens&rdquo;).</P>
<P>4. Barbara Carroll commenced this action to recover damages for her personal injuries sustained in the accident. She named as defendants in the action, in addition to the McEwens, the Pilot Insurance Company (&ldquo;Pilot&rdquo;) and Aviva Canada Limited (&ldquo;Aviva&rdquo;) as her OPCF 44 (Family Protection Endorsement) insurers. The Family Protection Endorsement contained insurance limits of $2,000,000. The McEwens held liability coverage with Aviva with a limit of $1,000,000.</P>
<P>5. The jury, at the conclusion of a lengthy hard fought trial assessed the Plaintiffs damages at $4,083,000 and split liability 62/38 in the Plaintiffs' favour. The resulting Judgment amount of $2,610,774.32 was broken down as follows:
<P1>(a) Barbara Lynn Carroll
<P2>General damages of $186,000 plus prejudgment interest of $58,512.50</P2></P1>
<P1>(b) Shannon Luknowsky
<P2>General damages of $43,400 plus prejudgment interest of $13,652.92</P2></P1>
<P1>(c) Jeffrey Carroll
<P2>General damages of $43,400.00 plus prejudgment interest of $13,652.92</P2></P1>
<P1>(d) The Estate of Lome Carroll
<P2>General damages of $15,332.60 plus prejudgment interest of $4,823.38</P2></P1>
<P1>(e) Barbara Lynn Carroll
<P2>For the cost of future care $2,232,000</P2></P1></P>
<P>6. Following receipt of the jury verdict, McLean J entertained further evidence and heard submissions on, <EM>inter alia</EM>, the following issues:
<P1>(a) assignment of benefits under the <EM>Statutory Accident Benefits Schedule</EM> (the &ldquo;SABS&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>(b) the effect of the McEwen bankruptcy on the McEwen's personal liability; and</P1>
<P1>(c) costs.</P1></P>
<P>6. McLean J determined as follows:
<P1>(a) upon payment of the full amount of the Judgment, Barbara Carroll is ordered to assign future accident benefits (attendant care and medical and rehabilitation benefits) to which the Plaintiff is entitled to receive after the Judgment is paid;</P1>
<P1>(b) Judgment was rendered for the full amount ($2,610,774.32) but the personal liability of the McEwens was limited to the insurance limits of $1,000,000;</P1>
<P1>(c) no determination was made regarding any claims which could be made in the bankruptcy;</P1>
<P1>(d) Pilot/Aviva were found liable for an additional $1,000,000 under the OPCF 44; and</P1>
<P1>(e) the Plaintiffs' request for costs (including disbursements) was reduced by more than 50% from a bill of costs of $795,616.09, on a partial indemnity basis, down to $375,000 to punish the Plaintiffs for alleged wrongdoings.</P1></P>
<P>7. The within appeal is limited to two issues:
<P1>(i) the assignment of future accident benefits; and</P1>
<P1>(ii) costs.</P1></P>
<P>8. On the issue of the assignment of accident benefits, the Plaintiffs respectfully submit that the learned trial judge erred in law in granting the assignment in circumstances where the Judgment had not been paid in full and the jury's lump sum assessment did not allow the court to match the award of future care costs to the particular accident benefits that might be received in the future</P>
<P>9. With respect to deductibility and assignment of collateral benefits, the issue before this five&mdash;member panel is to determine the law generally applicable to all litigants in motor vehicle litigation. An interpretation of the legislation that enables parties to litigate only issues actually in dispute (and then match the damages to collateral sources) is preferable to an interpretation that would require injured plaintiffs to sue for <UNDER>all</UNDER> past and future damages even if those damages are fully compensated by collateral sources. Litigants should be encouraged to act reasonably and not waste judicial time and resources to prove <UNDER>each and every</UNDER> claim for the sole purpose of avoiding unfair deductions and/or assignments.</P>
<P>10. On the matter of costs, the Plaintiffs respectfully submit that McLean J fell into serious error in sanctioning Plaintiffs' counsel for conduct that His Honour characterized as a &ldquo;trick&rdquo; by reducing the Plaintiffs' reasonable partial indemnity costs request by over 50% (a penalty of more than $400,000). His Honour erred in penalizing the Plaintiffs for accepting an offer to se ttle &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo; which the Defendants alleged, <UNDER>only after acceptance</UNDER>, had implied terms including claims outside of &ldquo;this proceeding.&rdquo; Any misunderstanding resulting from the Defendants' conduct in failing to identify implied terms in an offer to settle should be borne solely upon them. This was particularly alarming as there was another offer, using the same wording to settle &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo; that was still open for acceptance which the Defendants maintained had Rule 49 costs consequences. It was only during a mid-trial motion proceeding before Hackland J that it was discovered that both offers had implied terms which required release of claims which fell outside of the proceeding. The deceptive practice of having implied terms in offers to settle th at purport to have costs consequences is not reasonable nor appropriate. There may have been a &ldquo;trick&rdquo; being played, but the &ldquo;trick&rdquo; was not perpetrated by the Plaintiffs.</P>
<P>11. Furthermore, McLean J fell into palpable and overriding error in:
<P1>(a) failing to give any weight to Offers to Settle made by the Plaintiffs which were in amounts considerably less than the Judgment amount;</P1>
<P1>(b) penalizing the Plaintiffs for the Defendants seeking leave at the outset of trial for an examination for discovery of the Plaintiff Barbara Carroll; and</P1>
<P1>(c) penalizing the Plaintiffs for non-compliance with the case management time line for service of expert reports in circumstances where both parties failed to meet the time line.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>i.</N><TI>BACKGROUND</TI>
<P>12. Barbara Carroll was a pedestrian who was struck by the Defendant, Robert McEwen, while driving a vehicle owned by Caroline McEwen. Barbara Carroll sustained catastrophic injuries, including a brain injury. She was insured by Pilot Insurance (now Aviva Insurance) under the Family Protection Endorsement OPCF44.</P>
<P>13. The Plaintiffs were successful in achieving a jury award of $4,083,000. After reduction for contributory negligence, Judgment was rendered against the Defendants in the amount of $2,610,774.32, exclusive of costs and post-Judgment interest.
<P1>Jury Verdict, dated October 30, 2015; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 24, pp. 145-146.</P1>
<P1>Judgme nt of Justice McLean, October 30, 2015; Appeal Book and Co mpendium, Tab 3, pp.13&ndash;16.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>ii.</N><TI>ASSIGNMENT OF ACCIDENT BENEFITS</TI>
<P>14. The Defendants drafted questions to the jury which lumped all future care into one question for &ldquo;future care costs&rdquo;. The question posed and the answer given by the jury is as follows:
<QUOTE><P><EM>What is your assessment of the Plaintiff Barbara Carroll's future care costs as a result of the injuries sustained in the March 28, 2009 accident?</EM></P>
<P><EM>Answer:</EM> <UNDER><EM>$3,600,000</EM></UNDER></P></QUOTE>
<P1>Jury Verdict, dated October 30, 2015; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 24, p. 145-146.</P1>
<P1>Defendants' Proposed Jury Questions and Authorities Brief, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 25, p. 147&mdash;150.</P1></P>
<P>15. At trial, the Plaintiffs' claims for future cost of care were detailed by individual items claimed, their annual cost and the present value factor. The jury was also provided with the tools to calculate the present value of items for differing periods of time depending upon the length of time the jury determined the item(s) would be payable.
<P1>Present Value Chart of Gary Principe; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 62, pp.572&ndash;575.</P1></P>
<P>16. The Defendants did not ask the jury to divide the damages into particular items of future care nor did they ask the jury to determine the future care costs by benefit categories contained in the <EM>SABS</EM>. This is despite the fact that the evidence at trial divided the needs in a manner consistent with proper matching of the jury award to benefits available. Under the <EM>SABS</EM>, medical and rehabilitation benefits are covered by a separate limit of insurance than attendant care benefits.
<P1>Jury Verdict, dated October 30, 2015; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 24, p. 145-146.</P1>
<P1>O. Reg 403/96: SABS, s. 1 9.</P1>
<P1>Future Care Chart, Trial Exhibit #10, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 63.</P1></P>
<P>17. Arguments were made by the Plaintiffs after trial that the issue of an assignment of benefits was moot or premature as the Defendants had not paid the Judgment as required by the legislation. The trial judge accepted that the Judgment may not be paid but nonetheless concluded that the argument advanced by the Plaintiffs was &ldquo;not persuasive&rdquo; as &ldquo;the Plaintiffs were well aware of this situation before trial commenced and were well aware of the risks of litigation.&rdquo; McLean J's reasoning was unresponsive to the Plaintiffs' argument.
<P1>Judgment of Justice McLean, October 30, 2015; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 3, p.5, para 8 and 30.</P1></P>
<P>18. The trial judge ordered that once the Defendants pay the full amount of the Judgment (plus interest and costs), Barbara Carroll will then be required to assign to Aviva/Pilot all payments that Barbara Carroll is entitled to receive, after the Judgment has been paid, for SABS in respect of medical and rehabilitation benefits and attendant care benefits. No determination was made by the trial judge matching the jury award to particular benefits-payable to Barbara Carroll under the SABS.
<P1>Judgment of Justice McLean, October 30, 2015; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 3, pp.13&ndash;16.</P1>
<P1>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 4, pp.17&ndash;34.</P1></P>
<P>19. The trial judge determined that Ms. Larouche, the Defendant's actuary, &ldquo;provided substantial evidence with regard to the nature of the future care plan and indirectly its matching with the jury's award.&rdquo; This is not correct. After trial, Ms. Larouche provided evidence on the present value of accident benefits as of September 8, 2015 as well as a calculation comparing the total value of the jury award to settlement offers exchanged prior to trial. Neither her affidavit material, nor her report, attempts any sort of matching between the jury award and the SABS. It was an analysis made purely for cost purposes to compare the ultimate Judgment to a series of offers to settle.
<P1>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean at para 7; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 4, pp.20-21.</P1>
<P1>Report of Maryse Larouche, February 5, 2016, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 61, p.558&ndash;571.</P1>
<P1>Affidavit of Maryse Larouche, February 9, 2016; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 45, p.305&ndash;309.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>iii.</N><TI>COSTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>(a)</N><TI>Attempted settlement of &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo;</TI>
<P>20. Prior to the calling of evidence at trial, the Plaintiffs accepted an offer of the Defendants in the amount of $2,150,000 inclusive of costs. The offer was drafted by the Defendants with the style of cause in the within court file and read as follows:
<QUOTE><P>The Defendants offer to settle this <UNDER>proceeding</UNDER> on the following terms:</P>
<P>Payment by the Defendants to the Plaintiffs the sum of $2,150,000 inclusive of all damages, prejudgment interest and costs. [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Offer to Settle of the Defendants, September 11, 2015, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 36, pp. 177&ndash;179.</P1></P>
<P>21. The wording for Rule 49 Offers to Settle is set out in Form 49A as follows:
<QUOTE><P>The (identifying party) offers to settle <UNDER>this proceeding</UNDER> (or the following claims in this proceeding) on the following terms:... [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Form 49 A, Table of Forms, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 40, p. 196.</P1></P>
<P>22. Correspondence from counsel of Pilot/Aviva stated that the joint offer to settle was made &ldquo;pursuant to the Rules&rdquo; and warned of &ldquo;costs consequences&rdquo; of the offer if not accepted.
<P1>Letter of Robert Sutherland, dated September 11, 2015, Exhibit &ldquo;U&rdquo; to the Affidavit of Elizabeth Quigley, September 14, 2015 Appeal Book and Co mpendium, Tab 41, p.197.</P1></P>
<P>23. After the Plaintiffs accepted the Defendants' offer, the Defendants took the position that the offer was not limited to this proceeding and sought to rescind the settlement on the basis that the settlement required a full and final release of:
<P1>(a) any and all bad faith claims between the Plaintiffs and Pilot/Aviva; and</P1>
<P1>(b) any past claims for SABS and only permitted &ldquo;<UNDER>future</UNDER> claims that Barbara Lynn Carroll may have with respect to a claim for Accident Benefits to her under Pilot Policy No. XXXXXXXXXX <UNDER>based on facts that do not exist as of the date hereof</UNDER>.&rdquo;[emphasis added]</P1>
<P1>Full and Final Release, Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; to the Affidavit of Stephanie Neate, sw orn September 15, 2015;</P1>
<P1>Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 42, pp. 198&ndash;201.</P1></P>
<P>24. The expansive release was demanded by the Defendants after the Plaintiffs brought bad faith litigation against Pilot/Aviva as OPCF44 and accident benefits insurer. The bad faith litigation was no surprise to anyone as the bad faith litigation was the subject-matter of letters exchanged by the parties <UNDER>prior</UNDER> to the Defendants' offer to settle. Indeed, in the correspondence string <UNDER>prior</UNDER> to any settlement being reached, the parties had debated whether or not the lawyers acting in the within proceeding would be able to represent the parties in the subsequent bad faith claim.
<P1>Letter of Kevin Nearing, dated Septe mber 7, 2015, Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo; to the Affidavit of Elizabeth Quigley,</P1>
<P1>September 14, 2015; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 46, pp. 310&ndash;313.</P1>
<P1>Letter of Joseph Obagi, dated September 7, 2015, Tab &ldquo;K&rdquo; to the Affidavit of Elizabeth Quigley, September 14, 2015; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 47, pp. 314&ndash;323.</P1>
<P1>Bad Faith Statement of Claim (Court File 15-65711), Tab 10 of Defendants' Document brief; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 48, pp. 324&ndash;335.</P1></P>
<P>25. No bad faith claims or accident benefit claims are at issue in the within proceeding. Pilot/Aviva, in its capacity as accident benefits insurer, was not a party to this action. The Defendants' expert and Plaintiffs' expert agreed that the past accident benefits release alone had a value of $50,584.
<P1>Statement of Claim, Court File No. 11-50983; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 8, pp. 43&ndash;58.</P1>
<P1>Affidavit of Gary Principe, January 29, 2016 at para 3; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 44, p. 3 02.</P1>
<P1>Affidavit of Maryse Larouche, February 9, 2016, para 8; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 45 p. 30 7.</P1></P>
<P>26. At the motion before Hackland J to enforce the settlement, issues arose with respect to the interpretation of: (a) the accepted offer; and (b) another open offer to settle of the Defendants in the amount of $ 1,757,500 plus costs (characterized by the Defendants as a &ldquo;Rule 49 offer&rdquo;). Both offers were to settle &ldquo;this proceeding.&rdquo; Plaintiffs' counsel raised the following concerns:
<QUOTE><P>[T]here is danger in allowing a defendant, who is represented by three competent counsel, making offers under Rule 49 that are silent about things. And then, when the plaintiff accepts, the claws come out. But if the plaintiff doesn't accept&mdash;it's an ingenious offer. It's an ingenious offer. They never accepted, Your Honour. Read the statement. It's &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo; only. It's a dangerous game.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Transcript before Justice Hackland, p. 5 line 6&ndash;17; p. 6 line 20-p.7 line 11; p.21, line 9&ndash;19; p.30 line 25-p.32 line 7; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 14, pp. 87&ndash;94.</P1>
<P1>Quote from Plaintiffs Submissions&mdash;Transcript before Justice Hackland p.31 line 27-p.32 line 3; Appe al Book and Compendium, Tab 14, pp 93-94.</P1>
<P1>Offer to Settle, August 27, 2014, Offers to Settle Brief Tab 7; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 34, pp. 172-175.</P1></P>
<P>27. At the motion, the Defendants took the position that all offers, including the purported &ldquo;Rule 49 offer&rdquo; required the same release (including the bad faith claims and past accident benefits).
<P1>Transcript before Justice Hackland p..54 line 17-p.55 line 23; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 15, pp. 95&ndash;97.</P1></P>
<P>28. After trial, the Defendants took the position, for costs purposes, that the $1,757,500 to settle &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo; (which impliedly included the additional claims) was a Rule 49 offer. This was the exact mischief that the motion before Justice Hackland sought to eliminate.
<P1>Submission of the Defendant, March 7, 2016 at para 3; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 47 at p.304.</P1>
<P1>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean at pa ra 26; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 4, p.2 6.</P1>
<P1>Rule 49.02(1) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</P1></P>
<P>29. The Defendants misled the trial judge by referring to comments made by Hackland J during a dialogue with counsel before he fully understood the facts. The transcripts show that Hackland J was still trying to grasp what actually occurred and admitted as follows:
<QUOTE><P>... I get it now. Sorry, I'm a bit slow. Maybe it's because I'm dealing with drug trafficking at the same time. Okay.</P>
<P>So you're saying you get a Rule 49 offer. The Rule 49 offer can only apply to the personal injury claim. So you knew from that, or you thought from that, that it must be understood that there's no release&mdash;that there's no involvement above the other action you've been talking about bringing, because it's a Rule 49 offer?</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Transcripts of Motion to enforce settlement (Hackland, J.), September 15, 2015, p.34, line 24-p.35 line 3;</P1>
<P1>Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 16, pp. 98&ndash;100.</P1></P>
<P>30. Hackland J. further stated during the hearing of the motion:
<QUOTE><P>I think a judge looking at it would probably have to say, assuming that they are looking for release to the bad-faith claim, that it probably isn't a Rule 49 offer. I got your point on that.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Transcripts of Motion to enforce settlement (Hackland J.), September 15, 2015, p. 35, line 26&ndash;32.Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 16, p.100.</P1></P>
<P>31. The motion to enforce the settlement was withdrawn and costs awarded in the cause. No reasons were delivered by the motions judge.
<P1>Order of Justice Hackland, September 15, 2015; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7, pp. 40&ndash;42.</P1>
<P1>Transcripts of Motion to enforce settlement (Hackland J.), September 15, 2015, p.57 line 5&ndash;9; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 17, pp.101-102.</P1></P>
<P>32. In his reasons delivered after trial, McLean J determined that it is &ldquo;without question&rdquo; that the offers were made on the basis of settlement of &ldquo;all matters.&rdquo; He further stated that the Plaintiffs had tried to enforce what was essentially a &ldquo;non-enforceable offer.&rdquo; McLean J concluded that, &ldquo;[t]his is not something that this Court can countenance without sanction.&rdquo;
<P1>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean at paras 13, 34, 36 and 48-49; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 4, pp. 22 and 28 and 32.</P1></P>
<P>33. In arriving at his conclusion on costs at trial, McLean J refers to and relies upon &ldquo;Reasons&rdquo; of Hackland, J in the motion. There were no &ldquo;Reasons&rdquo; and there was no decision. Once the Defendants admitted that their alleged &ldquo;Rule 49&rdquo; offer contained the implied terms, the motion was withdrawn. Hackland J explained his understanding during an appointment to settle the terms of his Order that costs of the motion were &ldquo;in the cause&rdquo;:
<QUOTE><P>...it seemed to be that there are a number of different layers of issues that were unfolded in front of me. When it started out the previous day, actually, in a case conference, when we were talking about this, and then an argument, I thought the basic issue was with respect to the, the second offer, and the acceptance, the communication that Ms. Quigley entered whether or not that was a, an acceptance of an offer that needed, that should be enforced, and, of course, the issue was this sort of, that was this good faith issue that, that has been out there. Was that caught in the settlement or was it not? And then I hear&mdash;that's what I had completely focused on. You know, then, then I hear about whether pa rties intended one or more offers to be Rule 49 offers. I think whether it's a Rule 49 offer not as a characterization of the offer the need to stand to make an offer. Whether it's a Rule 49 offer or not will depend on the criteria that is set out in the r ules and whatever judge adjudicates on it. I didn't really get into that though I heard an active debate about all so that. From my point of view, I was, I, I think I had simply put to you, Mr. Obagi, that I, I might, and I might indeed enforce your motion but I would imply on it a release provision, or we would leave it to the Court to sort out if you withdrew your motion. You decided the latter point, and I simply held out as an inducement that we just let&mdash;I could've said &ldquo;no costs&rdquo; and walked out, which I should've probably. But I said &ldquo;costs in the cause&rdquo; and walked out. So truly, I was not intended to do anything other than to put those into the pot of the rest of the costs. I wasn't intending to restrain Judge McLean. And if that results in Judge McLean hearing, you know, as, one sort of sub issue who was right or wrong in that motion I think that's, that's too bad, but I think it's probably a reality that that's a possibility. The trial judge has the overall control, doesn't he, of all the costs of t he action. [sic!]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Transcripts of Motion to settle the terms of an Order (Hackland J.), February 23, 2016, p. 13-14, lines, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 18, pp. 118-119.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>(b)</N><TI>Success in the Proceeding / Offers to Settle</TI>
<P>34. The Plaintiffs were successful in obtaining a Judgment greater than the amounts for which the Plaintiffs attempted to settle the action prior to the commencement of trial yet the trial judge gave no consideration to this success in the award of costs.</P>
<P>35. Prior to the commencement of trial, the Plaintiffs made various offers to settle, including:
<P1>(a) an offer to settle the action as against the McEwens for the amount of their insurance limit of $1,000,000. This offer was made six (6) days before the comme ncement of trial; and</P1>
<P1>(b) offers to settle against all defendants in amounts from $1,856,280 to $1,950,000 plus costs.</P1>
<P1>Offers to Settle Brief with Chart and Offers; Appeal Book and Compendium Tab 26, pp. 151&ndash;155 and Tabs 27&ndash;337.</P1></P>
<P>36. The offers made by the Plaintiffs were <UNDER>lower than</UNDER> the eventual Judgment.</P>
<P>37. The trial judge was then asked by the Defendants to consider the potential future value of accident benefits. The Judgment had not even been paid and no assignment granted. Notwi thstanding this incorrect approach to costs, the experts on behalf of both parties agreed that the Plaintiffs had beaten their offers to settle, <UNDER>even when the full present value of future SABS were taken into account</UNDER>. The Defendants' expert made the following admissions:
<P1>(a) with respect to the Plaintiffs' offer to settle for $1,000,000 with the McEwen Defendants, the offer beat the jury verdict; and</P1>
<P1>(b) with respect to the Plaintiffs' offer to settle for $1,856,280, the offer beat the jury verdict by $10,486.00 <UNDER>using all of her own assumptions and the deduction of the full present value of SABS</UNDER>. Using the Plaintiffs' expert assumptions, the Defendants' expert admitted that the Plaintiffs' offer beat the jury verdict by $170,000.</P1>
<P1>Affidavit of Gary Principe at para 8, Feb 22, 2016; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 38, p. 185.</P1>
<P1>Cross-Examination of Maryse Larouche, February 25, 2016 at Q. 1022-1023 and 1038; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 39, pp. 189-190, 193.</P1></P>
<P>38. In the Defendants previous submissions before this Honourable Court, the Defendants have attempted to refer to the inaccurate valuations of future accident benefits by their expert, <UNDER>prior</UNDER> to cross-examination, which inflates the values. In the previous factums and submissions, the Defendants have (a) referred to a document provided by Aviva (as accident benefits insurer) prior to trial regarding the valuation of benefits which all experts acknowledged was wrong; and (b) submitted that the value of benefits was somewhere between &ldquo;$760,511 and $813,748.&rdquo; The Defendants own expert admitted these numbers were wrong in cross-examination. Any attempt to use the uncorrected evidence of the Defendants' expert, Maryse Larouche, prior to corrections made in cross-examination, is entirely improper and misleading to this Honourable Court.
<P1>Cross-Examination of Maryse Larouche, February 25, 2016 at Q. 1021-1047; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 39. pp. 189&ndash;195.</P1></P>
<P>39. The trial judge did not to consider the $1,000,000.00 offer to the McEwens in his Reasons for Decision. This offer was $1,610,774.32 less than the Judgment. Defence counsel admitted on behalf of his expert that it was &ldquo;self-evident&rdquo; that this offer beats the jury verdict. It is plain and obvious that this offer ought to have been accepted by the McEwens yet the trial judge did not even refer to the offer in his determination of costs.
<P1>Cross-Examination of Maryse Larouche, February 25, 2016 at Q. 1022-1023; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 39, p. 190.</P1></P>
<P>40. With respect to the Plaintiffs' joint offers to settle, the trial judge determined that these offers were also beaten by the jury verdict. The Plaintiffs' offer to settle of $1,856,250.00 was:
<P1>(a) $754,494.32 less than the verdict; and</P1>
<P1>(b) $154,750.00 less than the insurance limits of the Defendants.</P1>
<P1>Offers to Settle Brief with Chart; Appeal Book and Compendium Tab 26, pp. 151&ndash;155.</P1>
<P1>Reasons for Decisio n of Just ice McLea n at para 45; Appeal Book and Compe nd ium, Tab 4, para 31.</P1></P>
<P>41. The Defendants <UNDER>never offered</UNDER> their insurance limits ($2,000,000) to settle this action. <UNDER>All</UNDER> of the Plaintiffs' offers were <UNDER>under</UNDER> the insurance limits. None were accepted. The Defendants have <UNDER>now paid</UNDER> their insurance limits (and not the balance of the Judgment). The Plaintiffs have now recovered more in damages than <UNDER>all</UNDER> the offers to settle.
<P1>Judgment of Justice McLean, October 30, 2015; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 3, pp.13&ndash;16.</P1>
<P1>Offers to Settle Brief with Chart; Appeal Book and Compendium Tab 26.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>(c)</N><TI>Discoveries of the Plaintiff Barbara Carroll at the outset of trial</TI>
<P>42. Barbara Carroll had a litigation guardian&mdash;her daughter Shannon. The Defendants proceeded with examination for discovery of the litigation guardian. The action was set down for trial. All parties agreed to a fixed trial date. All parties agreed that discoveries were complete. No orders were requested or made for continuing examinations for discovery. After the matter was set down for trial, new counsel for Pilot/Aviva communicated with Plaintiffs' counsel. The subject matter of those conversations were disputed. Counsel for Aviva alleged that he was told that calling Barbara Carroll at trial would not serve any useful purpose. It is agreed by all parties that no undertakin g was given not to call Barbara Carroll as a witness. This is confirmed by counsel for the Pilot/Aviva ten (10) months prior to trial (although this affidavit was only served at trial).
<P1>Affidavit of Elizabeth Quigley, sworn the 7th day of September, 2015 a t para 3-4, 7, 9&ndash;11 and 15; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 50, pp. 378&ndash;380.</P1>
<P1>Affidavit of Robert S. Sutherla nd, sworn the 20th of Nove mber, 2014 at para 10; Appeal Book and Compe ndium, Tab 51, p. 384.</P1></P>
<P>43. The Defendants objected to Barbara Carroll testifying at trial and brought a motion at the outset of trial to conduct an examination for discovery of Barbara Carroll or, in the alternative, an Order that Barbara Carroll not be permitted to testify. The trial judge refused to permit the Plaintiffs to cross-examine the counsel for Pilot/Aviva (not trial counsel) on his affidavit.
<P1>Notice of Motion of the Defendants, dated September 4, 2015; Appeal Book and Compendium Tab 52, pp 385&ndash;389.</P1>
<P1>Trial Transcripts, September 8, 2015 p.4 line 31 to p. 12 line 1&ndash;4; Appeal Book and Compendium Tab 11</P1></P>
<P>44. No evidence was advanced by any party that any discussions took place at examinations for discovery regarding whether Barbara Carroll would testify at trial. Despite this lack of evidentiary foundation, the trial judge reached following conclusions:
<QUOTE><P>Apparently, some while ago discoveries were held and it was indicated to defence counsel that Ms. Carroll would not be testifying at trial. Ms. Carroll was represented, at that t ime, by a litigation guardian, as she still is. The implication was that the litigation guardian should be examined, and really Ms. Carroll would not be helpful as a witness.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>The difficulty we have is that during the prior discoveries the indication, at least, was given to defence counsel that she would not testify, and that she really could not say anything helpful to the court. It would seem that no formal undertaking was given that she not testify. However, we have to look at the context of this litigation. [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Ruling of Justice McLean, Trial Transcripts, September 9, 2015, p. 47 line 17&ndash;27 and p. 49 line 3&ndash;10; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 12 and 13.</P1></P>
<P>45. In his costs decision, the trial judge makes a finding that the Defendants' counsel were told that Barbara Carroll &ldquo;would not be called as she could not give useful evidence.&rdquo; No such undertaking was ever given or even alleged at trial.
<P1>Reasons for Decision of Just ice McLean at para 42 and 45; Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 4, p. 29-30 and 31.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>(d)</N><TI>Expert reports</TI>
<BLOCK4><N>A.</N><TI><EM>Generally</EM></TI>
<P>46. The case conference endorsement of Master McLeod applied to <UNDER>all</UNDER> parties. The trial judge makes no mention of the late reports of the Defendants, including:
<P1>(a) the Defendants' mid-trial life expectancy report changed the life expectancy from a five year reduction to a nine year reduction based upon information available since 2012. Due to the timing, the Plaintiffs were unable to retain an expert in response;</P1>
<P1>(b) the Defendants served their first future care report only three weeks prior to the trial date (and approximately <UNDER>three years</UNDER> after the first Future Care Report of the Plaintiffs); and</P1>
<P1>(c) the Defendants did not serve any accident reconstruction reports until one month after the Plaintiffs even though the Defendants had the reverse onus to disprove negligence.</P1>
