<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ISSUES RAISED BY THE APPELLANTS</TI>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Issue"><N>#1</N><TI>The trial judge erred in awarding an assignment of accident benefits at trial</TI>
<P>50. This Honourable Court is faced with conflicting judicial decisions regarding the proper interpretation of s.267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>. The seminal decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC></CASEREF> outlines the basic principles dealing with collateral benefit legislation. The reasoning in <EM>Bannon</EM> has been applied and adopted for s.267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> in other Court of Appeal decisions, namely <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Fonseca v. Hansen</SOC></CASEREF>. It is the Plaintiffs' position that the reasoning and statutory interpretation contained in this line of cases is correct.</P>
<P>51. It is a principle of statutory interpretation that courts are to respect the intent of the Legislature as much as possible, and therefore a section of a statute should be read to comply with the legislative text, promote the legislative purpose, and produce a reasonable and just meaning. The <EM>Insurance Act</EM> and its regulations are remedial legislation and should receive such fair, large and liberal construction and interpretation as will best ensure the attainment of its objects.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC><CITE>1998 CanLII 4486</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <UNDER>at p. 29-30, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 1</UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Co-oyerators General Insurance Company</SOC><CITE>2000 CanLII 4138</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>aff'd</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>[2002] 2 SCR 129</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2002 SCC 30 (CanLII)</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 2</UNDER></P1>
<P1><UNDER>Section 64 of the Legislation Act, 2006, SO 2006, c 21, Sch F.</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>52. Generally, there are two competing interests when addressing deductibility and assignment of collateral benefits: (a) the Plaintiff should not receive double recovery; and (b) the Plaintiff should receive full compensation and not recover less than that to which he or she is entitled.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC><CITE>1998 CanLII 4486</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <UNDER>at p. 33, Appellants' Book of Authorities. Tab 1</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>53. It is also important to interpret the legislative provisions in a manner that is going to promote access to justice and proportionality. The <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC></CASEREF> principles provide flexibility to litigants to narrow the areas of disagreement for the purpose of a tort trial (particularly if a plaintiff has been fully compensated for some losses by a collateral source).</P>
<P>54. If a party has received full compensation for past loss of income from a collateral source, a statutory interpretation that <UNDER>requires</UNDER> them to advance claims for those losses to avoid a deduction or assignment relating to different claims is not an interpretation that should be favoured. It is illogical to force plaintiffs to litigate past losses simply to avoid an unfair deduction or assignment of past losses from future losses. Similarly, if a party is receiving full compensation for attendant care claims, they should not be forced to make claims for attendant care simply to avoid a deduction from medical or rehabilitation claims, covered under separate limits of insurance.</P>
<P>55. In simple cases where most medical and rehabilitation claims are paid by the collateral source, a litigant should be able to advance claims only for the portion of loss not compensated by the collateral source, such as a denied home renovation claim. Otherwise, the party would have to litigate every single claim already compensated by the collateral source to obtain recovery for the one expense which was not paid. Lawsuits that ought to be simple and straightforward will become unnecessarily lengthy and complicated for no identifiable purpose.</P>
<BLOCK3><N>i.</N><TI>Deduction of Collateral Benefits</TI>
<P>56. Section 267.8 addresses the deductions available for income loss and health care expenses. These provisions state that the amount of damages for these items should be reduced by all payments that the plaintiff received or that were available in respect of those damages. In particular, the deduction of statutory accident benefits specifically refers back to the damages awarded. For example:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>267.8</N>
<SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>In an action for loss or damage from bodily injury or death arising directly or indirectly from the use or operation of an automobile, the damages for income loss and loss of earning capacity shall be reduced by the following amounts:
<PARA><N>1.</N><PARAP>all payments in respect of the incident that the plaintiff has received or that were available before the trial of the action for statutory accident benefits in respect of <BOLD><UNDER>the</UNDER></BOLD> income loss and loss of earning capacity. (Emphasis added)</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>57. It is noteworthy that the Legislature specifically linked the benefit payments to the damages awarded. The Legislature did not state that all payments for income loss are to be deducted. The Legislature stated that all payments for <BOLD><UNDER>the</UNDER></BOLD> income loss are to be deducted. Similar wording is used in section 267(4) for health care expenses (i.e. ...in respect of <BOLD><UNDER>the</UNDER></BOLD> expenses for health care).</P>
<P>58. The intention of the Legislature was to deduct only those payments which relate to the specific damages awarded at trial. Not all income loss benefits are to be deducted from income loss damages. Similarly, not all health care benefits are to be deducted from damages awarded for health care. The benefits must relate to the particular damage award, otherwise the word &ldquo;<UNDER>the</UNDER>&rdquo; becomes superfluous.</P>
<P>59. The Supreme Court of Canada recognizes that there is a general presumption against tautology in statutory interpretation. It is presumed that the Legislature avoids superfluous or meaningless words, that it does not pointlessly repeat itself or speak in vain. Every word in a statute is presumed to make sense and to have a specific role to play in advancing the legislative purpose. The presumption carries &ldquo;considerable weight.&rdquo; It is rebuttable when it can be shown the words do not serve a function, or that the words were added for greater certainty.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>McDiarmid Lumber Ltd. v. God's Lake First Nation</SOC><CITE>[2006] 2 SCR 846</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2006 SCC 58 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>36</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Authorities. Tab 3</UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Placer Dome Canada Ltd. v. Ontario (Minister of Finance)</SOC><CITE>[2006 ] 1 SCR 7 15</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2006 SCC 20 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>45-46</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Authorities. Tab 4</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>60. The interpretation of the provision which would give meaning to the specific words used by the Legislature is consistent with the principles laid out in <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC></CASEREF>. The policy rationale is to ensure there is no duplication in a tort judgment and receipt of SABS. An &ldquo;apples to apples&rdquo; approach furthers that objective without eroding principles of full compensation to the Plaintiff.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC><CITE>1998 CanLII 4486</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> p.29, Appellant's Book of Authorities, Tab 1</P1></P>
<P>61. In <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF>, this Honourable Court held that there is a requirement that the jury's award mirror the collateral benefit such that the statutory accident benefit must be deducted from a head of damage or type of loss <UNDER>akin</UNDER> to that for which the benefits were intended to compensate. A collateral benefit which may not &ldquo;truly overlap with the sums recovered in a tort judgment&rdquo; should not be unfairly deducted from the damages.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC><CITE>[2015] OJ. No. 5573</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <UNDER>at para 43-44; Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 5</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>62. The decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF> outlines the requirement that there must be both a <UNDER>temporal</UNDER> matching (same time period) as well as a <UNDER>qualitative</UNDER> matching (compensating for the same loss).</P>
<P>63. This Honourable Court revisited this issue in the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Fonseca v. Hansen</SOC></CASEREF> and held that the damages must mirror the collateral benefit&mdash;temporally and qualitatively.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Fonseca v. Hansen</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 299 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>104&ndash;107</PARANUM></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 6</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>64. It has been stated that s. 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> is a codification of the principles of <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC></CASEREF>. The Plaintiff agrees. Unfortunately, the interpretation of that codification is at i ssue. It is the Plaintiffs's position that the Legislature specifically codifies that the deduction against a damage award must be for SABS relating to <UNDER>the</UNDER> particular income loss and <UNDER>the</UNDER> health care expense to which the damages relate. The comparison of the benefits to the damages must be made on both a <UNDER>temporal</UNDER> basis as well as a <UNDER>qualitative</UNDER> basis.</P>
<P>65. Unfortunately, confusion has arisen as courts have not given meaning to the specific wording of the provisions of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>. This Honourable Court has not been asked to evaluate the fact that these provisions refer only to benefits in respect of &ldquo;<UNDER>the</UNDER>&rdquo; tort award. In fact, the interpretation adopted by this Honourable Court in both <CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC></CASEREF> as well as <CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long</SOC></CASEREF> adopt an interpretation which would place no meaning on the word &ldquo;<UNDER>the</UNDER>&rdquo; and reads the provision as if the word is omitted. This distinction does not appear to have been argued in either case.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 251 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 8</UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 717 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 7</UNDER></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>ii.</N><TI>Implications of the Interpretations</TI>
<P>66. The &ldquo;apples to apples&rdquo; interpretation of the legislation, which is consistent with <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Fonseca v. Hansen</SOC></CASEREF>, enhances the likelihood that the plaintiff is fully compensated while avoiding double recovery. Benefits that are matched to the actual damages awarded on both a <UNDER>temporal</UNDER> as well as a <UNDER>qualitative</UNDER> basis will ensure that the benefits actually overlap the tort award.</P>
<P>67. This approach also provides flexibility to litigants to recognize that claims which are fully compensated from collateral sources need not be advanced. Litigants would not be compelled to advance past income loss claims if they are not seeking damages for past income loss. It would enable litigants to pursue only claims for which they are seeking damages from the tort defendant. It also permits judges to ensure that only deductions for the particular claims p ursued are made. It promotes reasonableness and efficiency rather than a proliferation of claims at trial.</P>
<P>68. Proportionality has become fundamentally important in litigation in recent years. All levels of court are demanding proportionality. It is contrary to proportionality to require litigants to pursue claims for which a collateral source has fully compensated them. It is contrary to proportionality to require litigants to pursue claims simply to avoid an unfair deduction or assignment rather than for the purpose of seeking damages from the tortfeasor.</P>
<P>69. Flexibility and reasonableness should be encouraged in the judicial system particularly as the plain language of the legislation supports such an interpretation. Parties should be encouraged to continue the practice of narrowing issues in dispute. This Honourable Court in <CASEREF><SOC>El Khodr v. Lackie</SOC></CASEREF> appears to have approved of the practice of advancing &ldquo;net claims&rdquo; only at trial or the ability of plaintiffs to frame their claims to address only the amounts actually in dispute:
<QUOTE><P>In <EM>Bannon</EM>, the plaintiffs did not seek recovery of benefits already provided to them by their no-fault insurer; their claims were presented net of those benefits. Nevertheless, the appellants in that case argued that the payments still had to be deducted from the damage award in the tort claim. The result in <EM>Bannon</EM> is not surprising; where the claim was presented net of no-fault payments, any further deduction would have amounted to a <UNDER>double counting of the no-fault benefits</UNDER>. <UNDER>[Emphasis added]</UNDER></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>52</PARANUM></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 9</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>70. An interpretation that demands the rigid deduction or assignment of benefits without attempting to match the benefits to the damages awarded would eliminate the possibility of such an approach.</P>
<P>71. <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC></CASEREF> confirmed the availability of a &ldquo;Cox and Carter&rdquo; order for future benefits under s.267(l) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>. As stated in <EM>El Khodr</EM>, the provisions contained in s. 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> providing for assignments of collateral benefits are a codification of the &ldquo;Cox and Carter&rdquo; order. As such, the same general principles outlined in <EM>Bannon</EM> relating to future collateral benefits should be applicable under the current legislation. The Supreme Court affirmed that it is presumed, in the absence of a clear provision to the contrary, that the Legislature does not intend to change existing law or to depart from established principles, polic ies or practices.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC><CITE>1998 CanLII 4486</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <UNDER>at p. 38, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 1</UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>53</PARANUM></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Anthorities, Tab 9.</UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Parry Sound (District) Social Services Administrat ion Board v. O.P.S.E.U., Local 324</SOC><CITE>[2003] 2 SCR 157</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2003 SCC 42 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>39</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 10</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>72. With respect to the implications of the Supreme Court of Canada decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC></CASEREF>, caution is required in transposing principles contained in the B.C. legislation to the Ontario legislation. The B.C. legislation contained a very specific provision that &ldquo;[a] person who has a claim for damages and who receives or is entitled to receive benefits respecting the claim, is deemed to have released the claim to the extent of the benefits.&rdquo; As noted in the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>El Khodr v. Lackie</SOC></CASEREF>, the equivalent provision in the Ontario legislation was removed from the legislation in 1990. The current legislation has no such provision. Given that the applicable provision was expressly removed from the legislation, the interpretation of deductibility of benefits contained in <EM>Gurniak</EM> is not applicable to the statutory provisions at issue in the within appeals.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gurnia k v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>44</PARANUM></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>39</PARANUM></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 9</UNDER></P1>
<P1>Insurance Act, R. S. O. 1980, c. 218., s.s. 239(2) [version not available on Canlii]</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>iii.</N><TI>Trust and Assignment Provisions</TI>
<P>73. Unlike the deduction provisions of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, the assignment provisions do not mandate the nature or scope of the assignment or trust. The provisions provide for determination by arbitration (trust provisions) or discretion of the trial judge (assignment). Unlike the deduction provisions, which specifically mandate the deductions to be applied, the trust and assignment provisions simply provide that &ldquo;a plaintiff who recovers damages&rdquo; will be impressed with a trust, or subject to an assignment, in respect of future collateral benefits. The trust provisions mandate that the any resulting dispute be determined by way of arbitration while the assignment provisions are subject to judicial discretion &ldquo;subject to any conditions the court considers just.&rdquo;</P>
<P>74. With respect to the trust provisions contained in the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, a plaintiff who recovers damages for income loss, loss of earning capacity, expenses that have been or will be incurred for health care, or other pecuniary loss in an action for loss or damage from bodily injury or death arising directly or indirectly from the use or operation of an automobile shall hold <UNDER>all</UNDER> payments relating to <UNDER>all</UNDER> collateral benefits in trust. The legislation enumerates the types of collateral benefits available. The legislation requires the plaintiff to hold the money in trust for the b enefit of persons from whom &ldquo;damages were recovered&rdquo; in proportions that those persons paid &ldquo;the damages.&rdquo; Disputes relating to the &ldquo;plaintiff's liability to make payments&rdquo; are referred to arbitration.
<P1><UNDER>Insurance Act, R.S.O. 1990. c.I.8. s.267.8(9)-(11)</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>75. The assignment provisions contained in s. 267.8(12) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, on the other hand, use permissive, rather than mandatory, language:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>267.8</N>
<SSEC><N>(12)</N><SSECP>The court that heard and determined the action for loss or damage from bodily injury or death arising directly or indirectly from the use or operation of the automobile, on motion, <BOLD>may order that, subject to any conditions the court considers just</BOLD>,
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>the plaintiff who recovered damages in the action <BOLD>assign to the defendants or the defendants' insurers all rights in respect of all payments to which the plaintiff who recovered damages</BOLD> is entitled in respect of the incident after the trial of the action,
<SPARA><N>(i)</N><SPARAP>for statutory accident benefits in respect of income loss...;...</SPARAP></SPARA>
<SPARA><N>(iv)</N><SPARAP>for statutory accident benefits in respect of expenses for health care...;...</SPARAP></SPARA></PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>76. The assignment provision also requires recovery of the damages as a precondition of any assignment. This makes logical and practical sense as there is no potential for double recovery unless the judgment is paid in full. It was an error of law for the trial judge to order an assignment in the present case given that the Defendants have failed to pay the Judgment. Recovery of the damages awarded is a necessary precondition to an assignment. This is particularly concerning since the trial judge acknowledged in his Reasons for Decision that it is unlikely that the Defendants will ultimately pay the Judgment. The necessary preconditions were not met to grant an assignment.</P>
<P>77. The Plaintiffs are not disputing that a trial judge could, under different circumstances, award an assignment of all payments for each of the enumerated benefits if such assignment is warranted and matches <UNDER>the</UNDER> damages which were awarded at trial. However, the provision does not provide an automatic right to such an assignment and the discretion must be exercised judicially.</P>
<P>78. Matching is required on several bases. Technically, the language of the assignment provisions does not import a requirement that the assignment be limited to the amount of damages and provides little guidance. It is logical to make reference to the deduction provisions which are contained in</P>
<P>79. There must be some matching of the collateral benefit to the damages awarded. The legislation cannot be literally interpreted as requiring an assignment of <UNDER>all</UNDER> payments for <UNDER>all</UNDER> the enumerated categories irrespective of the actual damages recovered. It would be an absurd interpretation to permit a tortfeasor to recover more in collateral benefits by assignment than the tortfeasor was required to pay in damages. There must be a matching of benefits beyond the express language of the legislation in order for the assignment to be fair and reasonable. A trial judge is required to consider whether the assignment, or the conditions to be placed upon the assignment, are &ldquo;just.&rdquo;</P>
<P>80. It is respectfully submitted that a just assignment must include a matching analysis to ensure that (a) the benefits <UNDER>temporally</UNDER> match the damages and (b) the benefits <UNDER>qualitatively</UNDER> match the damages. Justice requires a balancing of the interests of full compensation to the pl aintiff contrasted with a prevention of double recovery.</P>
<P>81. In dismissing the appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF>, this Honourable Court determined that a global jury award for &ldquo;future care costs&rdquo; that did not allocate damages to particular items of care was insufficient to secure an assignment, even where &ldquo;some overlap might be likely.&rdquo; It must be accurately determined what portion of the jury's future care costs mirrored expenses which the plaintiff continues to be entitled to claim under the SABS before an assi gnment could be granted.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC><CITE>[2015] OJ. No. 5573</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A</COURTJUR></CASEREF> para 47-48. Appellants' Book of Authorities. Tab 5.</P1></P>
<P>82. In the within action, the Defendants drafted the damages questions to the jury. The question directed the jury to give one lump sum amount for the value of &ldquo;future care costs.&rdquo; The Defendants could have asked the jury to detail the specific items of future care costs for which they intended to seek an assignment. They elected not to do so and for possibly good reasons. As a result, the duration and amount of damages for medical and rehabilitation services, as well as the duration and amount of damages awarded for attendant care, was never disclosed to the parties.</P>
<P>83. With respect to <UNDER>temporal</UNDER> matching, it is admitted by all parties that the attendant care benefits will be exhausted in 8.67 years post-trial. With respect to medical and rehabilitation benefits, the parties agreed they would be exhausted between 1.5 and 2.55 years post-trial. The damages awarded to the Plaintiff were awarded for her lifetime. It is unclear what damages correspond to the period of time which temporally match the SABS benefits sought to be assigned. While there may be &ldquo;some overlap&rdquo; the precise breakdown of the award for &ldquo;future care costs&rdquo; is unknown.</P>
<P>84. The Plaintiffs submit that the assignment should not rely on guesswork or assumptions. The heavy burden of establishing double recovery falls entirely upon the Defendants. They had the onus to demonstrate that the jury award compensated Barbara Carroll for the same loss. There is no way to determine with any certainty what the jury was intending to compensate. An assignment of all medical rehabilitation and attendant care benefits runs the risk that Barbara Carroll will receive less than full compensation for her loss.</P>
<P>85. The Defendants had every opportunity, if they wished to pursue an assignment, to ensure that the jury award was properly particularized. They chose not to do so. This decision is likely based upon the fact that the Defendants never intended to pay more than their insurance limits. They have yet to pay more than their insurance limits.</P>
<P>86. In agreeing to hear the motion as a hypothetical, the trial judge erred in failing to make a comparison between the jury verdict and the future accident benefits for which the assignment was sought. The trial judge purported to rely upon the &ldquo;indirect matching&rdquo; allegedly performed by Ms. Larouche. No such analysis appears in the record. None.</P>
<P>87. The &ldquo;apples to apples&rdquo; comparison is required for the assignment of future accident benefits and the trial judge erred in failing to conduct the analysis. To the extent that the trial judge re lied upon a non-existent analysis conducted by Ms. Larouche, he committed a palpable and overriding error.</P>
<P>88. The Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>El Khodr v. Lackie</SOC></CASEREF> expressly acknowledged that &ldquo;the present legislation does, to a limited extent, import a matching requirement.&rdquo; According to that decision, the matching is limited to the &ldquo;silos&rdquo; created by 267.8 (presumably referring to deduction provisions of s.267.8 as the assignment provisions simply list all potential assignments that could be made).
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>60</PARANUM></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 9</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>89. Under the SABS, there are many categories of benefits. Section267.8 specifically enumerates three categories that can be assigned. The importance of the provision was not to create &ldquo;silos&rdquo; but to specifically exclude certain benefits from assignment, including non-earner benefits (Part III), caregiver benefits (Part IV), as well as death and funeral benefits (Part VII). Even if &ldquo;silos&rdquo; were created under the deduction provisions, they refer back to <UNDER>the</UNDER> specific damages which the plaintiff received and not <UNDER>all</UNDER> payments for loss of income or <UNDER>all</UNDER> payments for health care.</P>
<P>90. Flexibility in bringing claims for only amounts sought against the tortfeasor ought to be encouraged. An automatic deduction or assignment should not be given for <UNDER>all</UNDER> benefits in a category for the mere reason that they fall within a &ldquo;silo.&rdquo; This interpretation would require the plaintiff to litigate <UNDER>all</UNDER> damages even if fully compensated by a collateral source. If a party is only claiming for future income loss, a fair and reasonable assignment ought to be limited to benefits intended to compensate future income loss and then only to the extent that damages were actually awarded for future income loss. The intention of the legislation is to avoid double recovery and this objective can be met by ensuring that the deduction or assignment is restricted to a collateral benefit which matches, both <UNDER>temporally</UNDER> and <UNDER>qualitatively</UNDER>, the damages awarded.</P>
<P>91. Lastly, the Defendants have still not satisfied the Judgment amount. The legislation does not permit an assignment until payment has been made. This requirement makes practical sense as there is no potential for &ldquo;double recovery&rdquo; until the tortfeasor(s) pays the judgment. The Defendants should not be permitted, in these circumstances, to seek an advance ruling of their legal entitlement in the event of some hypothetical future conduct. The fact t hat they have yet to pay the Judgment, now nearly 2&nbsp;<TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC>years post-verdict, underlines the hypothetical nature of these issues.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Issue"><N>#2</N><TI>The trial judge made errors in principle in the exercise of his discretion on costs which resulted in a costs award that is plainly wrong and punitive to the Plaintiffs. Leave to appeal should be granted and partial indemnity costs should be awarded.</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>i.</N><TI>Leave to Appeal</TI>
<P>92. Section 133 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM> requires leave to appeal with respect to an Order for costs.
<P1><UNDER>Section 133 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c.C.43.</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>93. In circumstances where a trial judge has made an error in principle, or where the costs award is plainly wrong, the costs award may be set aside.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton v. Open Window</SOC><CITE>[2004] 1 S.C.R. 303</CITE><PARANUM>27</PARANUM></CASEREF><UNDER>; Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 12</UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith Estate v. Rotstein</SOC><CITE>2011 ONCA 491</CITE><PARANUM>45</PARANUM></CASEREF><UNDER>. Appellants' Book of Authorities. Tab 13</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>94. In circumstances where criticism or derisive comments by the trial judge of couns el are largely unwarranted, the costs award may be reviewed in appeal. Intervention of the costs award may be justified if the conduct of counsel did not warrant penalization or did not warrant penalization to such a significant extent in the costs award.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Jarbeau v. McLean</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 115</CITE><PARANUM>64, 80-81</PARANUM></CASEREF><UNDER>.Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 14</UNDER></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>ii.</N><TI>Attempted settlement of &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo;</TI>
<P>95. The trial judge erred in law in penalizing the Plaintiffs in costs for a motion which was cau sed by the Defendants making an offer to settle &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo; and then, <UNDER>only after the offer was accepted</UNDER>, disclosing that the offer to settle was intended to also include matters outside of the proceeding. The trial judge characterized the Defendants' offer as an &ldquo;unenforceable offer.&rdquo; Yet the Plaintiffs bore the severe consequences of having accepted the &ldquo;unenforceable offer.&rdquo;</P>
<P>96. The Plaintiffs state that the offer to settle which was accepted was clear and plain on its face and related to &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo; only. The Defendants took the position that their offer, though worded as pertaining to &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo; only, encompassed a bad faith dispute as well as past accident benefits. This raised additional issues as the Defendants had made a similar o ffer earlier in the action and had to admit that the earlier offer also attracted implied terms and conditions.</P>
<P>97. These offers were unfair to the Plaintiffs. Had the &ldquo;unenforceable offer&rdquo; not been accepted, the Defendants would have unfairly and wrongfully been able to rely on rule 49 in seeking cost consequences. This raises real concerns of mischief that could be accomplished by permitting hidden terms to attach to an offer that are only disclosed upon acceptance of the offer .</P>
<P>98. Rule 49.02(1) states that &ldquo;a party to a proceeding may serve on any other party an offer to settle any one or more of the claims <UNDER>in the proceeding</UNDER> on the terms specified in the offer to settle.&rdquo; Form 49A contains the same wording as the Defendants's offer as follows:
<QUOTE><P>The (identified party) offers to settle <UNDER>this proceeding</UNDER> (or the following claims in this proceeding) on the following terms. [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Rule 1.06(2) and 49.02(1) and Form 49A of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></UNDER></P1></P>
<P>99. A claim in the proceeding is a claim included in the statement of claim.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Igbokwe v. HB Group Insurance Management Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2001], 55 O.R. (3d) 313</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <UNDER>at para 8. Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 15</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>100. Offers that extend beyond claims in the proceeding, including the requirement for a full and final settlement of all claims that a plaintiff may have against a defendant, whether pertaining to the proceeding or not, do not qualify as Rule 49 offers.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Amyotte v. Wawanesa Mutual Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 3321</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Div.Ct</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <UNDER>at para 14. Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 16</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>101. The Plaintiffs state that it is an error of law to interpret the wording of the offer to settle utilizing Rule 49 wording as including matters outside of the proceeding. It would place considerable uncertainty into the meaning of offers to settle served under Rule 49. These offers are intended to settle the matters in dispute in the proceeding <UNDER>only</UNDER>. Full and final releases of all issues between the parties are not required nor mandated by Rule 49. If the parties seek to resolve issues outside of the proceeding, the offers could and should specify that other issues are encompassed in the offer.</P>
<P>102. The Plaintiffs were legitimately concerned that the Defendants were requesting the motions judge to &ldquo;read-in&rdquo; terms into an accepted offer to settle while asserting that their previous offer (also to settle &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo;) was a proper Rule 49 offer. On the motion before Hackland J, it was confirmed that all offers contained an implied terms requiring a full and final release of the bad faith claims and past accident benefits. Upon confirmation of the implied conditions in the previous offer, the Plaintiffs withdrew their motion and the parties proceeded to trial.</P>
<P>103. Despite receiving clarification that the Defendants' previous &ldquo;Rule 49&rdquo; offer of $1,757,500 required release of bad faith claims and past accident benefit claims, the Defendants proceeded, post-trial, to characterize the very same offer as a Rule 49 offer despite assurances on the motion before Hackland J that the offer contained implied conditions relating to matters outside the scope of &ldquo;this proceeding.&rdquo; This was the precise problem the Plaintiffs sought to clarify before Hackland, J. As the Defendants did not ultimately beat the offer, nor even the Plaintiffs' offers, the $1,757,500 offer became irrelevant for cost purposes but it certainly raises concerns regarding the potential abuse that could have occurred had the jury verdict been different.</P>
<P>104. The Plaintiffs obtained a Judgment in excess of the &ldquo;unenforceable offer.&rdquo; In addition, the Plaintiffs have not released any bad faith claims or claims for past accident benefits. The Plaint iffs have recovered over $2,000,000 in damages and $50,584 in past SABS. Their bad faith action is ongoing. The Defendants would have been well served to have accepted the settlement without insisting upon release of matters outside of this litigation.</P>
<P>105. The Plaintiffs state that it was ultimately the Defendants who were responsible for the failed settlement. If the Defendants had intended to make an offer encompassing the bad faith claims, past accident benefits or any other matters outside of &ldquo;this proceeding,&rdquo; they could have easily done so. Instead, they opted to use Rule 49 wording in their offer.</P>
<P>106. Vast uncertainty would arise if offers to settle using the actual wording of Rule 49 were then interpreted as including implied terms to resolve claims falling outside of the subject proceeding. The entire purpose of Rule 49 is to have offers which can be directly compared with the ultimate Judgment. Implied inclusion of claims outside of the proceeding renders that exerc ise impossible. A trial judge cannot and should not quantify the value of claims outside of the proceeding.
<P1><UNDER>Rule 49 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></UNDER>.</P1></P>
<P>107. It was the Plaintiffs position that an offer to settle &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo; is limited to the claims in &ldquo;this proceeding.&rdquo; It was a reasonable position based on the plain wording of the offer to settle and as well as the authority of this Honourable Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Igbokwe v. HB Group Insurance Management</SOC></CASEREF>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Igbokwe v. HB Group Insurance Management</SOC><CITE>55 O.R. (3d) 313</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A</COURTJUR></CASEREF><UNDER>.Appellants' Book of Authorities. Tab 15</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>108. Bad faith claims against insurers are not claims for indemnity under the insurance contract. On the contrary, there is an independent duty of the utmost good faith which an insurer owes to an insured which is independent of and in addition to the breach of a contractual duty. A breach of the duty to act fairly and in good faith gives rise to a separate cause of action that is distinct from a cause of action under the insurance policy.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Dundas v. Zurich Canada</SOC><CITE>[2012] OJ No. 1321</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <UNDER>at para 49&ndash;51;Appellants' Book of Authorities. Tab 17</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>109. The correspondence between the parties prior to the failed settlement demonstrate that the parties recognized that the bad faith claims would be the subject matter of another legal action and a debate was already underway regarding who could act as counsel in that action. Irregardl ess, even if there was a misunderstanding, that misunderstanding was caused by the Defendants.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>iii.</N><TI>Failure to Consider the Plaintiffs' Offers</TI>
<P>110. A trial judge is required to consider offers to settle, and Rule 49.13 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, particularly in a case where offers to settle are close to the result.
<P1><UNDER>Rules 57.01(1) and 49.13 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Elbakhiet v. Palmer</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 544</CITE></CASEREF><UNDER>.Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 18</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>111. The trial judge failed to consider the Plaintiffs' Offer to Settle against the McEwens (made six days before the commencement of trial and open until the last week of trial). The offer of $1M was unequivocally more favourable to the McEwen Defendants and ought to have been given significant weight by the trial judge.</P>
<P>112. In addition to the offer to settle as against the McEwens, the Plaintiffs made joint offers which were all within the combined insurance limits of the McEwens (Aviva) and the insurance limits under the OPCF44 policy of Barbara Carroll (Pilot/Aviva). The ultimate Judgment secured exceeded all of these offers.</P>
<P>113. Instead of considering the Plaintiffs' offers to settle to justify a higher costs award or penalizing the Defendants in any way for their failure to accept reasonable offers, the trial judge appears to have imposed a requirement that Plaintiffs not only beat their offers, but that they have to beat them by a &ldquo;substantial&rdquo; margin simply to secure partial indemnity costs. In any event, the Judgment did exceed the offers by a substantial margin. The Plaintiffs have already received in damages $143,720.00 more than they were willing to accept in their joint Offer to Settle. The Plaintiffs have received $1,610,774.32 more than the Plaintiffs' Offer to Settle as against the McEwens. These numbers are substantial by any measure.</P>
<P>114. It is certainly curious that the McEwens did not accept the $1,000,000 Offer to Settle as against them despite the fact that the Defendants' joint offers clearly indicated that the insurance limits of the McEwens were exhausted. No explanation has ever been provided for this conduct. Why were two counsel at trial representing the McEwens? The Plaintiffs were forced to litigate an eight we ek trial against two sets of lawyers: Pilot/Aviva (represented by Ms. Neate) and the McEwens (represented by Mr. Nearing and Ms. Durant), also insured by Aviva. The trial judge ought to have considered the McEwens' failure to accept the Plaintiffs' offer o r at least question what reasonable basis existed for the McEwens to remain in this action in light of the offers made.</P>
<P>115. The trial judge further erred in stating that the joint offers were &ldquo;virtually all of the money available.&rdquo; Even if the Plaintiffs' claim in the McEwens' bankruptcy were disregarded, the combined insurance limits of the Defendants was $2M. <UNDER>All</UNDER> of the Plaintiffs' offers were within those insurance limits. The Plaintiffs were willing to accept $143,720 less than the combined insurance limits of the Defendants to resolve the action. The Defendants refused and have since paid out their insurance limits.</P>
<P>116. If the trial decision is left to stand, it essentially gives <EM>carte blanche</EM> to insurers to withhold their full insurance limits in claims that exceed those limits and then argue after trial that Plaintiffs should be penalized for obtaining a higher judgment that is not &ldquo;substantially more&rdquo; than the Plaintiffs' own offers. Beating one's own offer is a victory. It demonstrates that the Plaintiffs were acting reasonably and that the Defendants were not. The trial judge failed to give any weight to the Plaintiffs' offers, thereby penalizing the wrong party in costs..</P>
<P>117. The Defendants chose to force these Plaintiffs through an eight week trial. They gambled and lost. The result is a Judgment greater than the Plaintiffs' offers. Consequences ought to have followed and the Plaintiffs were entitled to their partial indemnity costs.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>iv.</N><TI>Leave for examination for discovery of the Plaintiff Barbara Carroll at outset of trial</TI>
<P>118. Where an action is brought by a party under disability, the litigation guardian may be examined in place of the person under disability. At the option of the examining party, the person under disability may be examined. Parties who have consented for a matter to be set down for trial shall not initiate or continue any form of discovery without leave of the court.
<P1><UNDER>Rule 31.01 and Rule 31.03(5) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</UNDER></P1>
<P1><UNDER>Rule 48.04(1) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>119. The Defendants brought a motion at trial requesting that Barbara Carroll to be excluded as a witness in her own trial. In the alternative they requested to conduct an examination for discovery.</P>
<P>120. The decisions of the trial judge indicate that he misapprehended the evidence and incorrectly, and without evidentiary foundation, determined there was a representation during examination for discoveries that Barbara Carroll would not be called as witness as she would not give useful evidence. No such representation was even argued at trial.</P>
<P>121. The Defendants position that they relied on alleged comments of Plaintiffs' counsel (supposedly made <UNDER>after</UNDER> completion of discoveries and after consenting to the matter being set down for trial), opining on the &ldquo;usefulness&rdquo; of Barbara Carroll's evidence, to justify their failure to br ing a motion prior to trial was not tenable. In fact, ten (10) months prior to trial, the Defendants had turned their minds to the fact that there was no undertaking not to call Barbara Carroll as a witness at trial. They went so far as to put that information in an affidavit (which was not served until trial).</P>
<P>122. The Plaintiffs strenuously challenged the allegations of the Defendants. The trial judge denied the Plaintiffs' request to cross-examine upon the affidavit evidence. If allegations of misconduct were to be levelled against Plaintiffs' counsel, a reasonable opportunity to challenge the allegations ought to have been provided to the Plaintiffs. Ultimately, the Defendants ought to be blamed for their <UNDER>own decision</UNDER> to proceed to trial without examination for discovery of Barbara Carroll.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>v.</N><TI>The trial judge erred in failing to consider the failure of the Defendants to adhere to the case management time lines</TI>
<P>123. None of the parties to this litigation ultimately complied with the case management order with respect to expert reports. Both parties served late reports. The only evidence of prejudice was upon the Plaintiffs regarding the Defendants' mid-trial revised life expectancy report. The Plaintiffs would have retained a life expectancy expert to respond to this report if sufficient time had been provided for an expert to review and respond to the report prior to the conclusion of trial.</P>
<P>124. As for the future care reports, even if one were to accept that there were significant changes between the Plaintiffs' two future care reports, it was irrelevant as the Defendants did not even have their own future care report completed and served until three weeks before trial (at the same time as the Plaintiffs' updated report). The Plaintiffs were not deserving of punishment in costs.</P>
<P>125. If adherence to time lines are considered, it was an error for the trial judge not to consider the conduct and time lines of both counsel in an even handed manner.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>vi.</N><TI>Conclusion on Costs</TI>
<P>126. The trial judge's approach to costs demonstrates significant errors in principle which justify intervention by this Honourable Court. In addition, a costs award which denies partial indemn ity costs to a party who was willing to settle for substantially less than the Judgment secured at trial is so plainly wrong that it ought to be set aside as both punitive and unfair to the Plaintiffs.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>127. The Plaintiffs (Appellants in Appeal) respectfully request that this Honourable Court grant the within appeal and Order that:
<P1>(a) the assignment of statutory accident benefits be set aside;</P1>
<P1>(b) leave to appeal on costs be granted to the Appellants;</P1>
<P1>(c) the Plaintiff is entitled to costs of the trial on a partial indemnity basis fixed at $795,616.09, or in the alternative, on a partial indemnity basis to be assessed;</P1>
<P1>(d) partial indemnity costs of the supplementary trial proceedings to the Plaintiffs in an amount to be assessed; and</P1>
<P1>(e) costs of the within appeal.</P1></P>
