<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The Appellants' appeal has two objectives: to obtain double recovery for future health care expenses to which they are already entitled under statutory accident benefits and, (if leave to appeal is granted) to avoid the costs consequences of their conduct of the action.</P>
<P>2. This action arises from a pedestrian/motor vehicle accident on May 28, 2009, in which the Plaintiff/Appellant Barbara Carroll sustained a catastrophic brain injury.</P>
<P>3. The maximum risk to the Defendants in the action and the total possible recovery by the Plaintiffs was $2,000,000 plus costs. The Respondent McEwens declared bankruptcy in 2011 and obtained an Absolute Discharge on June 18, 2012, except for an amount up to the $1,000,000 limit of their insurance coverage. There was a further $1,000,000 available by virtue of the Appellant Barbara Carroll's OPCF44 endorsement with the Respondent Aviva.</P>
<P>4. After an 8 week trial, the jury found that Barbara Carroll was 38% at fault for the accident and (taking into account the apportionment of liability), assessed her damages at $2,418,000 plus interest. Of that amount, $2,232,000 related to the cost of future care. Damages were awarded to the other Plaintiffs for <EM>Family Law Act</EM> claims. The total verdict was $2,610,774.32.</P>
<P>5. Following the jury's verdict, the trial Judge made two orders that are the subject of the appeal.</P>
<P>6. First, he ordered that the future accident benefits payable to Ms. Carroll under the statutory benefits scheme should be assigned to the Defendants upon payment of the judgment against them. The trial Judge made this order to prevent double recovery. He was satisfied that the Defendants had discharged a &ldquo;very strict onus of proof&rdquo; and that &ldquo;on the evidence it is patently clear that the preconditions for an appropriate assignment have been made out&rdquo;: para. 10 of the Reasons of the trial Judge.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean at para. 10 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, pages 21 and 22].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. The Respondent McEwens' position is that this discretionary order is supported by sound legal principle and by findings of fact that are not tainted by any reviewable error.</P>
<P>8. Second, the trial Judge reduced the Plaintiffs' claimed costs by more than 50% by virtue of the conduct of the Plaintiffs' solicitors. The Judge found that going to trial had resulted in little, if any, practical benefit to the Plaintiffs; that their solicitors' conduct had unnecessarily extended the proceedings and that they had tried to trick the Defendants by accepting an offer to settle the proceedings while, a minute later, serving the Defendant Aviva with a $2,000,000 claim for bad faith.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean at paras.45, 48, 49 and 50 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, pages 31 and 32]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>9. The Respondent McEwens' position is that leave to appeal this discretionary order should be denied as the Judge made no error in principle and the order is not plainly wrong.</P>
<P>10. The Respondent McEwens are not pursuing any cross-appeal with respect to the trial Judge's costs order.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>Background</UNDER></TI>
<P>11. The Respondent McEwens accept the facts as stated in paragraphs 12, 21, 22 and 32 of the Plaintiffs' (Appellants) Statement of Facts.</P>
<P>12. The Plaintiffs initiated proceedings against the Defendants (Respondents) Robert McEwen and Caroline McEwen (the driver and owner of the motor vehicle). The Plaintiffs also sued their own insurer, the Respondent Aviva Canada Inc. (&ldquo;Aviva&rdquo;), pursuant to the OPCF 44 Family Protection Endorsement in Barbara Carroll's motor vehicle insurance policy. Aviva's exposure under Barbara Carroll's OPCF44 endorsement was $1,000,000 inclusive of interests and costs.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Statement of Claim issued March 25, 2011 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 8, pages 43 to 58].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. The McEwens' insurance policy limits were $1,000,000, inclusive of prejudgment interest. The McEwens had declared bankruptcy in 2012. The Plaintiffs' claim was listed as a liability in their bankruptcy.</P>
<P>14. The McEwens were given an absolute discharge from their bankruptcy in June 2012. The Carrolls' solicitors obtained an Order from the Registrar in Bankruptcy enabling them to continue with the action but only to the extent of the limits of McEwens' policy.</P>
<P>15. Throughout these proceedings, the Plaintiffs' solicitor maintained the position that they had a right to take proceedings for further recovery against the McEwens over and above the limits of the McEwens' insurance policy, a position that has no basis in law.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>McEwen Insurance Declaration, Exhibit Book Vol. 2, pages 514 to 518 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 1, page 1]</BOLD>; Certificate of Absolute Discharge of the Bankruptcy of the McEwens dated June 18, 2012 Exhibit Book, Vol. 3, pages 704 to 710 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 2, pages 8 and 10]</BOLD>; Order of Master Pierre E. Roger dated October 12, 2002 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 5, pages 35 to 37]</BOLD>; Email from Joseph Obagi to Kevin Nearing dated September 7, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 1, pages 180 and 181 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 3, page 13]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. The Appellants have abandoned the Appeal with respect to the trial Judge's Decision prohibiting the Plaintiffs from claiming under the Defendants' bankruptcy, for any shortfall in the satisfaction of the resulting judgment.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Notice of Appeal dated June 16, 2016, <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 1, page 3, at paras.(h) and (i)]</BOLD>; Revised Plaintiffs' Factum, para.7 at page 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>17. The maximum realistic recovery for the Plaintiffs was thus the limits of the insurance coverage, plus costs, and the maximum risk to the Defendants in the action was the same: $2,000,000 plus costs.</P>
<P>18. There were two main issues at trial: liability and Barbara Carroll's claim for damages for the cost of future care.</P>
<P>19. Liability was a serious issue as witnessed by the jury's verdict dividing liability 62/38% in the Plaintiffs' favour.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Jury Questions answered October 30, 2015 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 24, page 145].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. With respect to the claim for damages for the cost of future care, by the time of trial, Barbara Carroll had already used $1,011,045 of the $2,000,000 of available accident benefits for attendant care and medical and rehabilitation benefits.</P>
<P>21. Prior to trial, the Defendants had served a motion for an assignment, <EM>inter alia</EM>, of future statutory accident benefits in respect of expenses for health care.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Notice of Motion dated August 28, 2015 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 4, pages 15 to 17]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>22. After the jury was selected and opening statements were made, and before any evidence was called, the Defendants served a time-limited offer dated September 11, 2015, to settle the Plaintiffs' claim for $2,150,000 inclusive of all damages, prejudgment interest and costs.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Offer to Settle of the Defendants September 11, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 2, page 530 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 36, page 177]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>23. The offer did not request any assignment of the remaining future health care expenses available to Barbara Carroll through her accident benefits insurer. At the start of trial, the information provided by the Plaintiffs' solicitors was that Barbara Carroll had $988,955 of remaining health care expenses available to her from her accident benefits insurer. On its face, the Defendants' offer had an apparent value in excess of $3,000,000.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Elizabeth Quigley to Kevin Nearing dated August 18, 2015, Exhibit Book, pages 1161 and 1162 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 5, pages 19 and 20].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. One minute after purporting to accept the offer, the Plaintiffs served counsel for Aviva with a brand new statement of claim in which they sought punitive damages and damages for bad faith in the amount of $2,000,000. The Defendants advised the Plaintiffs' counsel that their offer was intended to settle all litigation and that, if the Plaintiffs were not prepared to release the Defendants of any and all claims, they were not prepared to proceed with a $2,150,000 settlement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter from Ms. Quigley to Mr. Sutherland and Ms. Neate dated September 11, 2015 serving new Statement of Claim, Exhibit Book, page 229 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 6, page 21]</BOLD>; Letter from Ms. Quigley to Mr. Nearing and Mr. Sutherland dated September 11, 2015 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 32, page 169]</BOLD>; Email from Ms. Quigley to Mr. Nearing, Mr. Sutherland and Stephanie Neate sent September 11, 2015, at 4:24 p.m ., Exhibit Book, page 268 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 7, pages 22 and 23]</BOLD>; Email from Ms. Quigley to Mr. Sutherland and Ms. Neate sent September 11, 2015, at 4: 25 p.m., Exhibit Book, pages 271 and 272 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 8, pages 24 and 25].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. The Plaintiffs' solicitors then brought a Motion to enforce the &ldquo;settlement&rdquo;. This led to a hearing before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015. The Plaintiffs ultimately withdrew their Motion to enforce the &ldquo;settlement&rdquo; and proceeded to trial.</P>
<P>26. The jury assessed Barbara Carroll's cost of future care claim at $3,600,000. After reducing the award by Barbara Carroll's contributory negligence of 38%, the net amount awarded for Barbara Carroll's cost of future care claim was $2,232,000.</P>
<P>27. The jury questions were the result of back and forth negotiations between counsel. The mutually agreed upon proposed questions were accepted by the trial Judge and given to the jury. The wording proposed by the Defendants was amended. With respect to future care costs, the parties and the trial Judge agreed upon a question that put all future care costs in one question.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Defendants' proposed jury questions <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 25, pages 147 and 149];</BOLD> Jury verdict <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 24, pages 145 and 146].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. After presiding over the trial and considering oral and written submissions, the trial Judge exercised his discretion and granted the Defendants an assignment of the future health care expenses in accordance with Section 267.8(12) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean at paras.9 to 11 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, pages 21 and 22].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>29. With respect to costs, the trial Judge concluded that the Plaintiffs had achieved little or no benefit by proceeding to trial. As part of the costs hearing, he reviewed the complete record regarding the aborted settlement, including the transcript of the proceedings before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean at para.36 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, page 28].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> After considering all of the relevant factors, the trial Judge properly exercised his discretion and reduced the Plaintiffs' request for costs from $795,616.09 to $375,000.00.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean at paras.48 to 51 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, pages 32 and 33]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>Assignment of Accidents Benefits for Health Care Expenses</UNDER></TI>
<P>30. After the jury verdict, the Defendants sought an order for the assignment of future health care expenses upon payment of the judgment. The purpose of the assignment is to prevent double recovery where it is clear that the damages awarded at trial duplicate the amounts covered by the statutory benefits for health care expenses.</P>
<P>31. Based on the evidence summarized below, the trial Judge concluded that there was no doubt that Barbara Carroll would receive all of the outstanding statutory accident benefits for health care expenses; that the Defendants had met the applicable onus of proof; and that &ldquo;based on that evidence, it is patently clear that the preconditions for an appropriate assignment had been made out&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean at paras. 10 and 11 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, pages 21 and 22]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>32. Because she had suffered a catastrophic impairment, Barbara Carroll had $2,000,000 of accident benefits available to her for health care expenses: $1,000,000 for medical and rehabilitation expenses and $1,000,000 for attendant care expenses.</P>
<P>33. As of the start of the trial, the information provided by the Plaintiffs' solicitors was that Barbara Carroll had already received $1,011,145 in health care expenses for medical/ rehabilitation benefits and attendant care, leaving a further $988,955 available to her.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Elizabeth Quigley to Kevin Nearing dated August 18, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol . 4, pages 1161 and 1162 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 5, pages 19 and 20]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>34. Subsequent information provided by the Plaintiffs' solicitors indicated that, as of the start of the trial, an additional $50,584 had been incurred but not yet paid.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Report of Gary Principe dated December 18, 2014, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, pages 1224 and 1229 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 43, pages 206 and 217].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There was no dispute with respect to these additional health care expenses. The record demonstrates that some of these expenses had already been paid by the time the parties came before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015. There was never any attempt by the Defendants or any intention on their part to have the Plaintiffs release any claim to the health care expenses that had been incurred but not yet paid.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Report of Gary Principe dated December 18, 204, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, page 1223 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 43, page 217].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>35. There was no evidence that there had been any dispute whatsoever with respect to any of Barbara Carroll's claim for accident benefits.</P>
<P>36. The vast majority of the evidence at trial was evidence with respect to Barbara Carroll's health care needs. As the trial Judge noted, there was substantial evidence led at trial, including the evidence of life care planners, caregivers and Barbara Carroll's occupational therapists.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean at paras.6, 9 and 10 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, pages 21 and 22].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>37. During the hearing regarding the assignment and costs, evidence filed by the Defendants indicated that Barbara Carroll's available medical and rehabilitation accident benefits would be exhausted in 1.5 years from the start of the trial. The Plaintiffs' evidence was that the remaining medical and rehabilitation benefits would be consumed in 2.55 years from the start of the trial. The experts agreed that attendant care benefits would be exhausted in 8.67 years from the start of the trial.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Report of Maryse Larouche dated February 5, 2016, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, page 1182 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 61, page 564];</BOLD> Report of Gary Principe dated December 18, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, page 1233 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 43, page 216].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>38. The Plaintiffs' updated cost of future care report indicated that medical and rehabilitation services were going to be consumed at $81,552.85 a year and personal care services (attendant care) were going to be consumed at a rate of anywhere between $136,733.26 and $195,100.00 a year.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Future Care Report Summary for Tort dated August 18, 2015 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 59, page 555].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. After adjusting for the $50,084 of health care expenses incurred but not paid as of the start of trial, Ms. Larouche, the Defendants' actuary, calculated the present value of the remaining health care expenses for medical and rehabilitation services and attendant care at between $760,511 and $813,748.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Maryse Larouche sworn February 9, 2016, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, pages 1171 and 1172 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 45, pages 306 and 307 at paras.6 and 7].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>40. Ms. Larouche's calculations and the calculations of Mr. Principe, the Plaintiffs' accountant, resulted in the identical figure for attendant care: $623,893. They differed slightly with respect to medical/rehabilitation benefits. Ms. Larouche calculated a figure of $274,180 to $277,895 whereas Mr. Principe calculated a figure of $263,714: a marginal difference.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Report of Gary Principe dated December 18, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, at page 1233 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 43, page 216]</BOLD>; Report of Maryse Larouche dated February 5, 2016, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, page 1182 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 61, page 564].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>41. The major difference between the two experts was an unsubstantiated 20% to 30% reduction by Mr. Principe on the theory that in a negotiated settlement, an accident benefits insurer would require this level of discount to settle a claim on a lump sum basis. With respect, this consideration is irrelevant in determining a present value figure for the outstanding health care expenses.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Gary Principe sworn January 29, 2006, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, page 1215 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 44, page 302, at para.5].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>42. The net result of the calculations was that the available accident benefits for health care expenses was either $749,037 (the Plaintiffs' number) or $760,511 to $813,748 (the Defendants' numbers).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Report of Maryse Larouche dated February 5, 2016, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, page 1182 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 61, page 564]</BOLD>; Report of Gary Principe dated December 18, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, page 1233 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 43, page 216].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>43. There was no dispute that Barbara Carroll was entitled to these accident benefits for future health care expenses.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI><UNDER>Costs</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><N>a)</N><TI><UNDER>Background</UNDER></TI>
<P>44. In exercising his discretion to substantially reduce the partial indemnity costs requested by the Plaintiffs, the trial Judge relied on three main factors: the conduct of t he Plaintiffs' solicitors in trying to trick the Defendants with respect to the &ldquo;settlement&rdquo;; conduct of the Plaintiffs' solicitors that unnecessarily extended the trial; and the modest results obtained at the trial.</P>
<P>45. The trial Judge received and reviewed affidavit and actuarial evidence regarding the present value of the remaining health care expenses, all of which demonstrated that the Plaintiffs achieved little, if any, benefit by proceeding with the trial.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, page 31, at para.45]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>b)</N><TI><UNDER>The Trick</UNDER></TI>
<P>46. A unique aspect of this case is the attempt by the Plaintiffs' solicitors to enforce their acceptance of the joint offer from the Defendants for $2,150,000 inclusive of interest and costs <UNDER>with no assignment of any remaining benefits for health care expenses</UNDER> after immediately issuing a $2 million bad faith claim against Aviva.</P>
<P>47. Without any risk of proceeding to trial, the value of the Defendants' offer using either the Plaintiffs' valuation of the accident benefits or the higher number of the Defendants' valuation of the accident benefits ranged from $2,899,037 to $2,963,748. The amount recovered in the jury verdict was less than these amounts.</P>
<P>48. The Plaintiffs accepted the $2,150,000 offer without disclosing that they had issued a new Statement of Claim against Aviva claiming $2,000,000 for bad faith, exemplary and punitive damages in connection with the handling of Ms. Carroll's claim. Literally, one minute after accepting the Defendants' offer, the Plaintiffs served the new Statement of Claim. The trial Judge made a finding of fact, based upon the evidence, that the solicitors for the Plaintiffs knew or should have known that the Offer the Plaintiffs' solicitors accepted was intended to settle all claims against the Defendants.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, pages 28, paras.34 and 36].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>49. There was ample evidence for the trial Judge to make this finding. There was nothing in the correspondence that went back and forth between the parties indicating that a bad faith claim would be brought in the event of a settlement.</P>
<P>50. Plaintiffs' counsel attempted to rely upon the words &ldquo;in the proceeding&rdquo; in the Defendants' offer to mean that the settlement would not have encompassed a claim against the Respondent, Aviva, for bad faith and punitive damages.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Offer to Settle of the Defendants September 11, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 2, page 530 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 36, page 177]</BOLD>; Factum of the Appellants, paras. 21, 22 and 23; Affidavit of Robert Sutherland dated September 12, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 1 pages 265 and 266 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 9, pages 26 and 27]</BOLD>; Affidavit of Jonathan L. Barker dated September 13, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 2, pages 289 to 291 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 10, page 29]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>51. It was clear from the record that, based upon representations made in the continuously aggressive correspondence of the Plaintiffs' solicitors, any threatened bad faith claim would only be brought after the <UNDER>trial</UNDER> of the Action.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Ms. Quigley to Ms. Neate and email chain dated September 6, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 1, pages 165 to 166 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 11, page 32].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>52. Other correspondence from the Plaintiffs' solicitors implied that a bad faith claim would be brought in the event that the parties did not reach a reasonable settlement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email of Joseph Obagi dated September 7, 2015. Exhibit Book, Vol. 1, page 180 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 47, page 314].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>53. At least one of the previous offers made by the solicitors for the Plaintiffs to the Defendants contemplated paying a sum of money &ldquo;for all damages and pre -judgement interest&rdquo; without limiting the offer to claims made &ldquo;in this proceeding&rdquo;. In other words, the Plaintiffs' offer contained the same &ldquo;defect&rdquo; as the Defendants' offer.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Offer to Settle of the Plaintiffs dated September 9, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 1, page 191 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 31, page 167].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>54. In an email dated September 10, 2015, the Plaintiffs negotiated separately with Aviva and made no mention of the possibility of a bad faith claim against Aviva should the Plaintiffs and the Defendants, including Aviva, reach a settlement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Ms. Quigley to Ms. Neate and Mr. Sutherland dated September 10, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 1, page 201 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 12, page 33]</BOLD>; Email from Ms. Quigley to Ms. Neate and Mr. Sutherland dated September 10, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 1, page 211 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 13, page 34].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>55. In a letter dated September 11, 2015, the solicitors for the Plaintiffs made a further attempt to negotiate separately with Aviva and continue the action against the McEwens, again with no reference to an imminent bad faith claim to be issued that very day against Aviva.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter from Ms. Quigley to Robert Sutherland and Stephanie Neate dated September 11, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 1, pages 222 and 223 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 14, pages 35 and 36].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>56. Having had the bad faith claims sprung on them, the Release that the Defendants required included a specific reference to any bad faith claims against Aviva. The Defendants' concern regarding the scope of the release has been proven by subsequent facts. On August 25, 2017, two weeks before the initial hearing of this appeal, the Appellants issued a further Statement of Claim for damages for breach of the duty of good faith in their capacity as assignees of the Trustee in Bankruptcy of the McEwens.</P>
<P>57. Having abandoned the appeal with respect to the Carrolls' ability to make a claim in the McEwens' bankruptcy, the Plaintiffs are attempting to do indirectly what they could not do directly by advancing a claim as the assignees of the McEwens against the McEwens' insurer.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Statement of Claim in action no. CV-17-00073740 issued August 25, 2017, served February 21, 2018 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 17, pages 100 to 114].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>58. The Appellants maintain that the release would have required the Plaintiffs to release an y claims for past accident benefits which had been incurred and not paid. This is not correct. There was no evidence in the record of any dispute with respect to expenses that had been incurred but not paid. Subsequent evidence demonstrates that as of September 15, 2015, the accident benefits for health care expenses incurred prior to the scheduled start date for the trial continued to be paid.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Report of Gary Principe dated December 18, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, page 1233 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 43, page 217].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>c)</N><TI><UNDER>The Plaintiffs' motion to enforce the &ldquo;settlement&rdquo;</UNDER></TI>
<P>59. The settlement fell apart with the service of the new Statement of Claim. The Plaintiffs brought a motion to enforce the settlement. Affidavits were exchanged and the matter was heard by Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015. The Plaintiffs ultimately withdrew their motion when it became clear that Justice Hackland was not going to enforce the &ldquo;settlement&rdquo;. The trial Judge, in his decision on costs, referred to the Plaintiffs' conduct in relation to the settlement as &ldquo;essentially a trick&rdquo; (see para.49 of the Reasons).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, page 32, at para.49]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>60. Justice Hackland indicated that it would have been &ldquo;so easy&rdquo; for Plaintiffs' counsel, when they accepted the Offer, to have indicated that the acceptance was without prejudice to the Plaintiffs' right to pursue a bad faith claim and then everything would have been &ldquo;on the table for both sides to know&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of hearing before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 15, page 49, line 17 to page 50, line 4].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>61. Justice Hackland also indicated that he was not going to enforce any settlement and if there was going to be a settlement, a release that corresponds with the reasonable expectations of the parties would be part of the package.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of hearing before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 15, page 51, line 32 to page 52, line 4].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Justice McLean also concluded, on the facts, that the parties did or should have understood that the offer was made on the basis that it would deal with everything outstanding, including a bad faith claim.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the Trial Judge <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, pages 28 and 30]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>62. This Court has implicitly endorsed the views and expectations of Justice Hackland and Justice McLean, particularly with respect to Releases against an insurer, as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Furthermore, the reference in the Release to claims for &ldquo;aggravated, exemplary and punitive damages or damages for alleged bad faith&rdquo; is standard language in any form of release. Indeed, the paragraph goes on to explain that the Release covers such claims for damages &ldquo;whether these claims are past, present or future, <UNDER>and whether these claims are known or unknown at the present time</UNDER>&rdquo;. (emphasis added)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 717</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Plaintiffs' Book of Authorities, Tab 7, para.37].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>63. Justice Hackland also indicated that no one would seriously suggest that the Defendants' offer would be accepted and the amount of the settlement be paid, only to be faced with instalment litigation on the bad faith issue.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of hearing before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 15, page 82, lines 9 to 22].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>64. Justice Hackland was clearly troubled by what the Plaintiffs' solicitors had done. Justice Hackland referred to the tactics and arguments of the Plaintiffs' counsel as &ldquo;a little elaborate&rdquo;. Justice McLean made a more direct finding. He called it a trick.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of hearing before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 15, page 72, lines 5 and 6]</BOLD>; Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, para.49, page 32].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>65. Justice Hackland indicated that it would be, in his opinion, &ldquo;so much better&rdquo; if the settlement went ahead as is, with a general release that would include the bad faith claim. The Appellants chose not to follow Justice Hackland's suggestion.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of hearing before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 15, page 82, lines 24 to 29].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>66. Justice Hackland offered the Plaintiffs the opportunity to withdraw their motion, which they did, leaving the entire merits of the Plaintiffs' attempt to litigate in instalments to the trial Judge.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of hearing before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 15, page 93, lines 22 to 29, page 94, lines 5 to 9, page 88, lines 17 to 19].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>67. The record of the proceedings before Justice Hackland was sealed until after the jury verdict was received. The trial Judge reviewed the complete record and there should be no suggestion that he was misled (see para.29 of the Revised Plaintiffs' Factum). The trial Judge made the following findings of fact:
<QUOTE><P>... all parties did or should have understood that that Offer was made on the basis that it would deal with everything outstanding, including a mala fide claim, (at para.36 of the Reasons)</P>
<P>... the Plaintiffs were clearly aware of what they were doing and that they were in fact taking the Defendants by surprise ... Clearly when one looks at the nature of the various offers that were made, it is without question that the situation before all parties was that the offers were made on the basis of settlement of all matters. (para.37)</P>
<P>Clearly the Court is interested in making sure that <EM>bona fide</EM> offers are treated in a <EM>bona fide</EM> manner. It helps little that a <EM>bona fide</EM> offer is made and that a party who knows or ought to know that the basis of that offer is the settlement of all issues then turns around and without notice to all parties begins another proceeding. This is not something that this Court can countenance without sanction. If such behavior was not sanctioned, then it would in this Court's view cause great difficulty with regard to obtaining settlements themselves. (para.48)</P>
<P>It is ... very concerning that ... an attempt would be made to enforce what was essentially anon-enforceable offer. Its unenforceability was caused by the fact that the party who accepted the offer intended to change the rules of the game immediately after the offer's acceptance. This was essentially a trick, (para 49)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, pages 28 and 32].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>d)</N><TI><UNDER>The Plaintiffs needlessly extended the trial</UNDER></TI>
<P>68. The second factor on which the trial Judge relied to reduce the costs claimed by the Plaintiffs was that the Plaintiffs' solicitors failure to comply with a case management order and in this and other ways needlessly extended the trial. He held that &ldquo;the behaviour of the Plaintiffs did extend the proceedings&rdquo;, for example by requiring discovery in the middle of the trial and by giving &ldquo;lip service&rdquo; to the Order of the Case Management Master, (paras. 45 and 47). These conclusions are amply supported by the record.</P>
<BLOCK5><N>(i)</N><TI><UNDER>The Case Management Order</UNDER></TI>
<P>69. Counsel for the Plaintiffs ignored the Case Management Order of Master McLeod, as he then was, dated May 26, 2014. They failed to serve any of the expert reports relied upon at trial 90 days in advance of the pre-trial, as required by the Case Management Order. The trial was set for September 8, 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Case Management Order of Master McLeod dated May 26, 2014, Exhibit Book, Vol. 3, pages 729-730 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 6, pages 38 and 39].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This put the Defendants in the position of doing their best to obtain responding reports as soon as they could.</P>
<P>70. The Plaintiffs served a liability report less than eight days before the pre-trial held on June 17, 2015. The Defendants were only able to obtain a responding report by July 29, 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Submission of the Plaintiffs' judgement and costs, Exhibit Book, Vol. 3, page 849 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 57, page 541].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>(ii)</N><TI><UNDER>The Plaintiffs' change of position on the cost of future care</UNDER></TI>
<P>71. The cost of future care was obviously one of the main issues in this case. Until a few months before trial, the Plaintiffs maintained that there had been no change in Ms. Carroll's condition as it related to future care requirements. However, three weeks before the trial was scheduled to commence, this position changed and the Plaintiffs advanced a much more expensive option. The Plaintiffs advanced a different theory for Ms. Carroll's cost of future care.</P>
<P>72. When the Respondent McEwens asked about the status of the Plaintiffs' cost of future care report in correspondence dated May 29, 2015, (approximately 3 months before trial) Plaintiffs' counsel advised that &ldquo;... I do not believe that her needs have changed substantially. We do not expect that we will be bearing the expense of updating the report until after the pre-trial&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter from Ms. Quigley to Mr. Nearing dated May 29, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 3, page 736 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 60, page 556]</BOLD>; Letter from Mr. Nearing to Ms. Quigley dated May 27, 2015, re readiness for pre-trial and trial, Exhibit Book, Vol. 3, page 731 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 20, pages 125, 126].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>73. In a letter dated June 9, 2015, Plaintiffs' counsel maintained its opposition to the Defendants' future care expert conducting an assessment and clearly indicated that the future care report being relied upon was an October 2012 report by Ms. Laura Feldt. As a result, the Defendants were only able to obtain their cost of future care report by August 17, 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter from Ms. Quigley to Mr. Nearing and Mr. Sutherland dated June 9, 2015; Exhibit Book, Vol. 3, page 738 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 21, page 130]</BOLD>; Preliminary future care needs and costs analysis report by Ms. Laura Feldt dated October 24, 2012, Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, page 1061 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 22, page 131].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>74. The very next day, three weeks before trial, the Plaintiffs served their revised cost of future care report by Carol Bierbrier dated August 18, 2015. As the Court heard from the evidence, the August 18, 2015 report by Ms. Bierbrier was not simply an update regarding Barbara Carroll's future care needs, nor was it simply a rebuttal of the Defendants' cost of future care report. It was a departure from what could be considered an update and it advanced various options, including a new and more expensive approach to Barbara Carroll's future care.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter serving Carol Bierbrier report dated August 18, 2015 Exhibit Book, Vol. 3, page 742 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 23, page 132]</BOLD>; Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, page 29, at para.41].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>75. The evidence at trial of Ms. Bierbrier confirmed that counsel's representation that there had been no substantial change in Barbara Carroll's needs was incorrect. Ms. Bierbrier testified that there had been an improvement over the last number of years (i.e. since the October 2012 report) and that maybe now the time was right to proceed with intensive treatment that had not been recommended in earlier reports.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Trial transcripts (Carol Bierbrier) September 30, 2015, page 88, lines 7 to 25 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 19, page 130]</BOLD>; Trial transcripts (Carol Bierbrier) October 1, 2015, page 15, line 17 to page 16, line 3 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 20, pages 132 and 133].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> According to Ms. Bierbrier, the improvements in Ms. Carroll's function had occurred over time and not just after Plaintiffs' counsel letter dated May 29, 2015.</P>
<P>76. The Plaintiffs suggest that annual future care costs claims decreased from the October 2011 report to the August 2015 report. Specific numbers are given but the &ldquo;various options provided&rdquo; are not quantified.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Revised Appellants' Factum, para.51.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>77. Plaintiffs' counsel failed to mention that one of the &ldquo;various options provided&rdquo; in the new report and advanced at trial was a much more expensive option. The new report suggested as an option that Ms. Carroll move into an apartment in the retirement facility wing of her residence with a 24-hour a day/7-days a week attendant care at a cost of $130,000 a year.</P>
<P>78. This new option increased the total annual recurring costs for personal care services from $136,733.26 to $195,100.00. This increased the total annual recurring costs to approximately $276,652.85, making it the most expensive cost of future care scenario presented by the Plaintiffs to the jury.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Future care summary report for tort October 24, 2012 (Affidavit of Maryse Larouche, November 30, 2015), Exhibit Book, Vol. 4, page 1143 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 58, page 554]</BOLD>; Future care summary report for tort August 18, 2015 (Affidavit of Maryse Larouche, November 30, 2015) <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 59, page 555].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>79. The Plaintiffs did not quantify Mrs. Carroll's future care claims until September 8, 2015 (the day trial was scheduled to commence), when they served an accountant's report dated August 31, 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email serving Principe Report dated September 8, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 3, page 759 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 24, page 133]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>80. The trial Judge found that the Plaintiffs had changed their position on the cost of future care shortly before trial and that the Plaintiffs' solicitors' representation that her needs had not changed substantially was not correct. This factual finding is supported by the record.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge at para.41 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, page 29].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>(iii)</N><TI><UNDER>Motion for an Order to conduct a brief examination for discovery of Barbara Carroll</UNDER></TI>
<P>81. The trial Judge found that the Plaintiffs' conduct had required an adjournment in the middle of the trial because shortly before trial, the Plaintiffs changed their previous position and indicated that, contrary to what had been said earlier, Ms. Carroll herself would be called as a witness.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge at para.42 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, page 29].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This necessitated an adjournment of the trial for a brief discovery of Ms. Carroll.</P>
<P>82. Previous correspondence from the Plaintiffs' counsel indicated that Barbara Carroll would not testify at the trial because of her inability to provide useful information. As a result, counsel for the Defendants did not pursue an examination for discovery of Barbara Carroll.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Sutherland sworn November 20, 2014, Exhibit Book, Vol. 1, page 12 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 26, pages 136 to 138]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>83. Barbara Carroll was not on the list of witnesses submitted by the Plaintiffs in their pretrial conference brief.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Erin Durant sworn September 4, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 1, page 14, <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 25, pages 134 and 135]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> September 3, 2015 (i.e. 5 days before trial) was the first time Plaintiffs' counsel advised that Barbara Carroll would be testifying at trial.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Erin Durant sworn September 4, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 1, page 14, <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 25, pages 134 to 135].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>84. During the submissions on the motion to compel a brief discovery of Barbara Carroll, counsel for the Plaintiffs, indicated as follows:
<QUOTE><P>We're now at trial. We're not even at the eve of a trial, and our office has elected to call Ms. Carroll. We have indicated, as Ms. Quigley's affidavit says, it's not going to add anything particularly useful to the trial ...<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Trial transcripts, September 9, 2015, Submissions of counsel for the Plaintiffs <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 11, page 78, lines 22 to 26].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>85. The trial Judge correctly summarized the evidence with respect to the Motion to compel Barbara Carroll's examination for discovery and exercised his discretion in favour of the Defendants who, otherwise, would have had no idea what Barbara Carroll was going to say in light of the recent decision to put her in the witness box.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean on Motion, Trial transcripts, September 9, 2014, page 120, line 30 to page 124, line 2, <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 27, pages 139 to 143].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>86. The trial Judge correctly concluded that a brief discovery was required due to representations by Plaintiffs' counsel that Barbara Carroll would not be testifying and she and her counsel had changed their minds.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean, at paras.42 and 45 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1 Tab 4, pages 29 to 31].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>e)</N><TI><UNDER>Conclusion on Costs</UNDER></TI>
<P>87. The Plaintiffs' maximum recovery in tort, due to the McEwens' bankruptcy, was $2,000,000 plus costs. They were offered $2,150,000 plus collateral benefits believed to be worth $988,000 and subsequently valued at somewhere between $749,000 and $813,000.</P>
<P>88. Rather than take the offer, they took the risk of proceeding to trial. The three significant &ldquo;trial risks&rdquo; were liability, the Defendants' motion for an assignment and the trial Judge's exercise of his discretion with respect to costs. All three issues went badly for the Plaintiffs.</P>
<P>89. On the facts of this case, the trial Judge made a reasonable exercise of his discretion by significantly reducing the Plaintiffs' costs.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ISSUES AND ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>The trial Judge's decision to grant the assignment was grounded in the evidence. supported by the case law and should be upheld</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><N>a)</N><TI><UNDER>The evidence satisfied the onus of proof in <EM>Gilbert v. South</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>90. Upon considering the evidence at trial and the evidence adduced on the costs hearing, the Court was satisfied, based upon the substantial evidence given by caregivers and Barbara Carroll's occupational therapist, that there was little doubt that all of the out standing amounts for health care expenses under the Statutory Accident Benefits (&ldquo;SABs&rdquo;) would be received. The trial Judge correctly concluded that the evidence satisfied the strict onus of proof set out by this Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF>. The record the trial Judge had before him appears to have been much more complete than the record that was before the trial Judge in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, paras.9, 10 and 11]</BOLD>; <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC><CITE>2015 ONCA 712</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 4]</BOLD>; <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 3485</CITE><PARANUM>6</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 3]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>91. Section 224 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> defines health care as follows:
<QUOTE><DEF><DEFP><TERM>&ldquo;Health Care&rdquo;</TERM> includes all goods and services for which payment provided by the medical, rehabilitation and attendant care benefits provided for in the statutory accident benefits schedule.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Section 224 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, supra, at Respondent McEwens' Factum, Schedule B, page 37.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></DEFP></DEF></QUOTE></P>
<P>92. The Plaintiffs have not been able to point to any health care expense addressed in the evidence adduced at trial that does not meet the definition of health care contained in the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>.</P>
<P>93. Section 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> sets out the law with respect to collateral benefits. Section 267.8(9) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> contains clear mandatory wording that require a plaintiff to hold amounts received after the trial of the action for statutory accident benefits in trust.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Section 267.8(9) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c.I-8 at Respondent McEwens' Factum, Schedule B, page 39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>94. The applicable provision in issue at the trial of this action and on this appeal is section 267.8(12) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> which provides as follows, with respect to the assignment of future collateral benefits:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(12)</N><SSECP>The court that heard and determined the action for loss or damage from bodily injury or death arising directly or indirectly from the use or operation of the automobile, on motion, may order that, subject to any conditions the court considers just,
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>the plaintiff who recovered damages in the action assign to the defendants or the defendants' insurers all rights in respect of all payments to which the plaintiff who recovered damages is entitled in respect of the incident after the trial of the action ...
<SPARA><N>(iv)</N><SPARAP>for statutory accident benefits in respect of expenses for health care ...<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Section 267.8(12) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, supra, at Respondent McEwens' Factum, Schedule B, page 40.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></SPARAP></SPARA></PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>95. The purpose of this assignment provision, and similar legislation, is to prevent double recovery while ensuring that the claimant is fully protected.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See, e.g., <CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>[2003] 2 S.C.R. 652</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 1]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>96. The provisions require the judgment to be paid in order to get the assignment. This protects claimants from any shortfall in recovery. In other words, there is no risk that a plaintiff will receive less than what was awarded at the trial. The Defendants have repeatedly acknowledged that if they get the assignment, they are prepared to pay the judgment in full.</P>
<P>97. The Appellants have refused to agree to the assignment. Their preferred approach appears to be that the judgment has to be paid in full before the motion for an assignment can be argued. This is impractical. The proper approach is to address the assignment issue with the trial Judge, at the conclusion of the trial.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No.1678</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>109 O.A.C. 102</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para.10 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 2].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>98. Barbara Carroll suffered a catastrophic impairment as that term is defined in the Statutory Accident Benefits Schedule (&ldquo;SABS&rdquo;). There was no evidence at trial of any issues with respect to the benefits being paid. Barbara Carroll is assured of receiving the full amount available for SABS health care expenses for her future care. This certainty distinguishes this case from other cases in which an assignment was not granted.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Chrappa</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM>, at para.27 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 2]</BOLD>; <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC><CITE>2015 ONCA 712</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 4]</BOLD>; <CASEREF><SOC>Hoang v. Vincentini</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 6644</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 5].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>99. The jury's award for damages for cost of future care was for health care expenses. The assignment ordered by the trial Judge is for health care expenses. The two mirror each other. The legislation and the case law require deducting apples from apples and oranges from oranges. It does not require deducting McIntosh apples from only McIntosh apples or deducting Sunkist oranges from only Sunkist oranges. The matching and deductions set out in the legislation are simply not as narrow as suggested by the Appellants.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. Hagerman Estate</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 1673</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>38 O.R. (3d) 659</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at page 679 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 6, at page 679]</BOLD>; <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM> at para.44 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 4]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>b)</N><TI><UNDER>The &ldquo;Silos&rdquo; approach in <EM>Basandra</EM> is consistent with the current legislation</UNDER></TI>
<P>100. In <CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court recently confirmed that the only &ldquo;matching&rdquo; of apples to apples, oranges to oranges required under Section 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> is between the <UNDER>type</UNDER> of benefits received and the <UNDER>type</UNDER> of damages awarded:
<QUOTE><P>An award can only be reduced by a corresponding statutory accident benefit, on a benefit by benefit basis, under Section 267.8 of the Insurance Act. This reflects the concept that &ldquo;apples should be deducted from apples, and oranges from oranges&rdquo;. For example, an award for housekeeping can be reduced by a housekeeping benefit, but not by a medical rehabilitation benefit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC><CITE>[2016] O.J. No. 1749</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2016 ONCA 251</CITE><PARANUM>4 and 5</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 7].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>101. Consistent with the decision of this Court in <EM>Basandra</EM>, the Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> recognized that there is nothing in the wording of the language of the current legislation that would require any further subdivision of statutory benefits beyond the &ldquo;silos&rdquo; created by section 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Basandra</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at paras.4 and 5 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 7]</BOLD> and <CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716</CITE><PARANUM>35</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>102. The trial Judge's decision is consistent with the assignment provisions in section 267.8(12) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>.</P>
<P>103. The trial Judge's decision is also consistent with the Supreme Court of Canada's decision in <EM>Gurniak</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at paras.70 and 71; <CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>[2003] 2 SCR 652</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>104. In <CASEREF><SOC>Mikolic v. Tanguay</SOC></CASEREF>, the Divisional Court reversed a trial Judge's decision not to award an assignment and held that the specific wording of Section 267.8(1) and (4) only requires the Court to carry out limited matching when determining the deductibility of statutory benefits.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mikolic v. Tanguay</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 71</CITE><COURTJUR>Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras.32, 44, 45, 46 and 47 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 9].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>105. This case involves none of the debate about matching past and future accident benefits with an award at trial for past and future damages. In this case, the damages claimed and the accident benefits for health care expenses are all with respect to future care claims.</P>
<P>106. On the facts of this case, there is no tort claim for past health care expenses so there is nothing from which to make deductions. There is nothing unfair about the trial Judge's granting the assignment. The Plaintiff receives full compensation without double recovery.</P>
<P>107. Neither does this case present a difficulty with respect to any time limit on the availability of the benefits. The benefits are available for the remainder of Barbara Carroll's life. By paying the judgment in full, it is the Defendants, not the Plaintiffs, who assume any risk with respect to Barbara Carroll's mortality.</P>
<P>108. The trial Judge considered all of the evidence, all of the case law, and carried out the matching to the extent required by the legislation and the case law.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge at paras.7 to 12 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, at pages 20 to 22].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>c)</N><TI><UNDER>There is no need to overturn this Court's Decisions in <EM>Bannon</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>109. There is no need to reverse this Court's decision in <EM>Bannon</EM>. As this Court noted in the motion for a re-hearing of <EM>El-Khodr, Bannon</EM> was decided in the context of the previous legislative framework.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716</CITE><PARANUM>45&ndash;54</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>; <CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2018 ONCA 66</CITE><PARANUM>4 and 5</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 10]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>110. In <EM>El-Khodr</EM>, this Court reviewed how the relevant provisions of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> have evolved. This evolution and, in particular, the provisions of section 267. 8(9) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> (the &ldquo;Trust&rdquo; provision) and (12) (the &ldquo;Assignment&rdquo; provision) have achieved a rational balancing of the two competing principles of avoiding double recovery and avoiding under-compensation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716</CITE><PARANUM>24&ndash;80</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>111. Past provisions of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> arguably exposed a claimant to a risk of under-compensation. Section 239(2) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, provided for a general release &ldquo;... to the extent of payments made or available to the claimant ...&rdquo; without specifying the nature of the payment, whether it be for past or future income, past or future care, and so on. In other words, there was no statutory requirement for matching.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras.38 and 39 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>112. In the past, <EM>Cox and Carter</EM> orders were used to address uncertainties with respect to future benefits. In <CASEREF><SOC>Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court upheld the trial Judge's imposition of a <EM>Cox and Carter</EM> Order to avoid the prospect of double recovery.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para.40. <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>; <CASEREF><SOC>Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC><CITE>[1998] 38 O.R. (3d) 651</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at paras.27 and 31 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 2].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>113. Provisions were arguably even &ldquo;harsher&rdquo; for a claimant under section 267(1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, in that, it mandated that the damage award be reduced by the present value of &ldquo;any no fault benefits to which the person is entitled&rdquo;; again, without concern as to which particular benefits were being used to reduce the damage award. Here again, there was no statutory requirement for matching.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras.41 and 46 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>114. However strict the &ldquo;apples to apples&rdquo; and &ldquo;oranges to oranges&rdquo; matching requirement was applied by the Court in <EM>Bannon</EM>, the more recent amendments to the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> have done away with the policy rationale for whatever strict matching requirements were previously required by the Courts. With the enactment of section 267.8(8) and (12), the legislation now directs how the matching is to take place.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras.53 and 54 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>115. This Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> and <EM>Basandra</EM> has recognized that section 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, enacted in 1996, codifies the common law principle that a plaintiff should not recover twice for the same kind of loss arising from the same accident.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para.33 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>; <EM>Basandra</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 18 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 7].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>d)</N><TI><UNDER><EM>Gilbert v. South</EM> is distinguishable from this case</UNDER></TI>
<P>116. The Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> recognized that the facts in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> were different than those in <EM>Gilbert</EM> such that there was little or no risk of under-compensation due to an assignment of future statutory benefits.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at para.73 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>117. Many aspects of the record that satisfied this Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> apply to the facts of this case:
<P1>a) The Appellant Barbara Lynn Carroll has been designated catastrophically impaired;</P1>
<P1>b) The ten-year temporal limitation for SABs in <EM>Gilbert</EM> does not arise; and</P1>
<P1>c) There were no benefits for which the assignment was requested that were not covered by SABs.</P1></P>
<P>118. The record before the trial Judge in this case was very different than the record before the trial Judge in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South et al.</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 3485</CITE><PARANUM>10&ndash;15, 18, 19 and 22</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 3].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Whether it be the &ldquo;strict&rdquo; matching required in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF> or the &ldquo;less stringent&rdquo; matching of silos applied in <EM>Basandra</EM>, the facts of this case meet either test.</P>
<P>119. The assignment granted by the trial Judge and the assignment in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> were both conditional upon the judgment being paid in full. Pending the resolution of this Appeal, the Respondents have paid the Appellants $2,000,000. If this court upholds the assignment granted by the trial Judge, there is absolutely no risk that the Appellants will not receive full compensation. The risk is completely on the Respondents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at paras.78&ndash;80 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>There is no basis in fact or in law to interfere with the trial Judge's exercise of his discretion in awarding the Plaintiffs a reduced amount of costs</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><N>a)</N><TI><UNDER>The Plaintiffs do not meet the high standard required to grant leave</UNDER></TI>
<P>120. Awarding and fixing costs is an exercise of the trial Judge's discretion. It is to be is afforded significant deference. Leave to appeal a costs order is granted sparingly and only where there are strong grounds to believe that the lower court erred.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>McNaughton Automotive Ltd. v. Co-Operative General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>[2008] O.J. No. 5040</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2008 ONCA 597</CITE><PARANUM>23 to 27</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 11]</BOLD>; <CASEREF><SOC>Feinstein v. Freedman</SOC><YEAR>2014</YEAR><CITE>119 O.R. (3d) 385</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2014 ONCA 205</CITE><PARANUM>52</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 12].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>121. In the event that leave is granted, a Court should set aside a costs award on Appeal only if the trial Judge has made an error in principle or if the costs award is plainly wrong.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton v. Open Window Bakery</SOC><CITE>[2004] 1 S.C.R. 303</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2003] S.C.J. No. 72</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>2004 SCC 9</CITE><PARANUM>27</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 13].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>122. The trial Judge reduced the Plaintiffs' costs for the following three main reasons: (1) the &ldquo;settlement&rdquo;, (2) the Plaintiffs' breach of the case management order and (3) little or no benefit was to be gained by proceeding to trial.</P>
<P>123. Misconduct of a party or miscarriage in procedure are grounds for the trial Judge to exercise his or her discretion when awarding costs.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Saleh v. Nibel</SOC><CITE>[2015] O.J. No. 2987</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2015 ONSC 3680</CITE><PARANUM>31 to 37, 89, 91, 102 and 107</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 14].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>124. The trial Judge made no error in principle. Leave should not be granted.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>b)</N><TI><UNDER>The trial Judge thoroughly considered the record of the aborted settlement and the Plaintiffs' attempt to enforce it</UNDER></TI>
<P>125. The trial Judge started his reasons with the following comment:
<QUOTE><P>Sometimes interpretation of costs in a jury verdict can be more complicated than the trial itself. This is such a case.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4 at page 17].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>126. The trial Judge found that, on the facts, it was without doubt that the Defendants' offers, including the all-inclusive offer of $2,150,000 dated September 11, 2015 were made on the basis that everything would be settled between the parties and any settlement would end all litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4 at page 28].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>127. The trial Judge presided over this trial for 8 weeks and was in the best position to appreciate the dynamics of the trial. He was satisfied that the Plaintiffs were, in fact, by accepting the offer and immediately serving the $2,000,000 Statement of Claim for bad faith, taking the Defendants by surprise. The trial Judge described the Plaintiffs' tactics as &ldquo;a trick&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4 at page 28].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>128. The trial Judge correctly held that the actions of the Plaintiffs was something the Court &ldquo;cannot countenance without sanction&rdquo;. The Court recognized the unnecessary complexity that the Plaintiffs' actions would inject into settlement negotiations.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 1 at page 32]</BOLD>; Transcript of hearing before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 16, page 100, lines 5 and 6].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>129. One can only imagine what would have happened had the Defendants accepted the Plaintiffs' offer dated September 9, 2015, which offered to settle &ldquo;all damages and pre&mdash;judgment interest&rdquo; and a specific figure for fees and disbursements without reference to the words &ldquo;in this proceeding&rdquo; and followed it up with a new Statement of Claim for bad faith. Would the Defendants have been able to insist on a release that included bad faith claims, or would the Plaintiffs' have argued that acceptance of the offer only applied to the existing litigation? The mischief caused by the Plaintiffs' actions and the uncertainty &bull; it would bring to settlement negotiations is obvious.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Offer to Settle of Plaintiffs dated September 9, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 1, page 191 and 192 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 31, pages 167 and 168].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>130. Justice Hackland and Justice McLean were both of the view that the reasonable (objective) expectations of counsel were that accepting a $2.15 million offer to settle with no assignment of accident benefits of approximately $900,000 would have ended any and all disputes between the parties.</P>
<P>131. With respect, the Appellants' submissions attempt to turn this issue on its head. The Defendants' expectation of a standard full and final release, including any and all other claims, was, as suggested by Justice Hackland and held by Justice McLean, a reasonable expectation.</P>
<P>132. The &ldquo;mischief&rdquo; caused, on the facts of this case, was the attempt by the Appellants' counsel to rely on a technical argument, i.e. a literal interpretation of the words &ldquo;in this proceeding&rdquo;, to force the Defendants into a settlement for $2,150,000 and one minute later, issuing a $2,000,000 claim for damages for bad faith and punitive damages.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of hearing before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 6, Tab 223 at page 1892, line 32 to page 1893, line 4, page 1923, lines 9 to 22, <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 15, page 51, line 32 to page 52, line 4].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>133. The trial Judge correctly held that the Plaintiffs knew, or should have known, that the Defendants' joint offer of $2,150,000 all-inclusive was intended to settle all claims between the parties.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, page 28].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>c)</N><TI><UNDER>The Plaintiffs Breached the Case Management Order</UNDER></TI>
<P>134. Failure to comply with a case management order has been held to be grounds for depriving a party of costs. In <EM>Saleh</EM>, Justice F.L. Meyers said the following with respect to breaching a trial management order:
<QUOTE><P>The civil justice system in Ontario is broken. It does not fulfill the goals of providing efficient, affordable, proportionate access to courts for the fair resolution of civil cases: <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE></CASEREF>. It is too slow and expensive to meet the needs of most Ontarians</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>In this case, Justice Stinson assisted the parties to ready this matter for trial. At a pre-trial conference on December 3, 2014, he made a comprehensive trial management order. He ordered two of the Plaintiffs treating physicians to provide copies of their up-to-date treatment records. Counsels were required to review their list of proposed witnesses to confirm that the trial could be completed in the available ten day window behind which a new trial date would have been required.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Saleh v. Nibel</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>Supra</EM>, aff'd <CASEREF><CITE>2018 ONSC 452</CITE><COURTJUR>Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras.21 and 23 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 14].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>135. Barbara Carroll's solicitors knowingly and willingly breached Master McLeod's order dated May 26, 2014. They consciously did not obtain an updated cost of a future care report in advance of the pre-trial and instead represented to the Defendants that not much had changed with respect to Barbara Carroll's care. Their own expert testified that this was not the case.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Case Management Order of Master McLeod dated May 26, 2014, Exhibit Book, Vol. 3, pages 729 - 730 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 6, pages 38 and 39]</BOLD>; Letter serving Carol Bierbrier report dated August 18, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 3, page 742 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 23, page 132]</BOLD>; Letter from Ms. Quigley to Mr. Nearing dated May 29, 2015, Exhibit Book, Vol. 3, page 736 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 60, page 556]</BOLD>; Trial transcripts (Carol Bierbrier) September 30, 2015, page 88, lines 7 to 25 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 19, page 130].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>136. The trial Judge had the benefit of hearing all of the evidence. He correctly identified that the new cost of future care report served on August 18, 2015, was not an update, but a new plan that contemplated more vigorous therapy.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge at paras.41 and 43 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, pages 29 and 30].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>d)</N><TI><UNDER>The trial Judge correctly identified that the Plaintiffs achieved little, if any, benefit by proceeding to trial</UNDER></TI>
<P>137. Justice McLean accurately concluded that not only was virtually all the money available put forward by the Defendants, there was no prospect of the Plaintiffs doing much better than the terms of the September 11, 2015 Joint Offer to Settle for $2,150,000 with no assignment of the outstanding accident benefits for health care expenses. The Plaintiffs were aware of the risk that the Defendants would seek an assignment of the health care expenses at the conclusion of the trial.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge at paras.8, 27, 45 <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, pages 21, 27 and 45].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Plaintiffs were also aware of the risk with respect to the liability issue.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of hearing before Justice Hackland on September 15, 2015, <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 15, page 70, lines 27 to 32].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>138. A review of the complete record demonstrates that the most contentious issue in the ultimately unsuccessful settlement discussions was the Plaintiffs' costs. The Plaintiffs risked the sure thing of a settlement offer worth in excess, by anyone's calculations, of $2.8 million all inclusive. Instead, they are left with a jury verdict of $2.6 million, less the value of the assignment of health care expenses valued somewhere between $750,000 and $830,000.</P>
<P>139. The net benefit to the Plaintiffs of the verdict, once the assignment of accident benefits of between $750,000 and $830,000 is taken into account, ranges from $1,770,000 to $1,850,000, depending upon the present value figure placed upon the accident benefits for health care expenses. These figures are well below the value of the Defendants' offer of $2,150,000 with no assignment for health care expenses.</P>
<P>140. At the end of the day, the only thing left for the Plaintiffs to recover over and above the offer to settle was costs. As indicated previously, $2,000,000 plus costs was the Defendants' total exposure. The Plaintiffs had 2 choices: accept $2,150,000 with no assignment and no risk, or go to trial and face the risks of the liability issue and the request for an assignment.</P>
<P>141. In the result, regardless of which valuation is accepted regarding the present value of the future accident benefits, the Plaintiffs did worse than the $2.15 million offer to settle.</P>
<P>142. The Plaintiffs decided to go through an 8-week trial in which they had very little to gain and much to lose. An award of $375,000 in costs easily meets the proportionality principle expressed by this Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Elbakhiet v. Palmer</SOC></CASEREF>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Elbakhiet v. Palmer</SOC><CITE>[2014] O.J. No. 3302</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2014 ONCA 544</CITE><PARANUM>38</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 15].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>143. In the face of all this, the trial judge made no reviewable error in applying a significant reduction of the Plaintiffs' cost demands of $795,000.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>144. The Respondent McEwens respectfully request that this Honorable Court:
<P1>a) Dismiss the Plaintiffs' appeal of the trial Judge's award of an assignment;</P1>
<P1>b) Deny the Plaintiffs' request for leave to appeal the trial Judge's costs decision; and</P1>
<P1>c) Award the Respondent McEwens their costs of this appeal.</P1></P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED, this 27<SUP>th</SUP> day of March, 2018.</P>
<P>&ellip35; Kevin P. Nearing</P>
