<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>Overview</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. Pursuant to the case management direction of Justice MacFarland, the Respondents, Aviva Canada Inc. and Pilot Insurance Company (hereinafter, &ldquo;these Respondents&rdquo;), submit the within supplementary responding factum, to be read together with all previously filed facta, for the consideration of the five-member panel hearing the within appeal.</P>
<P>2. Specifically, these Respondents address herein the manner in which future collateral benefits are to be handled at trial pursuant to the assignment mechanism set out in the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> (hereinafter, &ldquo;the <EM>Act</EM>&rdquo;), in light of this Court's decisions in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South and El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC></CASEREF>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC><CITE>[2015] O.J No. 5573</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont.C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 5; <CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab. 9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>3. For the purposes of the within appeal, the dichotomy between <EM>Gilbert</EM> and <EM>El-Khodr</EM> is of no moment because, on the facts, the approach set out in both authorities is met.</P>
<P>4. However, given the position taken in the plaintiff appellants' filed factum, and these Respondents' understanding that the panel is convening to address the state of the law generally with respect to the deduction and trust / assignment mechanisms set out in the <EM>Act</EM>, these Respondents submit that <EM>El-Khodr</EM> is the proper approach in the current legislative scheme.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II"><UNDER>The Policy Rationale Requiring Strict Matching Is No Longer Applicable</UNDER></TI>
<P>5. The present flux in the law with respect to the assignment of future collateral benefits arises from conflating two different iterations of the <EM>Act</EM> governing automobile insurance regimes and an unfounded risk of under compensation to a plaintiff where an assignment is granted</P>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>i.</EM></N><TI><EM>Overview of Deduction of Collateral Benefits</EM></TI>
<P>6. From June 22, 1990 onwards, s.231b (now s.267(1)) of the <EM>Act</EM> eliminated the collateral source rule in automobile cases to allow the deduction of collateral sources in the awarding of damages for personal injuries arising from automobile accidents (hereinafter, the &ldquo;OMPP regime&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>s.267.1 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, 1990, c. I.8, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Responding Factum, Schedule B, pg. 13</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. In the OMPP regime, no specific matching was legislatively mandated between the collateral benefit to be deducted and the head of damage awarded. There was no trust or assignment mechanism available to deal with future benefits which were simply to be present valued and deducted in appropriate circumstances. This led to an understandable concern about deducting the present value of future benefits that the plaintiff may never receive. It was under these circumstances, where the plaintiff bore the risk of undercompensation, that the trilogy of cases, <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. Mc.Neely, Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Cugliari v. White</SOC></CASEREF>, was rendered.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. Mc.Neely</SOC><CITE>1998 CanLII 4486</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 1 at p.29 citing <CASEREF><SOC>Jang v. Jang</SOC><YEAR>1991</YEAR><CITE>54 B.C.L.R. (2d) 121</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 1678</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 1; <CASEREF><SOC>Cugliari v. White</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 1628</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. In <EM>Bannon</EM>, the Court relied on the approach taken by the British Columbia Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Jang v. Jang</SOC></CASEREF> and required accident benefits to be deducted from a head of damage akin to that for which the benefits were intended to compensate. With respect to future benefits, their present value was to be deducted only when entitlement was &ldquo;beyond dispute&rdquo; and a plaintiff qualified in &ldquo;every aspect&rdquo; for the future payments.</P>
<P>9. In <EM>Chrappa</EM>, also set in the OMPP scheme, it was found that where the required certainty of future benefits was not demonstrated, the problem of potential double recovery was resolved by imposing trust/assignment obligations on the plaintiff.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 1678</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> affirming <CASEREF><SOC>Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC><CITE>[1996] O.J. No. 1667</CITE><COURTJUR>Gen. Div.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at pg. 3, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tabs 1 &amp; 2</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. In 1996, the Legislature amended the <EM>Act</EM> (hereinafter, &ldquo;the Bill 59/198 regime&rdquo;) for accidents occurring from November 1, 1996 onwards and codified the deduction matching principles developed in the <EM>Bannon</EM> trilogy. For example, s.267.8(4) of the <EM>Act</EM> created a matching &ldquo;silo&rdquo; which required that benefits for health care expenses be deducted from damages for health care expenses. There was, and is, no other subject or temporal matching required by statute.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>s.267.8(1), (4) &amp; (6) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, 1990, c. I.8, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Responding Factum, Schedule B, pg. 13</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>11. Since the legislative amendments, case law eventually and appropriately settled on an easing of the strict subject / temporal matching requirement where collateral benefits are to be deducted.</P>
<P>12. In <CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC></CASEREF>, a majority of the Supreme Court of Canada held that specific matching between the benefit received under the BC accident benefits scheme and the tort damages award was not required beyond the broad &ldquo;similarity&rdquo; stipulated in the BC statute in order to effect an appropriate deduction.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>35</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. Shortly thereafter, this Court came to a similar conclusion in <CASEREF><SOC>Cummings v. Douglas</SOC></CASEREF> where all benefits received by the plaintiff for past and future income losses were to be deducted from the global (past and future) award for loss of income.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Cummings (Litigation, Guardian of) v. Douglas</SOC><CITE>2007 ONCA, 615</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot. Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 4</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> No strict <UNDER>temporal</UNDER> matching was required.</P>
<P>14. Subsequent cases, including at the appellate level, have followed this approach. In <CASEREF><SOC>Mikolic v. Tanguay</SOC></CASEREF>, similarly no strict <UNDER>qualitative</UNDER> matching was required. Instead, the Divisional Court properly deducted accident benefits received for past and future attendant care and medical/rehabilitation benefits from the award for future care costs, resulting in a nil award.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mikolic v Tanguay</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 8196</CITE><COURTJUR>Div.Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras. 44&ndash;47, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 5; <CASEREF><SOC>Foniciello v. Bendall and Acculine</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 1119</CITE><PARANUM>112</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 6</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. This Court affirmed the more relaxed matching approach in the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC></CASEREF> where benefits received for medical/rehabilitation, attendant care and housekeeping (approximately $146,000) were deducted from the jury award of $105,000 for past and future care, medical/rehabilitation and housekeeping, resulting in a nil award.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 251</CITE></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. The correctness of this relaxed matching approach was most recently reiterated by this Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>[55] For these reasons, s. 267.8(1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> requires deduction of all income replacement SABs, and all payments in settlement of claims for income replacement SABs, that the plaintiff receives before trial from the total of all damages awarded at trial for past and future income loss arising from the same incident.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 717</CITE><PARANUM>48&ndash;55</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 7</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>ii.</EM></N><TI><EM>Overview of Assignment of Collateral Benefits</EM></TI>
<P>17. The Bill 59/198 regime also introduced trust and assignment provisions in s.267.8(9) through (12) of the <EM>Act</EM>, setting out the same matching categories or &ldquo;silos&rdquo; for an assignment as those required for a deduction.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Namely, income loss; expenses for health care and other pecuniary losses, section 267.8 (9)&ndash;(12), <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, 1990, c. I.8, at Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Responding Factum, Schedule B, pg.16</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. In statutorily codifying the trust/assignment approach developed in <CASEREF><SOC>Cox v. Carter</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Cox v. Carter</SOC><YEAR>1976</YEAR><CITE>13 O.R., (2d) 717</CITE><COURTJUR>H.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary, Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 7</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, and provided as the &ldquo;solution&rdquo; in <EM>Chrappa</EM>, the Legislature shifted the risk of future entitlement (or non-payment) from plaintiff to defendant. If the plaintiff does not receive any collateral benefit payments after trial, the defendant simply does not receive an offset (or repayment) of damages already paid to the plaintiff.</P>
<P>19. The <EM>Act</EM>, now a complete statutory code, strikes an equitable balance between the risk of undercompensation to a plaintiff and the unfairness of double recovery to a defendant.</P>
<P>20. Nevertheless, two decades after <EM>Bannon</EM> and in the context of a materially different legislative scheme, this Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF> again considered the <EM>risk</EM> of undercompensation to a plaintiff where an assignment was sought by the defendant. The strict matching approach in <EM>Bannon</EM> and <EM>Chrappa</EM> was followed, despite those decisions arising from the OMPP regime and despite the amendments to the <EM>Act</EM> in the interim, namely the codification of matching &ldquo;silos&rdquo; from <EM>Bannon</EM> and the imposition of trust/assignment provisions as it relates to future benefits from <CASEREF><SOC>Cox v. Carter</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>21. The matching approach followed by this Court in <EM>Cummings</EM> was not considered in <EM>Gilbert</EM>. The approach of the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Gurniak</EM>, which overruled the <EM>Jang</EM> strict matching approach followed in <EM>Bannon</EM>, was also not considered.</P>
<P>22. The finding in <EM>Chrappa</EM>, that where the required certainty of future benefits was not demonstrated, the problem of potential double recovery was resolved by imposing trust/assignment obligations on the plaintiff, was also seemingly overlooked.</P>
<P>23. Strict certainty of entitlement is misplaced where a trust/assignment is concerned, as is a strict matching approach beyond that mandated by statute. In short, <EM>Gilbert</EM> cannot be reconciled with <EM>Gurniak</EM> and erroneously relied on <EM>Bannon</EM>. As such, <EM>Gilbert</EM> is not tenable at law and should be formally overruled. The approach in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> should prevail.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>iii.</EM></N><TI><EM>The &ldquo;Silos&rdquo; in the Act are Deliberately Broad and Fairly Defined</EM></TI>
<P>24. In Ontario, the <EM>Act</EM> has undergone amendments since the introduction of the &ldquo;silos&rdquo; in the 1996 reforms, yet the breadth of the &ldquo;silos&rdquo; has not changed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Recent examples include, Bill 213 assented to December 9, 2002; Bill 186 assented to December 13, 2002; Bill 40 assented to June 24, 2004; Bill 18 assented to December 15, 2005; Bill 16 assented to May 18, 2010; Bill 135 assented to December 8, 2010; Bill 173 assented to May 12, 2011; Bill 65 assented to June 13, 2013; Bill 15 assented to November 20, 2014; Bill 91 assented to June 4, 2015; Bill 186 assented to June 9, 2016</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. In <EM>Gurniak</EM>, the Supreme Court of Canada, as part of its analysis, relied on the fact that the BC Legislature did not introduce an explicit matching requirement into the statute, when it could readily have done so.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>45</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Similarly, in <CASEREF><SOC>Madill v. Chu</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court of Canada directed that the degree of matching required should be no more than is required by the plain meaning of the legislation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Madill v. Chu</SOC><CITE>[1977] 2 SCC 400</CITE><PAGENUM>at pgs. 409-410</PAGENUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>26. A strict level of temporal and qualitative matching is not mandated by the <EM>Act</EM>. To find otherwise would theoretically permit a plaintiff avoid an assignment for physiotherapy by seeking out (post-trial) a similar treatment modality, like chiropractic care, or, if after having been awarded damages for Tylenol #3 (with a corresponding qualitatively specific trust/assignment being granted), a plaintiff instead takes Advil. Such an approach promotes the likelihood of double recovery.</P>
<P>27. These Respondents submit that this Court should follow the approach in <EM>Madill</EM> and <EM>Gurniak</EM>, and safeguard the Legislature's intent to prevent double recovery in a manner that is simple, expedient and effective. To require a more strict temporal or qualitative matching than is required by statute is to adopt a scheme which facilitates the potential for double recovery.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III"><UNDER>The Plaintiffs' Interpretation of the <EM>Act</EM> Is Flawed</UNDER></TI>
<P>28. The words of the <EM>Act</EM> are to be read in their entire context. It is a well-established principle of statutory interpretation that the Legislature does not intend to produce consequences which would render a statute illogical or incoherent, or which would be incompatible with other provisions or with the object of the legislative enactment.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Bell ExpressVu Limited Partnership v. Rex</SOC><CITE>[2002] 2 S.C.R. 559</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2002 SCC 42</CITE><PAGENUM>at pg. 561</PAGENUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 9; <CASEREF><SOC>Rizzo &amp; Rizzo Shoes Ltd. (Re)</SOC><CITE>[1998] 1 S.C.R. 27</CITE><PAGENUM>at pg. 43</PAGENUM></CASEREF>, Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities; Tab 10</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>29. The interpretation of the <EM>Act</EM> proposed by the Plaintiffs with respect to s.267.8(l) and (4) of the <EM>Act</EM> is inherently flawed and should not be read so as to limit the deduction of collateral benefits from only those related to the specific damages which the plaintiff received from the jury, and not all losses in that category or &ldquo;silo&rdquo;.</P>
<P>30. The Plaintiffs' approach would essentially allow a plaintiff to decide, at any stage in the proceedings, whether or not to pursue a past loss. If a past loss is not pursued for a period where collateral benefits were received, then a defendant would not be permitted to deduct those collateral benefits pursuant to s.267.8, and the effect of the split and deduct provisions in s.267.8(8) would be undermined. Pursuant to this subsection, collateral benefit deductions are made <UNDER>after</UNDER> any apportionment for contributory negligence. Those provisions could thus be rendered meaningless at the unilateral instance of a plaintiff.</P>
<P>31. As an example, consider a case where a plaintiff has past healthcare expenses of $500,000, which has been completely paid for by his or her accident benefits insurer. Suppose further that the plaintiff does not advance a <UNDER>past</UNDER> healthcare claim at trial and only pursues a <UNDER>future</UNDER> healthcare claim. If the plaintiff is awarded $1,000,000 in <UNDER>future</UNDER> healthcare damages at trial and is found 75% contributorily negligent, her net award would be $250,000.</P>
<P>32. However, if the plaintiff properly advanced her past healthcare claim at trial, she would be awarded nil for past healthcare ($500,000 - 75% = $125,000 - $500,000 of the healthcare benefits received = nil). There would be $375,000 in healthcare benefits remaining which would need to be deducted from the future healthcare damages awarded at trial. The future amount would be nil ($1,000,000 - 75% for contributory negligence = $250,000 - $375,000 = 0).</P>
<P>33. The plaintiffs' suggested approach of not pursuing tort damages that have been paid for by a collateral source is inconsistent with how collateral benefit deductions are to be handled and would render s.267.8(8) meaningless.</P>
<P>34. A plaintiff should not be permitted to manipulate the collateral benefit scheme in such a way, to the detriment of the tortfeasor. In <EM>Madill</EM>, the plaintiff chose not to apply for collateral benefits which he was otherwise &ldquo;entitled&rdquo; to and the Supreme Court deducted them nevertheless. As such, if a plaintiff chooses to not advance certain claims for past losses at trial, the collateral benefits that he or she received still need to be deducted.</P>
<P>35. Furthermore, s. 267.7(1) and (2) of the <EM>Act</EM> (as referenced in s.267.8(3)) sets out how joint and several liability is to be dealt with as between protected and non-protected defendants. The provisions call for an assessment of damages broken into the same &ldquo;silos&rdquo; of income loss, health care and other pecuniary losses, but does not reference only those losses the plaintiff choses to pursue or those not covered by collateral benefits. The Plaintiffs' interpretation of <BOLD><EM>the Act</EM></BOLD> appears inconsistent with this provision.</P>
<P>36. Moreover, the &ldquo;the&rdquo; modifier proposed by the plaintiffs<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Plaintiff's Factum, at para. 57</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> is not consistently applied in the <EM>Act</EM>. It is not seen, for example, in the s.267.8(9)&ndash;(12) trust/assignment provisions which specifically contemplate the assignment of <UNDER>all payments in respect of the incident</UNDER>. In fact, the &ldquo;the&rdquo; modifier appears in s.267.8 (1) and (4) only with respect to a deduction of <UNDER>statutory accident benefits</UNDER>, and not with respect to other collateral benefits received or available, such as a private employment benefits scheme. There is no rationale for the Legislature to intend a different scope of deductibility of SABS than other non-SABS collateral benefits. Such an approach would seem anomalous and would unduly complicate the process.</P>
<P>37. The Plaintiffs ask for all deduction and trust/assignment sections to be interpreted in the same manner so as to require strict temporal and qualitative matching. They submit that that outcome is compelled by the &ldquo;the&rdquo; modifier which was put in place in 1996. The problem, however, is that the &ldquo;the&rdquo; modifier is not present in the deduction of non-SABS collateral benefits, nor is it present in the trust/assignment provisions. As such, it is submitted that the &ldquo;the&rdquo; modifier cannot be the word that compels the interpretation the Plaintiffs seek since the modifier is not present in the trust/assignment context in which the Plaintiffs seek the same interpretation.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV"><UNDER>The Error in <EM>Gilbert</EM> Should be Corrected</UNDER></TI>
<P>38. In addition to identifying a legal error, this Court has established a broad contextual approach that &ldquo;weigh[s] the advantages and disadvantages of correcting the error in a previous decision&rdquo; to the question of when it will overrule one of its past decisions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>David Polowin Real Estate Ltd. v. Dominion of Canada General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2008 ONCA 703 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>127</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 11; <CASEREF><SOC>Green v. Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 90</CITE><PARANUM>15</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities; Tab 12</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. It is unnecessary to specifically overrule <EM>Bannon</EM> because it applies to a different regime. Similarly, the law on deductions in the current regime is otherwise well settled.</P>
<P>40. These Respondents submit, however, that the relevant considerations in the trust/assignment context, when taken together, support a ruling that <EM>Gilbert</EM> was wrongly decided and ought to be overruled in favour of the assignment approach outlined in <EM>El-Khodr</EM>.</P>
<P>41. <EM>Gilbert</EM> is a recent decision and so overturning it would not cause a dramatic change to the current regime. To reach an alternative conclusion and find as the Plaintiffs ask that there be strict matching in both the deduction and assignment context, would require this Court to overturn or depart from several appellate cases in the deductibility context, including <EM>Cummings, Mikolic, Bassandra</EM> and <EM>Cobb</EM>, and would be contrary to at least the dicta in <EM>Gurniak</EM>.</P>
<P>42. The strict qualitative and temporal matching in <EM>Gilbert</EM> should not be applied to s. 267.8 of the <EM>Act</EM>. The policy rationale is not applicable to the current regime. Although the approach in <EM>Gilbert</EM> is met on the facts herein, going forward, the approach in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> should be preferred.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V"><UNDER>Conclusion</UNDER></TI>
<P>43. The law dealing with <UNDER>deductions</UNDER> is well settled. The appellate decisions in <EM>Cummings, Mikolic, Basandra</EM> and <EM>Cobb</EM> required no more than the broad matching categories in the <EM>Act</EM> for qualitative matching for the <UNDER>deduction</UNDER> of collateral benefits.</P>
<P>44. Similarly, an <UNDER>assignment</UNDER> of collateral benefits should only require a matching to the broad, enumerated categories or &ldquo;silos&rdquo; stipulated in the <EM>Act</EM>, given the transfer of risk of future payment from plaintiff to defendant. To find otherwise would result in a scheme which facilitates double recovery for plaintiffs. This would be an inequitable result, unfair to defendants, and contrary to the scheme and object of the <EM>Act</EM>, as well as the intention of the Legislature.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED, this 28<SUP>th</SUP> day of March, 2018.</P>
