<P><LINE>Lawyers for the Defendants (Respondents), Aviva Canada Inc. and Pilot Insurance Company</LINE></P>
<P>1. The Respondents, Aviva Canada Inc. and Pilot Insurance Company (hereinafter, &ldquo;These Respondents&rdquo;) have been directed to provide brief written submissions addressing this Court's recent decisions in <CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie and Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC></CASEREF>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 717</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, These Respondents' Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 1.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, These Respondents' Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>2. There were only two issues raised in the within appeal:
<P1>(i) The assignment of future accident benefits;</P1>
<P1>(ii) Costs.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>These Respondents' Factum, para. 5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>3. The decisions in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> and <EM>Cobb</EM> fully support the position of These Respondents, particularly in the following respects.</P>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>Assignment of Future Accident Benefits</TI>
<P>4. <EM>El-Khodr</EM> supports the position of These Respondents in the following respects.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Matching Principles</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>5. In <EM>El-Khodr</EM>, the Court tracks the evolution of the legal principals governing the assignment of accident benefits and confirms that the certainty of entitlement requirements of <CASEREF><SOC>Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC></CASEREF> and the strict matching requirements in <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC></CASEREF> are no longer strictly applicable to the assignment of SABS' entitlement because the statutory regime has changed.
<P1><BOLD>These Respondents' Factum, para. 7.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, These Respondents' Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 2 at paras. 43&ndash;54 citing</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC><YEAR>1998</YEAR><CITE>38 O.R. (3d) 651</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>&amp; citing</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC><YEAR>1998</YEAR><CITE>38 O.R. (3d) 659</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>6. The Appellants argued that there should be no assignment of future SABS because the jury's global award for &ldquo;future care costs&rdquo; did not distinguish between rehabilitation expenses, attendant care, and medication and assistive devices. These Respondents argued that the &ldquo;silo&rdquo; of costs awarded by the jury for future care costs fell within the same &ldquo;silo&rdquo; of costs covered by the SABs.
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, para. 59.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>These Respondents' Factum, para. 17.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>7. <EM>El-Khodr</EM> makes clear that strict matching is not required. MacFarland J.A. stated at para. 60:
<QUOTE><P>. . . the Court is required only to match statutory benefits that fall squarely into the &ldquo;silos&rdquo; created by s. 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> with the tort heads of damage. Income awards are to be reduced only by SABs payments in respect of income loss and health care awards only by SABs payments in respect of health care expenses. The latter item is, I suggest, deliberately broad enough to cover all manner of expenses that relate to health care and would include medications, physiotherapy, psychology sessions, assistive devices and the like. All manner of other expenses that are covered by SABs and that do not fall under the income category or the health care category fall into the &ldquo;other pecuniary losses&rdquo; category.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, These Respondents' Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 2 at para. 60.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>8. This is precisely the position of each of the Respondents in this appeal. The silo of costs contained in the jury award for &ldquo;future care costs&rdquo; falls within the same silo as the SABs entitlement.
<P1><BOLD>These Respondents' Factum, para. 17.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>McEwen Respondents' Factum, paras. 85&ndash;93.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>9. Further, it was correct for the jury to discount the award for future care costs for any medications and assistive devices Barbara Carroll may receive from the Ontario Drug Benefit Program (&ldquo;ODBP&rdquo;), if the jury in fact did so. They jury is obliged to award damages based on the law as it currently exists. Given Barbara Carroll's eligibility under the ODBP at age 65, she would suffer no loss from that age forward because her drug claims would be covered by the ODBP. If the jury did <UNDER>not</UNDER> discount the award for future care costs for ODBP, the end result would be the <UNDER>overcompensation</UNDER> of the Plaintiffs.
<P1><BOLD><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, These Respondents' Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 2 at paras. 19&ndash;23.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, para. 59(e).</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Jury Questions</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>10. In this appeal, and in <EM>El-Khodr</EM>, the Appellants argued that the Respondents &ldquo;drafted the damages questions for the jury&rdquo; and must bear the consequences of any resulting uncertainty in the matching of costs. It should be noted that Appellant's counsel in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> is also counsel in the present case. In oral submissions, in response to a question from the Bench, he stated, in effect, that it was not his responsibility to ensure that the jury questions were properly categorized.
<P1><BOLD><EM>El-Khodr, ibid</EM>, Factum of the Appellant, These Respondents' Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 3 at paras. 52 &amp; 59-60.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, paras. 58&ndash;62.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>11. The Respondents' position was that the framing of jury questions was <BOLD>a joint</BOLD> responsibility ultimately to be determined by the trial Judge,</P>
<P>12. Madame Justice MacFarland states at para. 83:
<QUOTE><P>Plaintiff's should not be able to avoid either the deductibility or assignment of SABs already received or to which they will be entitled in future by the manner in which the claim for special damages is presented.</P></QUOTE>
and at para. 85:
<QUOTE><P>Plaintiffs should be required to present their cases in this way. They alone know best what amounts they have expended in relation to their injuries that their SABs insurer did not or will not reimburse. If those items are separately categorized, the matching difficulties disappear&mdash;as does any risk of over or under compensation.</P></QUOTE>
and at para. 86:
<QUOTE><P>A Plaintiff should not be permitted to avoid having SABs deducted fro m a tort award and thereby defeating the purpose of the legislation by lumping together claims covered by SABs with those which are not.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, These Respondents' Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 2 at paras. 83 &amp; 85-86.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>ii.</N><TI><UNDER>Costs</UNDER></TI>
<P>13. Justice McLean gave several reasons to support his cost decision including the net value of the Judgment compared to the settlement proposals, and &ldquo;the trick&rdquo;.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Net Recovery</UNDER></TI>
<P>14. Herein, the Appellants achieved a jury verdict of $2.6 million, less the value of the assignment of health care expenses valued in the range of $750,000 to $830,000, resulting in a net benefit to the Appellants in the range of $1,770,000 to $1,850,000.</P>
<P>15. The Appellants' joint offers to settle ranged from $1,856,250 to $1,950,000, plus costs.</P>
<P>16. The Respondents' joint offer to settle dated September 11, 2015 was for $2,150,000 all-inclusive with no assignment of future accident benefits.</P>
<P>17. It was entirely appropriate for Justice McLean to consider, in part, the value of the future accident benefits assigned to the Respondents in concluding that the Appellants' joint offers were less than the verdict's benefit to the Appellants.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>&ldquo;The Trick&rdquo;</UNDER></TI>
<P>18. The Appellants argued that the offer to settle dated September 11, 2015, referred only to issues in &ldquo;this proceeding&rdquo; which did not include a potential claim for bad faith.
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, para. 72.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. Justice McLean concluded that the Appellants' counsel would know that the offer included all potential claims against the Respondents. The purported acceptance of the offer to settle, while initiating a separate claim in bad faith, was &ldquo;a trick&rdquo;. This was one of the several reasons given by Justice McLean for the exercise of his discretion on costs.</P>
<P>20. In <CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC></CASEREF>, MacFarland, J.A. states at para. 37:
<QUOTE><P>Furthermore, the reference in the Release to claims for &ldquo;aggravated, exemplary and punitive damages or damages for alleged bad faith&rdquo; is standard language in any form of release. Indeed, the paragraph goes on to explain that the Release covers such claims for damages &ldquo;whether these claims are past, present or future and whether these claims are known or unknown at the present time.&rdquo;</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 717</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, These Respondents' Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 1 at para. 37.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>21. This supports the Respondents' contention, and Justice McLean's conclusion, that Appellants' counsel must have known that the offer to settle included all claims including any potential claims for bad faith.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED, this 5<SUP>th</SUP> day of October, 2017.</P>
