<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The Appellants make the following submissions in respect of <UNDER><EM>El-Khodr</EM></UNDER> and <UNDER><EM>Cobb</EM></UNDER>:
<P1>(a) the principles set out in <UNDER><EM>Bannon</EM></UNDER>, <UNDER><EM>Gilbert</EM></UNDER> and <UNDER><EM>Fonseca</EM></UNDER> are binding on this Court;</P1>
<P1>(b) <EM>Gilbert</EM> is directly applicable and not distinguishable on its facts in this case;</P1>
<P1>(c) this Court requires a five member panel to reverse these binding authorities; and</P1>
<P1>(d) <EM>El-Khodr</EM> confirmed that the law of deductions of future collateral benefits has been replaced by assignments. Similarly, the Court should similarly <UNDER>not</UNDER> be deducting the present value of collateral benefits from Judgments to assess offers to settle.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;SUBMISSIONS</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI><EM>Bannon, Gilbert and Fonseca</EM> are Binding Authorities</TI>
<P>2. The case of <EM>El-Khodr</EM> (as well as <EM>Cobb</EM>) was heard by a three member panel of this Honourable Court. No request for a five member panel was made to the Chief Justice and none of the appellants in those cases argued that <EM>Bannon</EM> was no longer good law nor that <EM>Gilbert</EM> was not binding authority. As a result, <EM>Bannon, Gilbert</EM> and <EM>Fonseca</EM> remain binding authorities.</P>
<P>3. The following principles of law are set out in <EM>Gilbert</EM> and <EM>Fonseca</EM>:
<P1>(a) a defendant seeking an assignment faces a very strict onus of proof that the entitlement to an assignment is &ldquo;beyond dispute.&rdquo; If there is uncertainty, then matters are not &lsquo;beyond dispute&rsquo;; and</P1>
<P1>(b) there is both a temporal and a qualitative matching requirement for assignments.</P1></P>
<P>4. The panel in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> distinguished <EM>Gilbert</EM> on three factual grounds:
<P1>(a) there was no temporal limitation for the <EM>Statutory Accident Benefits Schedule</EM> (&ldquo;SABS&rdquo;) benefits available to Mr. El Khodr as they were available for his lifetime;</P1>
<P1>(b) there were no benefits for which the assignment was requested that were not covered by the SABS; and</P1>
<P1>(c) there was no lump sum jury award in <EM>Ei-Khodr</EM> which would make it impossible to match SABS to the jury award.</P1></P>
<P>5. None of the above distinguishing factors apply on the facts of this case.</P>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(i)</EM></N><TI><EM>Temporal Limitations</EM></TI>
<P>6. It is common ground between the parties that Barbara Carroll's accident benefits are time limited. She will <UNDER>not</UNDER> be entitled to receive and collect benefits on an ongoing basis for the rest of her life. She had already exhausted a large proportion of the SABS limits prior to trial.</P>
<P>7. It is common ground that Barbara Carroll's attendant care benefits cease in 8.67 years post -trial With respect to her medical and rehabilitation benefits, the Appellant took the position that the benefits cease in 2.55 years post-trial. The Respondents took the position that the benefits ceased in 1.5 years. Benefits will not be available for the rest of Barbara Carroll's life.</P>
<P>8. The parties have no idea what amount the jury awarded to the Plaintiff in attendant care for the 8.67 year period for which Barbara Carroll will continue to be entitled to attendant care benefits nor do we know what the jury awarded in medical and rehabilitation expenses for the 1.5-2.55 year period of time for which Barbara Carroll will continue to be entitled to medical and rehabilitation benefits.</P>
<P>9. As in <EM>Gilbert</EM>, there is a temporal aspect to Barbara Carroll's entitlement to ongoing SABS benefits. No such evidence existed in <EM>El-Khodr</EM>. The evidence here is unequivocal and unchallenged. Barbara Carroll's SABS benefits are time limited.</P>
<P>10. While the jury award covers a period intended to indemnify Barbara Carroll for life, the SABS benefits sought to be assigned will not cover the same period. Effectively, this means that the temporal period of the insurance benefits sought to be assigned do not correspond in any way to the temporal period covered by the jury's award for damages.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(ii)</EM></N><TI><EM>Qualitative Limitations</EM></TI>
<P>11. The actual assignment granted by this Honourable Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> respects that there are qualitative restrictions. The resulting assignment was limited to the specific expenses claimed. The Defendant in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> received an assignment of benefits for &ldquo;future medical and assistive devices&rdquo; which was limited to the amount the jury awarded for that head of damage. The assignment of benefits payable for &ldquo;psychological, physiotherapy, occupational therapy, massage therapy, kinesiology/personal training, case management services and travel to medical or other specialists&rdquo; was also limited to the jury award relating to those damages.</P>
<P>12. In <EM>El-Khodr</EM>, there were also no benefits for which the assignment was requested which were not covered by the SABS. That is not the case here. While there are other examples of claims not covered by the accident benefits insurer (such as financial planning), the best example of this can be found in attendant care. Attendant care is limited to $6,000 per month by the SABS. The Plaintiffs' claim for attendant care ranged from $146,073 to $210,563 annually or $12,172,75 to $17,546.92 monthly.</P>
<P>13. This means that there were <UNDER>significant</UNDER> claims advanced that were not recoverable under the SABS. If the jury accepted the Plaintiffs' claims, there were over $10,000 per month of damages awarded (for attendant care alone) which are not recoverable at all under the <EM>SABS</EM>. Considering the Plaintiff took the position that her attendant care needs continued th roughout her lifetime, it would mean that the bulk of the future care award is not at all recoverable under the SABS yet a full assignment is sought.</P>
<P>14. Assuming the award can be justified entirely based upon attendant care (which is a possibility), the matching principle would be offended if the Defendants were to &ldquo;borrow&rdquo; from the SABS medical and rehabilitation payments to compensate themselves for attendant care amounts awarded but not recoverable under the SABS at all. Similarly, if the jury award is based primarily on medical and rehabilitation expenses (the SABS portion of which expire between 1.5 and 2.55 years), there would be significant claims that are awarded by the jury but not recoverable under the SABS which would be assigned.</P>
<P>15. The tort defendant cannot be permitted to &ldquo;borrow&rdquo; from another category of benefits to recover for tort damages that the SABS insurer was never responsible to pay.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(iii)</EM></N><TI><EM>Lump sum jury award</EM></TI>
<P>16. Unlike in <EM>El-Khodr</EM>, the jury award in this appeal is a lump sum global amount for future care which is precisely the award addressed in <EM>Gilbert</EM>. In the within case, it is impossible to match the global award for &ldquo;future care costs&rdquo; to the SABS benefits. The <EM>Gilbert</EM> decision affirms that even though overlap is <UNDER>likely,</UNDER> it does not negate the requirement to match the damages with the future treatment covered under the SABS. Accordingly, the Respondents cannot meet their onus of proof.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The Need for a Five Member Panel</TI>
<P>17. In the event that this Honourable Court is inclined to entertain the reasons in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> and <EM>Cobb</EM> as implicitly overruling <EM>Bannon, Gilbert</EM> and <EM>Fonseca</EM>, the Appellants submit that a five member panel should be convened to determine that issue in accordance with the <UNDER><EM>Practice Direction Concerning Civil Appeals at the Court of Appeal</EM></UNDER>. It would be inappropriate for a three member panel to reverse prior binding decisions.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>Implications on Costs</TI>
<P>18. <EM>El-Khodr</EM> clarifies that courts are <UNDER>not</UNDER> required to calculate and deduct the present value of collateral benefits to which the plaintiff would be entitled from the damage award. The court should similarly not be <UNDER>deducting</UNDER> collateral benefits from Judgment amounts for comparison with offers to settle. Plaintiffs are never required to accept such a deduction. The risk of non-payment of collateral benefits is squarely upon defendants, not injured plaintiffs. A plaintiff is entitled to the full value of the judgment with <UNDER>no deduction</UNDER>. The current legislation is premised on assignments, not deductions.</P>
<P>19. Even if a deduction for the present value of accident benefits was considered for costs purposes, the Appellants <UNDER>still</UNDER> beat their own offers to settle. Barbara Carroll and family received a Judgment of $2,610,774.32 (plus costs). They offered to settle the action for $1,856,000 (plus costs). The experts disagree on the present value of accident benefits however <UNDER>both</UNDER> experts agree that the Appellants beat their offer <EM>even if the present value of accident benefits were deducted</EM>. The Appellants' expert says they beat their offer by $170,130.00 and the Respondents' expert says the margin was $10,486.00. Barbara Carroll and family also offered to settle as against the McEwen Respondents for $1,000,000 (plus costs). It is admitted that this offer was beaten. Yet this $1M offer was not even mentioned in the costs decision.</P>
<P>20. The attempt to convolute the costs argument by attributing the full present value of accident benefits to the Plaintiffs is wrong in law. Even if it were proper, the result is that the Appellants were acting reasonably while the Defendants tailed to accept offers which were <UNDER>less than</UNDER> the Judgment and <UNDER>less than</UNDER> their insurance limits. The Respondents, not the Appellants, should have been penalized in costs.</P>
