<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;<UNDER>OVERVIEW</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. By coincidence, the Respondent, Aviva Canada Inc., is both the liability insurer of the Defendants, Robert McEwen and Caroline McEwen, and the insurer of the Plaintiff, Barbara Lynn Carroll, providing underinsured coverage (OPCF 44 endorsement) through its affiliate, Pilot Insurance Company.</P>
<P>2. The Plaintiffs sued both Aviva Canada Inc. and Pilot Insurance Company (hereinafter, &ldquo;These Respondents&rdquo;) for indemnity for any sums which could not be recovered from the defendants, Robert McEwen and Caroline McEwen (hereinafter, &ldquo;McEwen Respondents&rdquo;) pursuant to the underinsured coverage provided by the Plaintiff's policy. These Respondents defended the action brought against them, contesting liability and damages, as was their right.
<P1><BOLD>Statement of Defence of Aviva Canada Inc. and Pilot Insurance Company dated December 7, 2011&mdash;Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 10, p. 65</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>3. The interests of the McEwen Respondents and These Respondents are therefore closely aligned as Defendants (Respondents) in the context of this litigation. As a result, counsel for the McEwans took the lead for the Defendants at the trial, and does so again on this appeal.</P>
<P>4. These Respondents are in substantial agreement with the submissions contained in the Factum of the McEwen Respondents.</P>
<P>5. There are only two grounds of appeal. Each challenges the exercise of the trial Judge's wide discretion with respect to:
<P1>i. The assignment of future accident benefits;</P1>
<P1>ii. Costs.</P1></P>
<P>6. The trial Judge had broad discretion with respect to each of these decisions. After presiding over a lengthy trial he exercised that discretion carefully and based upon the appropriate legal principles.</P>
<P>7. Section 267.8 (12) of the <EM>Insurance Act of Ontario</EM> provides the trial Judge with discretion to order an <UNDER>assignment of future accident benefits</UNDER> in order to prevent double recovery. Here, the trial Judge had the advantage of hearing all of the evidence in a long trial. He then properly concluded that an assignment of future accident benefits was plainly necessary to prevent double recovery by the Plaintiff.
<P1><BOLD>Section 267.8(12) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c.1-8 at These Respondents' Factum, Schedule B, p. 11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>8. The trial Judge exercised his discretion in <UNDER>fixing the costs</UNDER> of the parties at the conclusion of the trial. The outcome for the plaintiff was arguably less favourable than a joint offer to settle made by the defendants. Furthermore, the Judge had ample opportunity to assess the conduct of plaintiff's counsel throughout the long trial and the proceedings leading up to it. The trial Judge had every right to take these factors into account in exercising his discretion to award costs to the Plaintiff of $375,000.00.</P>
<P>9. There is no good reason why leave should be granted to appeal the trial Judge's exercise of discretion in fixing the costs of this case. His award was balanced, based on proper principles, and, in the circumstances, more than fair to the Plaintiffs.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;<UNDER>STATEMENT OF FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<P>10. These Respondents adopt the Statement of Facts set out in the Factum of the McEwen Respondents in paragraphs 11&ndash;77 but add that the OPCF 44 endorsement does not provide compensation for costs. Although the Court does have overriding authority to award costs against an underinsurer in certain circumstances, this is not such a case. Accordingly, the cost award is essentially an issue for the McEwen Respondents to deal with.
<P1><BOLD>Section 13, OPCF Endorsement 44R, These Respondents' Book of Authorities, Tab 1.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Section 131 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. 43, These Respondents' Factum, Schedule B, p. 14.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Section 57 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, These Respondents' Factum, Schedule B, p. 15&ndash;18.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Burns v. Hedge</SOC><CITE>[2001] O.J. No. 1941</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, These Respondents' Book of Authorities, Tab 2.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mete v. Guardian Insurance Co. of Canada</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 3836</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, These Respondents' Book of Authorities, Tab 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>11. The trial Judge's decision to order the assignment of future accident benefits is relevant to the cost award and, therefore, is also of direct interest to the McEwen Respondents.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;<UNDER>ISSUES AND ARGUMENT</UNDER></TI>
<P>12. These Respondents accept and adopt the submissions of the McEwen Respondents in paragraphs 78&ndash;114 of their Factum but wish to add the following.</P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>Assignment of Future Accident Benefits</UNDER></TI>
<P>13. The strict onus of proof referred to by this Court in its decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF>, although met in this case, has no direct application here.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC><CITE>[2015] O.J. No. 5573</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. As Laskin, J. there made clear the purpose of section 267.8 (12) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>:
<QUOTE><P>is to ensure that a successful plaintiff in a tort action is not over-compensated by the receipt of collateral benefits&mdash;in other words, to ensure that the plaintiff does not obtain &ldquo;double recovery&rdquo;.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF><BOLD>, <EM>supra</EM> at para. 43, Appellants Book of Authorities, Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. It should not matter whether there is &ldquo;certainty&rdquo; of future payments. When the payments stop, the assignment ceases to have any effect. The risk is borne entirely by the Defendants.</P>
<P>16. In the case of an <UNDER>assignment</UNDER> of <UNDER>future benefits</UNDER>, as here, it is not the entitlement which should be &ldquo;beyond dispute&rdquo; but merely that the tort award be &ldquo;akin&rdquo; to the payments which are to be assigned to the Defendants.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. Hagerman Estate</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 1673</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>38 O.R. (3d) 659</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at p. 679, McEwen Respondents' Book of Authorities, Tab 5.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF><BOLD>, <EM>supra</EM> at para. 44, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 2.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC><CITE>[2016] O.J. No. 1749</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2016 ONCA 251</CITE><PARANUM>4 and 5</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 1.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mikolic v. Tanguay</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 71</CITE><COURTJUR>Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at paras. 32 and 44 to 47, McEwen Respondents' Book of Authorities, Tab 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. The relevant &ldquo;certainty&rdquo; referred to in the cases applies here to the nature of the future costs allowed by the jury, as compared to the category of costs to be covered by the assignment. In this case, the future benefits are not only &ldquo;akin&rdquo; to the costs of the jury award, they are identical. In the language of this Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC></CASEREF>, each falls under the &ldquo;silo&rdquo; of health care expenses, which includes attendant care and medical rehabilitation costs.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC></CASEREF><BOLD>, <EM>supra</EM> at para. 21, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. Here, the Judge identified the correct principles to be applied, considered the extensive evidence placed before the jury, and correctly concluded that an assignment was appropriate to prevent obvious double recovery.</P>
<P>19. The trial Judge determined, based on the extensive evidence given at trial, including affidavit and viva voce evidence concerning the present value of future entitlement, that an assignment was appropriate. His Honour held that:
<QUOTE><P>When we consider all of the evidence at trial, and indeed the further evidence with respect to this matter now placed before the Court, the Court is satisfied within the wording of <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF> that a very strict onus of proof has been made out and that based on that evidence it is patently clear that the preconditions for an appropriate assignment have been made out.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Decision of the trial Judge at para. 10, Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, p. 22</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. It is submitted the trial Judge should be shown deference in the exercise of his discretion in which, it is submitted, he was quite correct.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>Costs</TI>
<P>21. The trial Judge had a wide discretion to fix the costs at the end of this long trial. It is submitted that the trial Judge clearly considered the proper principles pursuant to Rule 57.01(1) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. Moreover, he had the advantage of presiding over the lengthy trial proceedings and properly took the relevant considerations into effect. The exercise of his discretion should be shown deference.
<P1><BOLD>Section 57.01 (1) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, These Respondents' Factum, Schedule B, p. 15.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton v. Open Window Bakery</SOC><CITE>[2004] 1 S. C. R. 303</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2003] S.C.J. No. 72</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>2004 SCC 9</CITE><PARANUM>27</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, McEwen Respondents' Book of Authorities, Tab 11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. It is submitted that leave ought not to be granted to appeal the exercise of the Judge's costs discretion which was, in any event, fair and reasonable.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>McNaughton Automotive Ltd. v. Co-Operative General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>[2008] O. J. No. 5040</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2008 ONCA 597</CITE><PARANUM>23 to 27</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, McEwen Respondents' Book of Authorities, Tab 9.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Feinstein v. Freedman</SOC><CITE>119 O. R. (3d) 385</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2014 ONCA 205</CITE><PARANUM>52</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, McEwen Respondents' Book of Authorities, Tab 10.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;<UNDER>ORDER SOUGHT</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. <BOLD>These Respondents respectfully request that this Honorable Court:</BOLD>
<P1>a) Dismiss the Plaintiffs' appeal of the trial Judge's award of an assignment;</P1>
<P1>b) Deny the Plaintiffs' request for leave to appeal the trial Judge's costs decision;</P1>
<P1>c) Award These Respondents their costs of this appeal.</P1></P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED, this 27<SUP>th</SUP> day of July, 2017.</P>
<P>&ellip35; <BOLD>D. H. ROGERS Q.C.</BOLD></P>
