<BLOCK1><TI>SUPPLEMENTARY FACTUM OF THE DEFENDANTS (RESPONDENTS), Robert McEwen and Caroline McEwen (Referencing the Decisions of this Court in <EM>El-Khodr v. Lackie, 2017 ONCA 716, and Cobb v. Long Estate</EM>, 2017 ONCA 717)</TI>
<P>October 2, 2017</P>
<P><LINE><BOLD>BORDEN LADNER GERVAIS LLP</BOLD></LINE>
<LINE>Barristers and Solicitors</LINE>
<LINE>World Exchange Plaza</LINE>
<LINE>100 Queen Street, Suite 1300</LINE>
<LINE>Ottawa, ON K1P 1J9</LINE></P>
<P><LINE>Kevin P. Nearing LSUC # 25476J</LINE>
<LINE>T: 613.787.3520 direct</LINE>
<LINE>T: 613.237.5160 main</LINE>
<LINE>F: 613.230.8842</LINE>
<LINE>E: knearing@blg.com</LINE></P>
<P><LINE>Lawyers for the Defendants (Respondents), Robert McEwen and Caroline McEwen</LINE></P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>I</N><TI>OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. At the request of the panel that heard the Appeal in this matter on September 14, 2017, the Respondents McEwens make the following submissions with respect to the effect of this Court's Decisions in <CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716</CITE></CASEREF>, and <CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 717</CITE></CASEREF>, both of which were released on September 19, 2017.</P>
<P>2. Particular emphasis will be placed on the <EM>El-Khodr</EM> decision as it is a decision that dealt directly with the issue of the assignment of benefits for an award for the cost of future care.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716</CITE><PARANUM>24&ndash;80</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>3. In <EM>El-Khodr</EM>, this Court set out, in considerable detail, how the relevant provisions of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> have evolved, as well as how the case law has evolved.</P>
<P>4. This evolution, and in particular, the provisions of section 267.8 (9) (the &ldquo;Trust&rdquo; provision) and (12) (the &ldquo;Assignment&rdquo; provision) have achieved a rational balancing of the two competing principles of avoiding double recovery and avoiding under-compensation.</P>
<P>5. The reasons in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> and <EM>Cobb</EM> are completely consistent and on all fours with the Respondents McEwens' submissions with respect to the facts and law in their Factum.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><BOLD>Factum of the Defendants (Respondents),</BOLD> Robert McEwen and Caroline McEwen, paras. 25&ndash;38 and 78&ndash;93.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>6. The reasons of this Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> and <EM>Cobb</EM> are also completely consistent with the Trial Judge's review of the facts and law in his Reasons for Decision.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the Trial Judge, para.3&ndash;12 <BOLD>[Appeal Book and Compendium, Volume 1, Tab 4, at pp.18&ndash;22.]</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>The Evolution of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>7. From paragraphs 38&ndash;54, the Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> reviewed past provisions of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> which arguably exposed a claimant to a risk of under-compensation. Section 239(2) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1980 provided for a general release &ldquo;... to the extent of payments made or available to the claimant ...&rdquo; without specifying the nature of the payment, whether it be for past or future income, past or future care and so on.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at paras.38 and 39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In other words, there was no statutory requirement for matching.</P>
<P>8. As the Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> explained, <EM>&ldquo;Cox and Carter&rdquo;</EM> orders were used to address uncertainties with respect to future benefits.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at para.40.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In <CASEREF><SOC>Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court upheld the Trial Judge's imposition of a <EM>&ldquo;Cox &amp; Carter&rdquo;</EM> order to avoid the prospect of double recovery.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Chrappa v. Ohm</SOC><YEAR>1998</YEAR><CITE>38 O.R. (3d) 651</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Authorities Brief, Tab 2].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>9. Provisions were arguably even &ldquo;harsher&rdquo; for a claimant under section 267(1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1980 in that it mandated that the damage award be reduced by the present value of &ldquo;any no-fault benefits to which the person is entitled&rdquo;; again, without concern as to which particular benefits were being used to reduce the damage award.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at para.41.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Here again, there was no statutory requirement for matching.</P>
<P>10. As the Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> explained, the result in <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. Hagerman Estate</SOC></CASEREF> was necessary to avoid a double accounting of the reduction for no-fault benefits.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at paras.52, 53 and 54.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Further, however strict the &ldquo;apples to apples&rdquo; and &ldquo;oranges and oranges&rdquo; matching requirement was applied by the Court in <EM>Bannon</EM>, the amendments to the legislation have done away with the policy rationale for whatever strict matching requirement was required by the Courts.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, Supra at paras.53 and 54.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>11. With the enactment of section 267.8 and, in particular, sub-sections (8) and (12), the legislation has evolved and directed how the matching is to take place.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>The Current Legislation and &ldquo;Silos&rdquo;</UNDER></TI>
<P>12. Section 267.8, in its current form, was enacted in 1996. This Court, in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> and <EM>Basandra</EM>, recognized that it codifies the common law principle that a plaintiff should not recover twice for the same kind of loss arising from the same accident.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at para.33, and <CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 251</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>130 O.R. (3d) 466</CITE><PARANUM>18</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Authorities Brief, Tab 6].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. Consistent with the decision of this Court in <EM>Basandra</EM>, the Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> recognized that there is nothing in the wording of the language of the current legislation that would require any further subdivision of statutory benefits beyond the &ldquo;silos&rdquo; created by section 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Basandra</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at paras.4 and 5 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Authorities Brief, Tab 6]</BOLD> and <CASEREF><SOC>Mikolic v. Tanguay</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 71</CITE><COURTJUR>Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras.44&ndash;47 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Authorities Brief, Tab 7].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Trial Judge's decision is consistent with the assignment provisions in section 267.8(12) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> and the decision of the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Gurniak</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at paras.70 and 71; <CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>[2003] 2 SCR 652</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Authorities Brief, Tab 1].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI><UNDER><EM>Gilbert v. South</EM> is Distinguishable from this Case</UNDER></TI>
<P>14. As the Respondents indicated in their Factum, the Trial Judge correctly concluded that, on the record before him, this case satisfied the onus of proof set out by this Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of the Trial Judge, Justice McLean <BOLD>[Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, paras.9, 10 and 11].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. The Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> recognized that the facts in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> were different than those in <EM>Gilbert</EM> such there was little or no risk of under-compensation due to an assignment of future statutory benefits.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at para.73.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. Many aspects of the record that satisfied this Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> apply to the facts of this case:
<P1>(a) The Appellant Barbara Lynn Carroll has been designated catastrophically impaired;</P1>
<P1>(b) The ten-year temporal limitation for SABs in <EM>Gilbert</EM> does not arise; and</P1>
<P1>(c) There were no benefits for which the assignment was requested that were not covered by SABs.</P1></P>
<P>17. In their Factum and in their oral argument, the Appellants attempted to raise an uncertainty with respect to medication under the Ontario Drug Benefit Program. The Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> conclusively rejected the identical submission made by the Appellants in this case.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Factum of the Appellants, para.59; <EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra Issue</EM> 3 at paras. 19&ndash;23.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. The assignment granted by the Trial Judge and the assignment in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> were both conditional upon the judgment being paid in full. Pending the resolution of this Appeal, the Respondents have paid the Appellants $2,000,000. There is absolutely no risk that the Appellants will not receive full compensation. The risk is completely on the Respondents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at paras.78&ndash;80.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>19. There is no need, on the facts of this case, to reverse this Court's decision in <EM>Bannon</EM>. It is a decision that was made with respect to a different legislative framework.</P>
<P>20. Similarly, there is no need for this Court to reverse <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF>. The record before the Trial Judge in this case was very different than the record before the Trial Judge in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF>. Whether it be the &ldquo;strict&rdquo; matching required in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF> or the &ldquo;less stringent&rdquo; matching of silos applied in <EM>Basandra</EM>, the facts of this case meet either test.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>II</N><TI>CONCLUSION</TI>
<P>21. The Respondent McEwens submit that, without the benefit of this Court's decisions in <BOLD><EM>El-Khodr</EM></BOLD> and <BOLD><EM>Cobb</EM>,</BOLD> it was completely appropriate and correct in law and on the facts, for the Trial Judge to grant the Respondents the assignment.</P>
<P>22. The Respondent McEwens submit that this Court's Decision in <BOLD><EM>El-Khodr</EM></BOLD> and <BOLD><EM>Cobb</EM></BOLD> serve to reinforce their position that the assignment was the proper exercise of the Trial Judge's discretion and that the Appeal of the Trial Judge's order granting the Respondents the assignment be dismissed with costs.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED, this 2<SUP>nd</SUP> day of October, 2017.</P>
<P>Kevin P. Nearing</P>
<P><BOLD>BORDEN LADNER GERVAIS LLP</BOLD></P>
<P>Lawyers for the Defendant (Respondents), Robert McEwen and Caroline McEwen</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
