<BLOCK1><TI>REPLY FACTUM OF THE DEFENDANTS (RESPONDENTS), Robert McEwen and Caroline McEwen, TO THE FACTUM OF THE INTERVENOR, ONTARIO TRIAL LAWYERS ASSOCIATION</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The issue in the main appeal (Court File No. C62293), besides costs, is the trial Judge's Order that future accident benefits for health care expenses payable to Barbara Carroll (&ldquo;Ms. Carroll&rdquo;) under the Statutory Accident Benefits Regulations (&ldquo;SABs&rdquo;) be assigned to the Defendants in that action upon payment of the Judgment.</P>
<P>2. The specific issues in this case have some overlap with the issues in <CASEREF><SOC>Cadieux v. Cloutier et al</SOC><DOCKET>Court File No. C63160</DOCKET></CASEREF>. As much has already been submitted to the Court regarding the extent of matching required between a tort judgment and SABs benefits, this Reply will focus primarily upon the access to justice issue raised by the Intervenor, Ontario Trial Lawyers Association (&ldquo;OTLA&rdquo;).</P>
<P>3. It is submitted that the position advanced by OTLA will actually have the opposite effect advanced by OTLA. Trials will become more expensive and even more protracted. More detailed evidence would be required; jury questions would become more complex; trial judges' instructions to the jury would become potentially overwhelming; and jury deliberations would, in all probability, take much longer.</P>
<P>4. As this Court and other Courts have held, neither the deductibility of benefits, nor the assignment of benefits was meant to be complicated.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie et al</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716</CITE><PARANUM>81</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>; <CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>[2003] 2 SCR 652</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 1]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>5. The Defendants/Respondents McEwens have no further facts to address.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;LAW AND ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>This Case Demonstrates the Practicality of Silos</UNDER></TI>
<P>6. Apart from the liability issue and general damages, this trial was mostly about the cost of future care.</P>
<P>7. In support of the claim, the Court heard evidence from Life Care Planners, Care Givers, and Ms. Carroll's Occupational Therapist.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Decision of Justice McLean <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 1, Tab 4, page 20 at para.6 and page 21 at para.9].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. In support of the claim, the Plaintiffs relied upon the evidence of Carol Bierbrier, a Life Care Planner, who presented evidence with respect to a Cost of Future Care Plan or Claim that consisted of 64 line items.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Chart of Medication and Assistive Devices, Professional, Personal Care Services, Retirement Facility, Nursing Home&mdash;Tort <BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 63, pages 576 to 585].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>9. The Plaintiffs also relied upon a chart entitled &ldquo;Schedule 1 Cost of Care as per Rule 53.09&rdquo; with present value factors provided by an actuary.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><BOLD>[Revised Appeal Book and Compendium, Vol. 2, Tab 62, pages 573 to 575].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. If the exercise at trial is to achieve perfect matching, a jury question and a jury response for all components of the Cost of Care Schedule would be required. Common sense dictates that this would be an onerous exercise that would make trials longer and more expensive.</P>
<P>11. The Respondent McEwens submit that for the reasons set out in their Revised Factum, the &ldquo;Silos&rdquo; approach adopted by this Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC></CASEREF> and followed in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> make it clear that the level of matching required is provided in Section 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>Evidence of Past Benefits is Readily Available</UNDER></TI>
<P>12. It is submitted that, as this Court said in <EM>El-Khodr</EM>, plaintiffs should not be able to avoid either the deductibility or assignment of SABs already received or to which they will be entitled in future by the manner in which the claim is presented.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at para.83 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. Typically, as occurred in this case, the health care providers involved in a plaintiff's care prior to the trial give evidence at the trial. Not only does their evidence speak to potential past claims, their evidence supports the theory of the plaintiff's case with respect to general damages, potential past and future loss of income claims, and potential past and future cost of c are claims.</P>
<P>14. In any event, there was no difficulty obtaining the particulars of the cost of past care. As in most cases, the information was requested and provided. It would have added nothing to the duration, expense or complexity of the trial if there had been a claim for past care.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Elizabeth Quigley to Kevin Nearing dated August 18, 2015, Exhibit Book, pages 1161 and 1162 <BOLD>[Respondent McEwens' Revised Compendium, Tab 5 at pages 19 and 20].</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. The guidance provided by this Court in <EM>El-Khodr</EM> provides a straightforward and logical roadmap for plaintiffs in the presentation of their cases that addresses the risk of over or under compensation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>El-Khodr</EM>, <EM>Supra</EM> at paras.84 to 86 <BOLD>[Revised Respondent McEwens' Brief of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. Hagerman Estate</SOC></CASEREF> required the deduction of the no-fault benefit to be from a head of damages or a type of loss <UNDER>akin</UNDER> to that for which the no-fault benefits were intended to compensate. Silos as provided for in Section 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> accomplish the result intended and provided for in the legislation.</P>
<P>17. There is no access to justice issue raised by this Court's interpretation of the provisions of Section 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> in the <EM>Basandra, El-Khodr</EM> and <EM>Cobb</EM> decisions of this Court.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED, this 12<SUP>th</SUP> day of April, 2018.</P>
<P>&ellip35; Kevin P. Nearing</P>
<P><BOLD>BORDEN LADNER GERAIS LLP</BOLD></P>
<P>Lawyers for the Defendants (Respondents), Robert McEwen and Caroline McEwen</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
</FREEFORM>
