<BLOCK1><TI>REPLY FACTUM OF THE APPELLANTS, BARBARA CARROLL AND FAMILY TO THE FACTUM OF THE INTERVENOR, ONTARIO TRIAL LAWYERS ASSOCIATION</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. OTLA was permitted to intervene with respect to:
<P1>(a) the proper interpretation of deduction and assignment provisions under the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>; and</P1>
<P1>(b) the proper interpretation of s.258.3(8.1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> with respect to prejudgment interest.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>2. The Appellant does not rely upon any additional facts for the within reply.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ISSUES RAISED BY THE INTERVENOR</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>I.</N><TI>DEDUCTION AND ASSIGNMENT PROVISIONS UNDER THE <EM>INSURANCE ACT</EM></TI>
<BLOCK4><N>i.</N><TI>Generally</TI>
<P>3. OTLA made the submission that if the <EM>Cadieux</EM> decision of Hackland, J., were upheld, it would have the following effect:
<QUOTE><P>If this decision stands, for all future cases, injured plaintiffs will be required to advance all potential claims, even those claims that have been completely covered by no-fault benefits at the tort trial to prophylactically protect other heads of damages.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>4. In practice, counsel have acted reasonably in narrowing the issues in dispute to pursue only claims that are actually sought and avoiding the pursuit of claims that have been entirely satisfied or paid by a collateral benefit provider. In our submission, such a practice should be encouraged not hindered. If the deduction and assignment provisions of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> are interpreted to require a plaintiff to pursue <UNDER>all</UNDER> losses, even those for which they are not seeking compensation, then the reasonable practice of only pursuing claims actually sought from the defendant will be in serious jeopardy.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii.</N><TI>Hypothetical application of <EM>Cadieux</EM> principles to <EM>Carroll v. McEwen</EM></TI>
<P>5. The <CASEREF><SOC>Carroll v. McEwen</SOC></CASEREF> trial represents a reasonable approach to past expenses. In <EM>Carroll</EM>, the Plaintiffs only sought and received recovery for general damages and <UNDER>future</UNDER> care costs. As such, only an assignment for future benefits was sought by the Defendants (which is the subject -matter of the within Appeal). As such, the following is a discussion of the hypothetical application of the principles of <EM>Cadieux</EM> to the <CASEREF><SOC>Carroll v. McEwen</SOC></CASEREF> facts.</P>
<P>6. If the <EM>Cadieux</EM> decision was left to stand, it would have required Barbara Carroll and her family to litigate approximately <BOLD>$1.1 M</BOLD> in past expenses<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The actual past expenses paid by the accident benefits insu rer was $1,093,063.00 representing $716,956.00 for past medical and rehabilitation expenses and $376,107 for past attendant care expenses.
<P1>See Report of Gary Princ ipe, dated December 18, 2015, Appeal Book and Compe ndium, Tab 43, p.207.</P1></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> which were incurred during the six and a half years before trial even though <UNDER>none</UNDER> of those expenses were being sought from the Defendants. It defies common sense and logic to demand that a plaintiff extend an already lengthy eight week jury trial in order to have the jury assess the reasonableness of past expenditures that the plaintif f fully recovered from collateral sources and for which the defendants are not being asked to pay.</P>
<P>7. The Reply Factum of the Respondent McEwen makes the patently false assertion that claims of past care would have &ldquo;added nothing to the duration, expense or complexity of the trial.&rdquo; Had the Plaintiffs been required to prove $1.1M in expenses previously incurred (but already compensated by collateral source), it would have been a cumbersome and exhausting process spanning over six and a half years, three different hospital and care facilities, different case managers, different treatment providers and attendant care providers. Additional <BOLD><UNDER>weeks</UNDER></BOLD> would have been added to the trial to prove these losses for which no compensation was sought. Past care claims could have been a trial unto itself.</P>
<P>8. The suggestion in the McEwen factum that evidence of Barbara Carroll's future care needs would somehow &ldquo;speak to potential past claims&rdquo; is patently false. Plaintiffs cannot rely upon assumptions in a trial&mdash;they need actual evidence for a jury to deliberate upon and ultimately award past expenditures. It would not be sufficient for a plaintiff to merely submit a print-out of past expenditures and expect a jury to rubber stamp the expenditures. It would be even more foolhardy to expect that a defendant would simply concede the past expenditures without demanding formal proof of their reasonableness. Indeed, why would they? A defendant's interest is in securing the lowest possible verdict against him/her and the highest possible credit for any payments made to the plaintiff by collateral sources.</P>
<P>9. In essence, both past and future expenditures would be expected to be vigorously challenged by the defence.</P>
<P>10. This approach was not even considered in <CASEREF><SOC>Carroll v. McEwen</SOC></CASEREF> because the practice which had been developed at trial advances the most cost effective and sensible approach to litigation. Namely, that a plaintiff should only advance the claims for which compensation is sought. Neither counsel for the Respondents in this appeal, namely Aviva nor McEwen, raised any issue with respect to this approach before, during or after trial. It is only in the appeal factums of the Respondents (before this five member panel) that these Respondents now advance the position that plaintiffs should be required to advance all potential claims regardless of whether compensation is sought from defendants or was paid by a collateral source. That was not the position advanced at trial.</P>
<P>11. Interestingly, this approach was recognized by MacFarland, J.A, in <CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC></CASEREF> as justifying the approach towards deductions adopted in <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC></CASEREF>. Regrettably, MacFarland, J.A., erred in concluding that this was an &ldquo;unusual&rdquo; approach when, in fact, it was and continues to be the norm. Paragraph 52 of Justice MacFarland's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC></CASEREF> is worth reproducing:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>[52] In Bannon, the plaintiffs did not seek recovery of benefits already provided to them by their no-fault insurer;</EM> <UNDER><EM>their claims were presented net of those benefits</EM>.</UNDER> <EM>Nevertheless, the appellants in that case argued that the payments still had to be deducted from the damage award in the tort claim. The result in Bannon is not surprising;</EM> <UNDER><EM>where the claim was presented net of no-fault payments, any further deduction would have amounted to a double counting of the no-fault benefits</EM>.</UNDER> <EM>[Emphasis Added]</EM></BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716 (C anLII)</CITE><PARANUM>50-52</PARANUM></CASEREF><UNDER>, Appella nts' Book of Authorities, Tab 9</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>12. Indeed, in <CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC></CASEREF>, the Plaintiff did not advance any claims for past expenses (which had been compensated by the accident benefits insurer) and only advanced claims for future expenditures. As a result, no deduction or assignment was sought for collateral benefits for past expenses. If the <EM>Cadieux</EM> reasoning were to be applied, the Plaintiff would have been compelled to advance eight (8) years of past expenses for the sole purpose of protecting himself against a deduction of the collateral benefits against future claims.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>iii.</N><TI>An &ldquo;Apples to Apples&rdquo; Interpretation Makes Sense</TI>
<P>13. In <EM>Cadieux</EM>, the Plaintiff was fully compensated for his attendant care by theaccident benefits insurer and therefore did not seek payment of these expenses from the Defendants. Forcing the Plaintiff to unreasonably advance and litigate claims for attendant care for the sole purpose of avoiding an unfair assignment is illogical. There is a clear way to determine what benefits should be assigned which would satisfy the goal of avoiding double recovery, namely the &ldquo;apples to apples&rdquo; comparison developed in <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC></CASEREF>, and which has been consistently applied for over twenty (20) years.</P>
<P>14. In order for personal injury trials to function in an expeditious and reasonable manner, an interpretation of the assignment and deduction provisions of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> that best reflects the reality of litigation is preferred. This Honourable Court should not adopt an interpretation of the legislation that would mandate the plaintiff to litigate claims that are not being pursued.</P>
<P>15. Encouraging parties to act reasonably ought to be the goal.</P>
<P>16. There is no added expense or complexity to ensuring that the jury questions mirror the benefits for which an assignment or deduction is sought. Defendants are fully aware of the benefits which plaintiffs are receiving. Defendants are fully aware of their intention to seek an assignme nt. There is nothing unfair of requiring defendants to demonstrate that the benefits for which they seek an assignment or deduction are akin to what was actually awarded by the jury. If this means longer verdict sheets, this is a small price to pay to ensure that plaintiffs are fully compensated and double recovery avoided. To do otherwise, would be to favour expediency over justice.</P>
<P>17. Section 267.8 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> should be interpreted simply as a mechanism to permit the Court to deduct collateral benefits when the Plaintiff has received compensation for the <UNDER>same loss</UNDER>. The legislation provides a listing of the type of benefits which are subject to such an assignment or deduction. The legislation is rooted in the underlying comparison of the collater al benefit to the damages received. If the plaintiff never receives damages for that loss, no deduction or assignment should be granted.</P>
<P>18. The <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. South</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Fonseca v. Hansen</SOC></CASEREF> approach make logical sense to ensure that the deductions or assignment sought actually match the damages received on an apples to apples basis. Otherwise, defendants receive a windfall at the expense of accident victims. Not only would this not advance the goal of ensuring full compensation, it fails to advance the goal of p reventing <UNDER>double</UNDER> compensation. If a plaintiff has not been compensated at all for the loss from the defendant, double compensation is a non&mdash;issue.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>II.</N><TI>RETROSPECTIVE APPLICATION OF A LEGISLATIVE AMENDMENT ABSENT TRANSITION LANGUAGE</TI>
<P>19. While this issue is not a live issue in the <CASEREF><SOC>Carroll v. McEwen</SOC></CASEREF> appeal, the issue is being addressed by the panel and all parties have been granted the right to respond to the Factum of the Intervenor. This party would like to make the following points with respect to this issue:
<P1>(a) section 258.3(1.1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> is &ldquo;entirely silent&rdquo; as to whether it is to be applied retrospectively;</P1>
<P1>(b) the <CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long</SOC></CASEREF> decision looked at the legislative history and concluded the previous enactments specifically provided for a temporal limitation (limiting application of interest rate provisions from the date of the enactment forward). The Court concluded that failure to include such a limitation in s.258.3(1.1) supports the view that the legislature intended the change to be retrospective;</P1>
<P1>(c) with the greatest of respect, the analysis in <CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long</SOC></CASEREF> fails to consider that the previous legislation <EM>[Courts of Justice</EM> Act in 1989, in S.O. 1989, c. 67] contained provisions that were <UNDER>expressly</UNDER> retrospective in their application and some that were expressly prospective. See s. 8 (1) and (2) of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM> S.O. 1989, c. 67. As such, the legislative history indicates that the Legislature gave clear and express language when retrospective application was intended. No such language is found in s. 258.3(1.1);</P1>
<P1>(d) the recent decision of the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Tran v. Canada (Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness)</SOC></CASEREF> states that the presumption against retrospectively is worthy of protection as it &ldquo;engages the rule of law&rdquo; and &ldquo;bespeaks fairness.&rdquo; The following is an excerpt from that decision:</P1>
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>[48] T he presumption is a tool for discerning the intended temporal scope of legislation. In the absence of an indication that Parliament has considered retrospectivity and the potential for it to have unfair effects, the presumption must be that Parliament did not intend them:</EM></BOLD>
<QUOTE><P><EM>The absence of a general requirement of legislative prospectivity exists despite the fact that retrospective and retroactive legislation can overturn settled expectations and is sometimes perceived as unjust: see E. Edinger, &ldquo;Retrospectivity in Law&rdquo; (1995), 29 U.B.C. L. Rev. 5, at p. 13. Those who perceive it as such can perhaps take comfort in the rules of statutory interpretation that</EM> <UNDER><EM>require the legislature to indicate clearly any desired retroactive or retrospective effects. Such rules ensure that the legislature has turned its mind to such effects and &ldquo;determined that the benefits of retroactivity (or retrospectivity) outweigh the potential for disruption or unfairness&rdquo;</EM></UNDER><BOLD>:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Landgraf v. USI Film Products</SOC><YEAR>1994</YEAR><CITE>511 U.S. 244</CITE><PARANUM>at p. 268</PARANUM></CASEREF>. <EM>[Emphasis added.]</EM></P>
<P><BOLD><EM>(Imperial Tobacco, at para. 71, per Major J.)</EM></BOLD></P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD><EM>[49]</EM> <UNDER><EM>The presumption exists to ensure that laws will only apply retrospectively where Parliament has clearly signalled that it has weighed the benefits of retrospectivity with its potential unfairness. Otherwise, we presume that Parliament did not intend such effects</EM>.</UNDER> [emphasis added]</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Tran v. Canada (Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness)</SOC><CITE>[2017] 2 SCR 289</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2017 SCC 50 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>47-49</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>(e) there are often strong policy reasons which ought to form part of the contextual analysis. The Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Angus v. Sun Alliance Insurance Co.</SOC></CASEREF> explained why courts should exercise caution in implying a retrospective change pertaining to insurance:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>This case is a good illustration of the policy reasons why statutes should not be given retrospective operation in the absence of an intention to do so that is either expressed in, or is necessarily implied by the statute. Substantial rights of insurance companies are affected by the decision ... Insurance companies calculate their premiums according to known risk factors. When the rates for the contract in uestion here were calculated it was &ldquo;known&rdquo; that this particular risk&mdash;a suit in tort by Diane Angus against her husband&mdash;was precluded by s. 7. The insurance company relied upon that &ldquo;knowledge&rdquo; in setting its rates</EM>.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Angus v. Sun Alliance Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>[1988] 2 SCR 256</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>1988 CanLII 5</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <UNDER>at para 28.</UNDER></P1></P>
<P><BOLD><EM>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</EM></BOLD></P>
