<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>Overview</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The Respondents, Aviva Canada Inc. and Pilot Insurance Company (hereinafter, &ldquo;these Respondents&rdquo;), submit the within reply factum in response to the written submissions of the intervenor, Ontario Trial Lawyers Association (hereinafter, &ldquo;OTLA&rdquo;), with respect to the manner in which the deduction and trust / assignment mechanisms set out in the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> (hereinafter, &ldquo;the <EM>Act</EM>&rdquo;) are to be handled at trial.</P>
<P>2. Specifically, these Respondents address herein OTLA's submission that strict matching of collateral benefits to damages awarded at trial ensures plaintiffs receive full compensation without double recovery, while a relaxed matching approach will impede access to justice by forcing plaintiffs to litigate losses compensated, or to be compensated, by collateral sources.</P>
<P>3. When taken to its logical conclusion, the foregoing proposition does not survive a comprehensive analysis of the <EM>Act</EM>, or a consideration of the practical realities of a personal injury trial.</P>
<P>4. Rather, to continue to apply the strict matching principles set out in <CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. McNeely</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Bannon v. Mc.Neely</SOC><CITE>1998 CanLII 4486</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 1</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> would frustrate the court's ability to order a deduction or assignment generally, and would defeat the purpose of the <EM>Act</EM> to avoid double recovery. Indeed, the approach suggested by OTLA of a strict matching requirement was contemplated, and specifically rejected, by the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>35</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>.</P>
<P>5. As such, these Respondents maintain that the approach set out in <CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 717</CITE><PARANUM>48&ndash;55</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 7</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and <CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 9</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> is the proper approach in the current legislative scheme, as is requiring a plaintiff to claim at trial for all damages to which a plaintiff is entitled as a result of a motor vehicle accident.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II"><UNDER>To Require Strict Matching is Contrary to the Legislative Scheme</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><N>i.</N><TI>The <EM>Act</EM> Explicitly Rejects A Strict Matching Approach</TI>
<P>6. OTLA suggests that the <EM>Act</EM> codified the matching principles in <EM>Bannon</EM>, and therefore, s.267.8 does not change but, rather, codifies the existing law in Ontario. OTLA also notes that this Court has cited <EM>Bannon</EM> with approval on a number of occasions, even in the context of the present regime.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>OTLA's Factum, at para. 13</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. Indeed, it is acknowledged that this Court has, in the recent past, cited <EM>Bannon</EM> with respect to certain non-contentious principles.</P>
<P>8. For example, in <CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court upheld the trial judge's approach to deduct benefits received for medical/rehabilitation, attendant care and housekeeping (approximately $146,000) from the jury award of $105,000 for past and future care, medical/rehabilitation and housekeeping, resulting in a nil award.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 251</CITE></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In so doing, <EM>Bannon</EM> was cited with respect to the statutory goal of achieving full compensation and preventing double compensation.</P>
<P>9. Nevertheless, it is clear from the outcome in <EM>Basandra</EM> that this Court differs greatly from OTLA in its interpretation of the impact of applying the principles of <EM>Bannon</EM> to the present statutory regime.</P>
<P>10. Further, it is acknowledged that the manner in which the collateral benefit interface issue was approached in <EM>Bannon</EM> likely did inform the nature of the legislative changes in 1996 (hereinafter, &ldquo;the Bill 59/198 regime&rdquo;). It is for that reason that the present statutory scheme makes completely unnecessary the strict matching requirement outlined in <EM>Bannon</EM>.</P>
<P>11. Moreover, and according to the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Gurniak</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>35 &amp; 44</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, no further matching of the plaintiff's damage award to the collateral benefits is required than that which is mandated by statute.</P>
<P>12. In <EM>Gurniak</EM>, the Court considered two different matching concepts&mdash;the first being the match between the Qu&ea;bec and British Columbia benefit plans permitting a deduction. Section 25(1) of the <EM>Insurance (Motor Vehicle) Act</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>s.25 of the <EM>Insurance (Motor Vehicle) Act</EM>, RSBC 1996, C.231, Aviva/Pilot Reply Factum, Schedule B, pg. 18</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> required the Qu&ea;bec benefit plan to be similar to the benefit plan in BC. It was the similarity between those plans that made the benefits <EM>prima facie</EM> capable of being deducted.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>30&ndash;33</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Neither <EM>Bannon</EM>, nor the within appeals, deal with this first level of matching.</P>
<P>13. In <EM>Gurniak</EM>, the plaintiffs further argued that pursuant to <CASEREF><SOC>Jang v. Jang</SOC></CASEREF>, there is a required second level of matching, in particular, a match between the plaintiff's damage award and the benefit paid. This is the nature of the matching endorsed in <EM>Bannon</EM> and at issue in the within appeals.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>43</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>14. The Supreme Court in <EM>Gurniak</EM> specifically rejected this second level of matching. Rather, the Court held that once it is determined that the plan is the type of plan that can be deducted, the damages are to be reduced by the benefits paid pursuant to that plan, in accordance with s.25(1) of the BC <EM>Insurance (Motor Vehicle) Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>7</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In short, in <EM>Gurniak</EM>, the Supreme Court rejected the concept of judicial matching that was urged upon them by plaintiffs' counsel.</P>
<P>15. Indeed, in British Columbia, <EM>Gurniak</EM> has been consistently cited to stand for the proposition that it is &ldquo;no longer a requirement that there be a match between the heads of damage for a tort award and specific heads of damages under the benefit recovery scheme&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>For example, most recently in <CASEREF><SOC>Dennstedt v. Lepine</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 220</CITE><PARANUM>82</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Book of Authorities Re: Response to OTLA, Tab 3 and also in <CASEREF><SOC>Sovani v. Jin</SOC><CITE>2005 BCSC 1285</CITE><PARANUM>66&ndash;76</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Book of Authorities Re: Response to OTLA, Tab 1 and <CASEREF><SOC>Manitoba Public Insurance v. Dybhaun</SOC><CITE>2016 BCSC 27</CITE><PARANUM>46-47</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Book of Authorities Re: Response to OTLA, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. In Ontario, a plain reading of the <EM>Act</EM> in its current form commands a similar result.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>ii.</N><TI>A Strict Matching Approach Will Facilitate Double Recovery</TI>
<P>17. Contrary to OTLA's submission, a strict matching approach will not ensure plaintiffs receive full compensation <BOLD>without double recovery</BOLD>. Rather, the extent of the strict matching OTLA suggests in theory would be very difficult to achieve in practice, and, as such, overcompensation would become the norm rather than the exception.</P>
<P>18. As stated in <EM>El-Khodr</EM>, this Court should not be prevented from making the appropriate deduction or assignment because of the manner in which the claim for special damages is presented to the jury.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>El-Khodr v. Lackie</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 716 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 9 at paras. 83&ndash;86</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>19. This outcome could ensue, for example, if certain time periods or certain losses are not presented to the jury, or where claims covered by accident benefits are lumped together with those which are not. Either approach would arguably make strict qualitative and temporal matching nearly impossible.</P>
<P>20. For example, consider the case of a plaintiff who was a high school student working at the time of the accident and who received income replacement benefits from a collateral carrier post-accident. That plaintiff could present the jury with a theory that but for the accident, s/he would have continued to university and then entered a workforce where s/he could have earned more money. That way, the plaintiff's income loss claim would necessarily start later on a higher annual loss basis.</P>
<P>21. As such, the time period of the loss being advanced would not match the time period of the collateral benefit. Requiring strict temporal matching would infuse significant uncertainty as to whether the income replacement benefits received by that plaintiff should be deducted in this circumstance.</P>
<P>22. Moreover, in terms of income loss, the SABS scheme bases entitlement and quantum on the preloss period (whether the plaintiff was working prior to the accident and the amount he or she was earning), while the tort scheme bases entitlement and quantum on the post-accident period using the &ldquo;but-for&rdquo; or &ldquo;real and substantial possibility&rdquo; tests. This key difference in compensation schemes (one looking back&mdash;SABS; one looking forward&mdash;tort) makes the level of strict temporal matching called for by OTLA more unlikely to be achieved in many cases. Double recovery would inevitably become much more commonplace.</P>
<P>23. The foregoing example highlights the inherent difficulties in reconciling two different systems of compensation, tort and SABS, for automobile-related personal injuries, and the inherent difficulties in requiring a strict level of matching as between them.</P>
<P>24. It is submitted that the issues associated with reconciling these two different schemes of compensation for injured plaintiffs was considered by the Legislature and answered by the broad matching &ldquo;silos&rdquo; set out in statute (income loss; health care; and other pecuniary losses). No further sub-division, either temporal or qualitative, is required or desirable.</P>
<P>25. Moreover, any residual concern regarding the matching of the jury award to a collateral benefit, particularly with respect to future collateral benefits, does not survive a hard look.</P>
<P>26. As an example, if the jury award for future care costs of $700,000 includes an item not covered by SABs (for example, government funded medication) and yet an assignment is granted for the full $700,000 which includes that amount, the net effect will simply be that if the plaintiff incurs the cost of medication post-trial and then submits it to the SABs carrier, that amount will simply not be reimbursed because the SABs carrier is not the first loss payor. The plaintiff will have already been compensated for that amount by the jury award. The tortfeasor will not recover that amount pursuant to the assignment or otherwise.</P>
<P>27. Through the assignment mechanism, the risk of future non-payment by the collateral carrier is borne by the tortfeasor, and not the plaintiff.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III"><UNDER>The Damages Subject to Deduction Must Be All Damages (Per Silo) To Which A Plaintiff Is Entitled</UNDER></TI>
<P>28. OTLA suggests that a plaintiff should be permitted to advance only net losses at trial, and that the deductions (if any) must match only the claims pursued.</P>
<P>29. This position is not sustainable in light of the plain language of the <EM>Act</EM>.</P>
<P>30. The <EM>Act</EM> mandates that the damages which are subject to deduction are the global damages for past and future losses and are to be reduced by all benefits received or available (per silo).</P>
<P>31. For example, s.267.8(4) of the <EM>Act</EM> expressly requires that the health care damages to which a plaintiff is entitled for expenses that have been incurred (past), or will be incurred (future), are to be reduced by the SABS received or available for health care.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>s.267.8(1), (4) &amp; (6) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, 1990, c. I.8, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Responding Factum, Schedule B, pg. 13</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The global (past and future) damages are reduced by the SABS received or available (per silo).</P>
<P>32. Thereafter, if the deduction would more than offset the past losses, it will, by necessity, offset some measure of the future losses.</P>
<P>33. Section 267.8(1) of the <EM>Act</EM>, dealing with damages to which a plaintiff is entitled for income loss and loss of earning capacity, has been similarly interpreted by this Court on a number of occasions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Cummings (Litigation Guardian of) v. Douglas</SOC><CITE>2007 ONCA 615</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 4; <CASEREF><SOC>Basandra v. Sforza</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 251</CITE></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 8; <CASEREF><SOC>Cobb v. Long Estate</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 717</CITE><PARANUM>48&ndash;55</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 7</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This Court has consistently held that the deductions are to be made from the global damage award (past and future).</P>
<P>34. There is no qualifying language in the <EM>Act</EM> which requires that the damages subject to deduction to be only the damages pursued by the plaintiff.</P>
<P>35. To the contrary, s.267.8 (1), (4) and (6) of the <EM>Act</EM> stipulate that &ldquo;the damages to which a plaintiff is entitled...shall be reduced by...all payments in respect of the incident&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>s.267.8(1), (4) &amp; (6) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, 1990, c. I.8, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Responding Factum, Schedule B, pg. 13</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Accordingly, the <EM>Act</EM> does not state that the damages pursued by the plaintiff are the net damages, but rather, the damages to which a plaintiff is &ldquo;entitled&rdquo;.</P>
<P>36. Under the OMPP / <EM>Bannon</EM> regime, the nature of the damages against which the deductions were to be made was worded differently.</P>
<P>37. In <EM>Bannon</EM>, s.267.1 of the <EM>Act</EM> read &ldquo;the damages awarded to a person shall be reduced by...&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>s.267.1 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, 1990, c. I.8, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Responding Factum, Schedule B, pg. 13</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>38. The now operative s.267.8 refers to &ldquo;the damages to which a plaintiff is entitled&rdquo;, not to &ldquo;the damages awarded&rdquo;.</P>
<P>39. In <CASEREF><SOC>Madill v Chu</SOC></CASEREF>, &ldquo;entitled&rdquo; was given its ordinary meaning where the nature of a collateral benefit entitlement was in issue.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Madill v. Chu</SOC><CITE>[1977] 2 SCC 400</CITE><PAGENUM>at pgs. 409-410</PAGENUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It was not interpreted to mean pursued by the plaintiff and accepted, and hence, payable. In <EM>Madill</EM>, the plaintiff chose not to apply for collateral benefits to which he was otherwise &ldquo;entitled&rdquo;, and the Supreme Court held they should be deducted nevertheless.</P>
<P>40. The use of the word &ldquo;entitled&rdquo; in s.267.8 of the current regime should be similarly interpreted to mean entitlement, at law, to all damages arising from the accident, and not just the specific damages sought by a plaintiff and awarded by a jury.</P>
<BLOCK3><N>i.</N><TI>The Supreme Court Has Considered and Rejected the &ldquo;Net Claims&rdquo; Approach</TI>
<P>41. The Supreme Court of Canada considered the very issue of a plaintiff presenting only &ldquo;net claims&rdquo; in <EM>Gurniak</EM> and rejected it, instead endorsing an approach consistent with this Court's decisions in <EM>Cobb</EM> and <EM>El-Khodr</EM>.</P>
<P>42. At paragraph 37, the Supreme Court quotes <CASEREF><SOC>Jang v. Jang</SOC></CASEREF> where the British Columbia Court of Appeal stated &ldquo;I do not think that the claim there referred to is the whole claim rather it is a claim to a particular heading of loss matched by a particular heading of benefits.&rdquo;</P>
<P>43. The Supreme Court went on to overrule <EM>Jang</EM> and therefore rejected that very sentiment. The claim to be advanced by a plaintiff is the whole claim, and not just some chosen portion of the claim, against which the like benefits may then be deducted.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>44. In <EM>Gurniak</EM>, the Court appreciated that with the rejection of judicial matching, there may be some unfairness, in rare cases, where the object of preventing double recovery would not be realized. The Court found that this potential unfairness could be overcome by a plaintiff advancing all claims. Any residual unfairness should be dealt with by legislative reform.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>45. In <EM>Gurniak</EM>, the Supreme Court recognized that if a plaintiff only advances part of his or her loss (punitive damages), s/he risks having the award for punitive damages reduced by a completely unrelated compensatory loss benefit. There would be no matching: a non-compensatory damage award (punitive) reduced by a compensatory loss benefit (<EM>i.e.</EM>: income- replacement benefits). The Court indicated the answer is for plaintiffs to advance all of their losses (compensatory and non-compensatory) so that when all benefits received as a result of the accident are deducted, there is no unfairness visited upon the plaintiff.</P>
<P>46. In any event, the Court stated that this will typically be more of a theoretical concern than a real one, as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Parties will, as a matter of course, advance tort claims for the <UNDER>full</UNDER> extent of the benefits to which they believe they are legally entitled (i.e., full compensatory and punitive damages). <BOLD>It would be an anomalous case indeed where the tort award consisted solely of heads of damage that did not have some type of a counterpart in the benefits determined to be similar under s. 25(1).</BOLD> To the limited extent that this may occur, this problem is more appropriately addressed through legislative reform. Importing a &ldquo;matching&rdquo; requirement into s. 25(2), beyond the matching required in the analysis of similarity, would risk undermining the legislature's intent to prevent double recovery in a manner that is simple, expedient and, on the whole, effective. [Emphasis added]<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>47. In other words, the Supreme Court anticipated that a plaintiff, in the above example, would seek both compensatory damages and punitive damages, thereby permitting a deduction against the compensatory damages, leaving only the punitive damages as the net award.</P>
<P>48. In short, the expectation of the Supreme Court of Canada is that a plaintiff should advance at trial a claim for all damages to which a plaintiff is entitled as a result of a motor vehicle accident.</P>
<P>49. Indeed, this approach has been identified by the British Columbia Court of Appeal as the &ldquo;preferable&rdquo; approach in the right circumstances.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gasior v. Bayes</SOC><CITE>2010 BCCA 285</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OTLA Book of Authorities, Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>50. The approach endorsed by the majority view in <EM>Gurniak</EM> is necessary to achieve the objectives of the <EM>Act</EM> in Ontario, which is that a plaintiff should advance at trial all damages to which a plaintiff is entitled, and from that, the court can deduct / assign all of the benefits received or to be received (matched only by the legislated &ldquo;<EM>silos</EM>&rdquo;) as a result of the accident.</P>
<P>51. <EM>Gurniak</EM> advises that to avoid any potential unfairness associated with a collateral benefit interface scheme without judicial matching, plaintiffs should advance a claim for the full extent of their losses flowing from an accident.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>52. In Ontario, there has arguably been some ambiguity and inconsistency in that regard, such that a plaintiff who failed to properly advance all losses may be met with an unexpected deduction. However, going forward, if this Court accepts the submissions of these Respondents (and maintains the approach articulated in <EM>Cobb</EM> and <EM>El-Khodr</EM>), future litigants will understand the manner in which the issue is to be handled.</P>
<P>53. As such, plaintiffs will understand that it is not appropriate to advance only net claims, or only those losses for which they wish to seek compensation. Plaintiffs should, and presumably will, advance at trial a claim for all damages to which a plaintiff believes they are legally entitled as losses flowing from the accident.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>ii.</N><TI>OTLA's Approach Would Undermine the Order of Operations Dictated by Statute</TI>
<P>56. OTLA's approach to permit a plaintiff to unilaterally decide to advance &ldquo;net claims&rdquo; would render meaningless the split and deduct order of operations mechanism in s.267.8(8) of the <EM>Act</EM>. This would be inherently unfair to defendants when there is a liability split.</P>
<P>5 7. The order of operations with respect to a liability split and the deduction of collateral benefits was determined by this Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Cummings v. Douglas</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Cummings (Litigation Guardian of) v. Douglas</SOC><CITE>2007 ONCA 615</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 4</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, and codified in Bill 59. Both the common law and s.267.8(8) of the <EM>Act</EM> stipulate that collateral benefits received or available are deducted <BOLD>after the split in liability</BOLD>:
<QUOTE><P>The reductions required by subsection (1) (4) and (6) shall be made after any apportionment of damages required by section 3 of the Negligence Act.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>s.267.8(1), (4) &amp; (6) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, 1990, c. I.8, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Responding Factum, Schedule B, pg. 16</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>58. As an example, consider a case where a plaintiff has a total past loss of income of $400,000 and received $100,000 in income replacement benefits prior to trial. If the plaintiff presents and proves a past income loss claim of $300,000 (without claiming for the time period already compensated for by his or her collateral carrier in the amount of $100,000) and is found 75% contributorily negligent, his or her tort award would be $75,000 ($300,000 x .25).</P>
<P>59. However, if the plaintiff properly advanced his or her full past income loss claim of $400,000 and was found 75% contributorily negligent, his or her tort award would be $100,000 minus the $100,000 received in income replacement benefits, for a net award of nil.</P>
<P>60. OTLA's approach of presenting net claims is inconsistent with the order of operations required by the <EM>Act</EM>. If net claims are presented, then collateral benefits are, by definition, deducted by counsel prior to the trial. As a result, any split in liability as determined by the court will take place <EM>after</EM> the deduction of collateral benefits. The effect is to reverse the order of operations mandated by the <EM>Act</EM>.</P>
<P>61. As demonstrated above, the impact of the proper order of operations (split, then deduct) can be significant. Indeed, it could well determine success, or not, at trial, as well a party's entitlement to costs.</P>
<P>62. The need to give effect to the intention of the legislature supports the approach urged by these Respondents, and indeed the approach most consistent with <EM>Gurniak, Cobb</EM> and <EM>El-Khodr</EM>.</P>
<P>63. That is, a plaintiff should advance at trial all damages to which a plaintiff is entitled, so that the trial judge can deduct / assign any collateral benefits received or to be received within the &ldquo;silos&rdquo; mandated by the <EM>Act</EM>.</P>
<P>64. Ultimately, this approach preserves the integrity of the <EM>Act</EM> and avoids any potential mischief, of the kind posited by the Supreme Court in <EM>Madill</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>In <EM>Madill</EM>, the Supreme Court of Canada noted that the consequences of the relevant section could not be avoided by simply not pursuing the benefit&mdash;<CASEREF><SOC>Madill v. Chu</SOC><CITE>[1977] 2 SCC 400</CITE><PAGENUM>at pgs. 409-410</PAGENUM></CASEREF>, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Supplementary Book of Authorities, Tab 8. It is noteworthy that in <EM>Carroll</EM>, the plaintiffs did, in fact, avoid the consequences of the s.267.8(8) split and deduct provision in the <EM>Act</EM> given the liability split found by the jury. The resulting impact was not insignificant.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, which would undermine the object of the legislation.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>iii.</N><TI>Trials Will Not Be Unnecessarily Lengthened</TI>
<P>68. OTLA submits that requiring plaintiffs to prove compensated losses will result in trial inefficiency and will impact access to justice. There appears to be no evidentiary support provided for this assertion.</P>
<P>69. The &ldquo;access to justice&rdquo; issue appears to be predicated on the notion that the approach OTLA recommends would be more efficient. This is not borne out when the broader and practical realities of a personal injury trial are considered.</P>
<P>70. As an example, at the tort trial, the <EM>Carroll</EM> Plaintiffs sought to recover only non-pecuniary general damages and damages for future costs of care. In the presentation of those claims, the Plaintiffs went through the process of establishing the pattern of consumption as it related to past losses, as part of proving and demonstrating their future loss. This approach is not atypical.</P>
<P>71. Most plaintiffs address thoroughly at trial their past healthcare treatment, whether they are seeking recovery for those expenses or not. As such, there is arguably minimal incremental cost, time or complexity in requiring plaintiffs to sue for all their losses (per category).</P>
<P>72. In any event, there are many ways to streamline the trial process in this regard in a cooperative fashion, once established. This might include counsel simply agreeing to a chart or schedule that sets out the expenses incurred to the date of trial.</P>
<P>73. Further, and in particular, OTLA's suggestion that litigants should be encouraged to only advance claims net of <EM>future</EM> collateral benefits is impractical.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>OTLA's Factum, para. 37</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>74. For example, if the <EM>Carroll</EM> Plaintiffs were to have presented their case as OTLA suggests, the trial would likely have been with respect to non-pecuniary general damages only. This would be a rare case indeed, and would almost certainly give rise to disputes as to which benefits will be available in the future. These are the very disputes which existed in the OMPP regime.</P>
<P>75. Therefore, OTLA's approach infuses a level of impracticality and uncertainty into the process. Rather than shortening trials, there could be lengthy and ongoing disputes about whether there is, or is not, a future collateral benefit &ldquo;entitlement&rdquo;. That is exactly the problem that the assignment mechanism in s.267.8(12) of the <EM>Act</EM> was meant to overcome.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>s.267.8(12) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, 1990, c. I.8, Aviva/Pilot Supplementary Responding Factum, Schedule B, pg. 17</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>76. Moreover, the strict matching approach espoused by OTLA would necessitate much longer and more detailed jury questions, and otherwise add to the length and complexity of the trial process.</P>
<P>77. In <EM>Gurniak</EM>, the Supreme Court has already held that importing a judicial matching requirement would risk making at least certain aspects of the trial more complex, less expedient and, on the whole, less effective. Conversely, the approach mandated by <EM>Gurniak</EM> (no greater matching than that required by statute), and urged by these Respondents, &ldquo;has the benefit of simplicity and ease of application&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gurniak v. Nordquist</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 59</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV"><UNDER>Conclusion</UNDER></TI>
<P>78. These Respondents submit that no more than the broad matching categories or &ldquo;silos&rdquo; in the <EM>Act</EM> is required for the deduction or assignment of collateral benefits.</P>
<P>79. Further, the intention of the legislature (for example, s.267.8(8)&mdash;split and deduct) should not be frustrated by simply presenting the tort claim net of collateral benefits.</P>
<P>80. The approach urged by these Respondents, which is consistent with the legislation, the approach of the Supreme Court of Canada <EM>in Gurniak</EM>, and this Court in <EM>Cobb</EM> and <EM>El-Khodr</EM>, ensures a fair and balanced application of the tort and collateral benefits interface scheme.</P>
<P>81. A plaintiff should advance at trial all damages to which a plaintiff is entitled, so that the trial judge can deduct / assign the collateral benefits within the &ldquo;silos&rdquo; mandated by the <EM>Act</EM>. No strict temporal or qualitative matching is required by statute, nor is it necessary or desirable. Indeed, as per <EM>Gurniak</EM>, it is expected that plaintiffs will advance all claims in any event. Indeed, the Supreme Court acknowledged that it would be a rare case where a plaintiff would not do so.</P>
<P>82. If this Court accepts the submissions of these Respondents, plaintiffs will on a going forward basis understand that they should advance at trial all damages to which the plaintiff is entitled as losses flowing from a motor vehicle accident. This approach should serve to eliminate any unexpected deductions and hence, any potential unfairness.</P>
<P>83. There is no evidence before this Court that this approach will actually serve to lengthen trials in any material fashion. The practical realities of a personal injury trial, and the implications of the disputes which would arise from OTLA's proposed approach, defeat the access to justice arguments presented.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED, this 13<SUP>th</SUP> day of April, 2018</P>
